Why disciple-making is important  Scriptural support for disciple-making  How disciple-making will be woven into everything at the new church  A plan for making disciple-makers in their community  A simple pathway for people to become disciple-makers  Tools and training resources to be used', 'Review the planter''s Disciple-Making Strategy document.  Provide feedback to the planter.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Disciple-Making Strategy.', 'template:  2019-10-14 new task --pb  2019-12-16 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 28& to 22 & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb ', 3, 'todo', 42, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('462d00be-c6b1-5d56-a3dc-38a83046320f', '6b7c39eb-4653-5796-8d7d-d30a90c5d6ec', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Write down your Personal Evangelism Plan', 'Write out a plan for how you as the lead planter will lead by example and reach people who are far from God.', 'After assessing you passion for reaching people far from God, develop a personal plan of evangelism to help deepen your passion and practice.  To some, evangelism comes naturally. Their heart aches for those who don''t know God yet. For the rest of us, we have to be intentional about making connections with people who are far from God. Too often pastors preach about evangelism, but never actually engage in evangelism themselves. You  have to  lead the way in reaching out to people far from God if the church is to have an evangelistic DNA.  A strategy is important, but it''s just theory. A  plan  requires action items with dates, doers and dollars attached. It''s time to get really practical with evangelism.  Part of any personal evangelism plan should be practical ways to be on mission in everyday life. For example, rather than spending time at home working, frequent the same coffee shop or restaurant to do work. You will get to know the employees and regulars. When you gas up, rather than paying at the pump, go inside to the counter. Avoid drive-throughs. Take the time to go inside and interact with people. Go the grocery store at the same time each week and go to the same cashier. This type of intentional living will help you build relationships.  A regular diet of prayer for the lost is also important. Have a list of names to pray for, and pray for a burden for lost people.  Also spend time where people far from God spend time. For example, join the gym and go daily at the same time in order to connect with the same people.', 'Make a list of all the stores and businesses you frequent on a regular basis. Determine how you can be more intentional in how you visit each of those places.  Create a prayer list of people you''re praying for.  Pray for more passion for the lost.  Determine where you can spend time that will put you in an environment to connect with the lost.  Write those things down and set yourself a monthly reminder to revisit the plan and evaluate how you''re doing.  This action is complete when you have written out a Personal Evangelism Plan.', 'template: standard  2017-06-02 content validated --pb  2019-11-25 content updated --pb ', 4, 'todo', 50, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('33c1f399-8958-571f-8903-e7c460aa9dd0', '6b7c39eb-4653-5796-8d7d-d30a90c5d6ec', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Embed ongoing disciple-making training', 'Continually promote disciple-making and empower your people to talk to others about Jesus.', 'Now is the time to embed disciple-making and evangelism deep in the DNA of the new congregation. Making disciples is the mission that Jesus gave us. But an overwhelming number of North American Christians have never been discipled, so they are not making disciples themselves.  But that doesn''t mean creating a system to give them more information . That approach has gotten us to where we are.  The easy part is making disciple-makers of new believers. They''ll get it faster and won''t have the baggage the rest of us have to undo.  The more challenging part is making disciple-makers of churched people. They don''t need to sit through another chemistry class; they need time in the lab to practice.  Regardless, your training needs to be heavy on  practice  and light on information. It has to include some version of, "I''m training you so that you can train the next disciple. We''re going to practice it right now so you''ll be ready."  Evangelism is part of making disciples. Provide training on how to do evangelism naturally through everyday relationships. This will equip and empower your people to reach their friends, family, neighbors and co-workers.  The expectation from the beginning should be that all Christians figure out some way to make disciples. Your Disciple-Making Strategy needs to be an ongoing element of your church culture for the life of your congregation.', 'Determine how you''ll get people practicing disciple-making and evangelism in practical ways.  As appropriate, pick a few simple tools.  Put your strategies into motion.  This action is complete when your first trainee begins training someone else.', 'template: standard  2017-12-29 content & links updated --pb  2018-04-20 moved to Launch Team milestone --pb  2019-02-13 additional resources subsection added --pb  2019-04-29 content updated --pb  2020-01-13 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 110& to 120& & Duration from 7 to 30& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 50, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('41f222e9-24aa-5f9f-8f19-c0e104d120fb', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a Vision Frame & beliefs handout', 'Create a summary handout or presentation to make sure Launch Team members understand the vision, values and beliefs of the new church.', 'The Launch Team members have to become the DNA carriers of the new church. They must be on board with the plans that God has given you for what type of church this will be.  For brand-new believers, this will be a helpful reference point for what church is about. For transfer believers, there may be some baggage they''ll have to ditch to align themselves with the vision. Some believers may quit your Launch Team because it''s just too different or not a good match. Now is the time to find that out.  At this point, you''ve hammered out your entire  Vision Frame . Now put it in a simple form that can be used with the Launch Team and, eventually, church members.  Hesitate to design this handout yourself, even if you have design skills. You should be spending that time with people instead of behind a computer screen. That said, it can be designed simply for printing at home or designed professionally for high-quality printing. Work with the designer to be sure they include the right things and represent the church''s brand well.', 'Review the  Vision Frame .  Enlist a graphic designer and direct them what to include in the summary handout.  Print them in house or send them out for professional printing.  This action is complete when you have the handout printed and in hand.', 'template: standard  2017-06-09 updated ''plan'' to ''strategy'' --pb  2017-06-14 content validated, audience changed to coach --pb&  2019-12-23 content updated --pb ', 0, 'todo', 66, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b25e3ae9-4ab3-5c3c-b27e-39c9d226a957', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Recruit First 10 People to the Launch Team', 'Grow the Launch Team to the initial milestone of 10 adults so that the team dynamic begins to form and momentum is developed.', 'Getting the first few people for a Launch Team is often the hardest part. Be intentional about how and where people will be approached about being recruited to the Launch Team. That will help ensure the right people are included.  As the planter begins networking in the community, meeting neighbors, and conducting community events, he should identify and recruit Launch Team members.  Initially, the Launch Team meets regularly as a small group. You invest significant time with the Launch Team members building relationships, communicating vision, and creating momentum. Often the first 10 people are:  Old Friends  Family  Friends of friends or family who live in the area  Christians living in the area who are commuting a considerable distance to attend a church like the one you are starting. Your church now gives them an option closer to home  People you befriend and build relationships with after moving to the new area. These are often some of your best stories of life change  Disgruntled Christians who hop from church to church looking for just the right place to satisfy their needs or agenda  Cast a wide net to everyone you know across the country. Ask them to identify people they know who live in your target area. Pray specifically for God to identify an initial core of people to join the team. Look in unexpected places. Assume that every interaction you have with someone you don''t know is the start of a new relationship with someone who needs to join your Launch Team. See each person as a potential member.  If only one out of ten people you ask to consider joining does, then you have to talk with over 100 people to recruit your first ten. Expect rejection. Be prepared for it. Circle back on people in the future. Don''t let one "no" be the final interaction.  Just as new converts are often the greatest evangelists, new Launch Team members have the potential to be the best recruiters of new Launch Team members. Challenge each new Launch Team member to bring at least one additional person along on the ride. Continually challenge your team to be praying for new people. Ask each of your team members to share the names of 3 people they are praying for and building relationships with.', 'Identify the people to specifically ask to be a part of the team.  Present the vision and expectations to the individuals. Be bold in approaching and asking people to join.  Encourage them to pray about their role.  Obtain a commitment from the interested people.  Ask each committed member to identify 3 additional people as potential prospects.  This action is complete when the planter had identified and recruited the first 10 members.', 'template: standard  2017-06-14 content validated --pb  2017-05-04 content tweaked --pb  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 120& to 151& & Duration from 14& to 60& --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 89, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('64dfb20b-1e7e-508d-87e4-e473aa3e2a42', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Expand Launch Team to 25 people', 'Grow the Launch Team to 25 adults so that momentum and excitement continue to grow.', 'Without at least 50 adults on your Launch Team, you will struggle with volunteerism, developing leaders, and financial sustainability after launch. Expanding the Launch Team to at least 25 people is an important milestone in getting to 50.  Expanding a Launch Team might seem overwhelming. The pressure can be frightening. Don''t fret. Take things one day at a time. Nearly every great team in history started small and grew healthily.  Consider the following factors when you put a plan together for expanding the Launch Team:  Pray  It is God''s church and we are called to cooperate. We are joining him in what he has planned. If we believe it is his church then we must trust he will provide the people. We have to figure out what it means to cooperate. That starts with prayer  Communicate Vision  People are drawn to a clear and compelling vision. You must be able to communicate the vision with passion and you must teach your entire team to do the same. Your current team members need to be disciples of the church vision  Build Relationships  People are skeptical of religion and church. However, they are open to spiritual things. Relationships break down barriers to start conversations. Conversations are the starting point to building trust. Trust leads to cooperation. You can''t spend enough time building relationships. One or two key relationships almost always open the door to many other relationships. Look for these key relationships. Often they are found in unexpected places  Cast a Wide Net  The more people you and your Launch Team pray for, the more people who will join your team. It''s that simple. More conversations. More people  Be Persistent  Some people need to be asked multiple times before they respond. Don''t pester people but also don''t give up after one "no"  Challenge Your Team  Your current Launch Team members are your best assets for growing the team. The DNA / culture you establish with them carries forward to future years. If the team is not praying for and inviting friends, neighbors and co-workers, you will have a problem with evangelism later. Challenge your team regularly to pray for and to invite their friends. Talk about the people you are praying to reach at every single gathering of the Launch Team. Spend time having each person tell about the specific people they are praying for.  It cannot be stated strongly enough how important the investment of time in people will prove to be later in the launch process. Planters who don''t spend enough time building relationships with those they hope to reach regret it later.  Don''t get discouraged. Growing the team from 10 to 25 is often the harder than growing from 1 to 10 (previous PlanterPlan Action) or from 25 to 50 (next PlanterPlan Action):  in growing from 1 to 10, you leverage your existing relationships  from 10 to 25 you are reliant on new relationships  from 25 to 50 you leverage the existing Launch Team to reach their networks', 'Identify people to pray for and to build relationships with. Challenge your team to do the same. Be specific.  Present your vision to as many people as possible. Cast a wide net. Be bold in approaching and asking people to join.  Encourage them to pray about their role.  Obtain a commitment from the interested people.  Ask each committed member to identify 3 additional people as potential prospects.  This action is complete once you have recruited 25 Launch Team members.', 'template: standard  2017-06-14 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 150& to 212& & Duration from 60& to 90 --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 150, 60, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('8ab74b9f-6114-5189-9118-a25e1562ce62', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Expand Launch Team to 40 people', 'Grow the Launch Team to 40 adults so that critical mass is achieved and basic ministry roles for the Opening Day of worship gatherings can be filled.', 'Expanding the Launch Team to at least 40 people is a significant step to ensuring a large opening day launch. With 40 committed servants, most new churches will be able to live out their vision for opening day.  Expanding a Launch Team might seem overwhelming for some planters. The pressure can be frightening. Don''t fret. Take things one day at a time. Nearly every great team in history started small and grew healthily.  Consider the following factors when you put a plan together for expanding the Launch Team:  Prayer  It is God''s church and we are called to cooperate. We are joining him in what he has planned. If we believe it is his church then we must trust he will provide the people. We have to figure out what it means to cooperate. That starts with prayer  Communicating Vision  People are drawn to a clear and compelling vision. You must be able to communicate the vision with passion and you must teach your entire team to do the same. Your current team members need to be disciples of the church vision  Relationships  People are skeptical of religion and church. However, they are open to spiritual things. Relationships break down barriers to start conversations. Conversations are the starting point to building trust. Trust leads to cooperation. You can''t spend enough time building relationships. One or two key relationships almost always open the door to many other relationships. Look for these key relationships. Often they are found in unexpected places  Casting a Wide Net  The more people you and your Launch Team pray for, the more people who will join your team. It''s that simple. More conversations. More people  Persistence  Some people need to be asked multiple times before they respond. Don''t pester people but also don''t give up after one "no"  Challenge Your Team  Your current Launch Team members are your best assets for growing the team. The DNA / culture you establish with them carries forward to future years. If the team is not praying for and inviting friends, neighbors and co-workers, you will have a problem with evangelism later. Challenge your team regularly to pray for and to invite their friends. Talk about the people you are praying to reach at every single gathering of the Launch Team. Spend time having each person tell about the specific people they are praying for.  It cannot be stated strongly enough how important the investment of time in people will prove to be later in the launch process. Many planters do not spend enough time building relationships with those they hope to reach.', 'Identify people to pray for and to build relationships with. Challenge your team to do the same. Be specific.  Present your vision to as many people as possible. Cast a wide net. Be bold in approaching and asking people to join.  Encourage them to pray about their role.  Obtain a commitment from the interested people.  Ask each committed member to identify 3 additional people as potential prospects.  This action is complete once the planter has recruited 40 launch team members.', 'template: standard  2017-06-14 content validated --pb  2020-01-13 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 120& to 122& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 211, 91, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('4f4706b6-ce9c-5556-b4b3-140d4ac6f0de', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Talk to your Launch Team about money', 'Conduct a financial stewardship lesson or series well before Launch to make generosity and giving part of the new church''s DNA.', 'The early financial health of the church will depend a lot on your willingness to talk with the Launch Team about money as a matter of being a disciple.  The Launch Team should participate in the financial life of the new church. Talking about generosity and taking up offerings needs to happen at some point before Launch. But when?  Planning and conducting financial stewardship training before Launch is one way to help the team understand the cost of what they are undertaking. And it may even be a good outreach event to serve people in your community who are struggling financially.  Consider these financial training resources:  <a href="https://www.ramseysolutions.com/ramseyplus/organization">Financial Peace University</a>  <a href="https://goodsensemovement.org/">Good Sense</a>  <a href="https://www.crown.org/">Crown Financial Ministry</a>  If not an entire series, plan how to weave talking about generosity & sacrifice into your Launch Team meetings.', 'Discern the attitude of your Launch Team about giving.  Select an appropriate financial training resource.  Put the training date on the calendar.  Conduct the training.  This action is complete when you have taught the/first financial stewardship lesson to the Launch Team.', 'template: standard  2017-12-29 content & links updated --pb  2018-04-20 moved to Preaching milestone --pb&  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 110& to 180& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 119, 29, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a0761217-da77-594f-8b95-e7a841c6b8cb', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Schedule Preview Services', 'Get at least 4 preview services on the calendar ahead of Launch Sunday.', 'Preview services benefit the new church in many ways:  Practice  There are lots of details to take care of to pull off a worship gathering, particularly when you are mobile. Preview services give you a chance to get the kinks out.  Outreach  Conducting preview services gives your launch team an excuse to invite friends, family and co-workers. It''s a good opportunity to expand the launch team and build momentum toward launch.  Vision  Preview services give you an environment to cast vision to the entire launch team and helps paint the picture for what worship gatherings will be like.  The 2007 survey of over 2,200 church plants in  <a href="https://a.co/3xHybAk">Planting Fast-Growing Churches</a>  by Stephen Gray demonstrates a  significant  difference in the post-launch health and growth of churches that conduct multiple preview services:  Of churches that conducted 3 preview services, 23% were fast-growing and 53% were struggling (p.115)  Of churches that conducted 4 preview services, 25% were fast-growing but only 7% were struggling (p.115)  Plan your preview services early - they impact the timing of other tasks in the launch plan:  when to sign a facility contract  when to order equipment  when to execute your marketing campaign  etc...  To get 4 preview services in, you may have to plan them every other week leading up to the launch. That many  monthly  previews would require a very long on-ramp.', 'Get a calendar and work backwards from your prospective launch of worship gatherings.  Watch out for holiday weekends, local school district breaks and major local festivals/events.  Schedule at least 4 preview services.  Add dates for preview services to the church calendar.  This action is complete when you have scheduled preview services.', 'template: standard  This task needs a complete review/update - request Pat''s input.&  ----ds  I asked tom to do this for us ---pcf  I consulted with Dave and Tom. I then simplified it. --sc  2017-03-31 removed rogue tags/formatting --pb  2017-11-15 content updated --pb  2022-11-21 updated links --sc  2018-01-24 moved additional resources to Actions section --pb  2018-08-21 tweaked title --pb  2018-10-30 replace broken link to dreamgrow.com with& infographic links --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 98& to 63 --pb&  2024-03-08 updated content & resource links --pb  &  ', 5, 'todo', 129, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0d52bab3-0b45-503f-9a50-c82bb4bb3190', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Delegate PlanterPlan tasks to others', 'Delegate actions from PlanterPlan to Launch Team members so that you are freed up to do what only you can do.', 'There are some things the lead planter cannot delegate. But most of what''s here in PlanterPlan can be done by other people. Free yourself up to do the most important things that only you can do. Delegate.  Now is the best time to establish a culture of delegation.  If you want to establish a culture where the church grows beyond what you alone as the leader can accomplish, you have to delegate responsibility. In a church plant, delegating responsibility to Launch Team members is a healthy part of the process of getting people to take ownership for the vision.  Once a Launch Team begins to come together, review all the outstanding tasks here in PlanterPlan (with a focus on the ones with your name on them) and identify tasks that can be delegated to people on the Launch Team.  But don''t limit yourself to just your Launch Team. Many tasks can be done virtually by extended family, friends, former neighbors, financial supporters or supporting churches.  Some tasks require you to make a leadership decision after someone else has done the research or heavy lifting. If you don''t have a volunteer, delegate the heavy lifting to a part-time, minimum wage helper (like a high school or college student).', 'Do an initial review of the outstanding tasks here in PlanterPlan for:  tasks that only  you  can do  tasks where someone else can do the heavy lifting for you  tasks that anyone can do with a little oversight and/or training  Think of a volunteer who could do each of the tasks not in the first category above.  For volunteers with only 1 or 2 tasks, use PlanterPlan''s email and/or print buttons to delegate the tasks.  For key volunteers, leaders and staff that will have many tasks, invite them to collaborate on your PlanterPlan project using  Project > Manage Team  .  Go through the list again and see if there are clusters of unassigned tasks that could be farmed out to a part-time seasonal hire.  For any remaining unassigned tasks, get your Prayer Team praying for people to fill the gaps.  This action is complete after you have identified and delegated every possible action from the PlanterPlan task list to someone else.', 'template: standard  2017-06-14 content validated --pb&  2019-12-23 content updated --pb ', 6, 'todo', 121, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('fa319920-705f-50d1-8637-ddcce682b48a', '89398a75-6aa5-5b8c-b447-49f80f679f9c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Check in on your Opening Day Expectations', 'Revisit the Opening Day Expectations document to determine if the church plant is on track or if the track has changed.', 'Every plan needs to be flexible and adapt to a changing environment.  Early in the planning process, you should have completed the <a href="/resources/item/197">Opening Day Expectations Worksheet</a>. Not all things will go according to plan. Assumptions that were made at the beginning of the planning process are subject to change.  For instance, you may have planned to bring on additional staff early in the pre-launch process in order to more quickly build the Launch Team. However, a qualified staff member was not found. That changes the plan.  Or perhaps, the plant had few partners in the beginning, but since then large donors have begun supporting the work. This has enabled the planter to hire additional staff and conduct a more robust marketing campaign. The result should be expectations for a larger Launch Team and larger attendance at opening day.  It is important that the Oversight/Management Team and Launch Team have a good understanding of what is being worked towards. If original assumptions have changed, update the Opening Day Expectations document.  It is important not to make these decisions alone. Seek the counsel of the Management Team when making changes to the Opening Day Expectations. This will ensure that you are making good decisions and that the church will be launched in a healthy manner.', 'Review the Opening Day Expectations Document created in an early PlanterPlan action. Based on new information, determine if it needs to be updated.  Present any proposed updates to the Management Team for insight and affirmation.  Communicate changes in the plan to the Launch Team.  This action is complete when you have reviewed and updated the Opening Day Expectations Document.', 'template: standard  2017-10-30 content validated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 154& to 171& & Duration from 105& to 121& --pb&  ', 7, 'todo', 180, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('8175d4d2-5b9f-5fff-987b-7a66934d4d81', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this startup equipment overview', 'Wrap your brain around everything that''s involved and at stake in ordering ministry equipment for the worship gatherings.', 'It''s easy to get wrapped up in the excitement and details of buildings and gadgets. We can''t let those things become the point of church. You can let your vision & mission drive your equipment choices, or let them drive your vision.  Be proactive and intentional about the kind of equipment you''ll use for worship gatherings. Keep the big picture in mind so you don''t get lost in the weeds or sucked in to a scarcity mentality by reacting to perceived circumstances.  Expectations  You even get to contextualize your equipment needs. Don''t buy an equipment package that is well above or below the means of the people you''re reaching.  Transportation and Storage  Chances are good you''ll have to get the equipment from storage to the facility and back each week. Common options include:  volunteers pulling small- to medium-sized trailer(s)  volunteers pulling large-sized trailer(s)  volunteers driving a church-owned truck & trailer combo  volunteers driving a church-owned box truck  storing some or all of the equipment at the facility  Opportunity Cost  Too many planters try to save a few bucks by shopping for all of the ministry equipment themselves, only later to regret eating up the 80-90+ work hours they could have used out in the community or developing leaders.', 'Read the brief overview above.  Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="/resources/item/75">Obtain Startup Equipment</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.  This task is complete when you''ve read the content and watched the video.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 updated content & links --pb&  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 112& to 135& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 121, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a659188f-b75b-55fb-9b93-b1a8989eec7b', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a rough draft equipment list', 'Create an initial ballpark list of equipment to begin the purchasing process.', 'At this stage of the equipment process, don''t get into model numbers and colors. You''re just putting together a rough list of the kinds of things you would need to pull off a worship gathering that supports the vision.  Start with a sample equipment list (see  Actions  below). Cross off things you won''t need and add things you will.  Quality Expectations  Note on the list for each category or even each item whether you''re looking for good, better or best quality. You need to communicate those expectations as you ask for pricing quotes.  Get Quotes  Use the list as the springboard for getting quotes from all-in-one equipment package vendors, like:  <a title="ChurchPlant.com" href="https://www.churchplant.com">ChurchPlant.com</a>  <a title="Portable Church Industries" href="https://www.portablechurch.com">Portable Church Industries</a>  <a title="Churcn in a Box" href="https://www.churchinaboxsolutions.com">Church in a Box</a> --> <a title="Church on Wheels" href="https://www.churchonwheels.com">Church on Wheels</a>  They will manage the entire process, build an integrated system, and save you tons of time for not much more than you''d spend doing it yourself.  DIY  Or you can use the list for delegating purchasing to your team. If you do manage your own list, find launch team members that have expertise in either equipment or project management. Beware of the time sink: many planters burn 80, 90 or more work hours managing the list themselves. That''s time that you could used for disciple-making, community service and leadership development.  Designing the AVL System  The equipment package vendor will offer to travel to your site to see the facility and take specific measurements, etc. There are lots of environment factors to consider when putting together both a sound system, a projection system and potentially also a lighting system.  Some sound considerations are:  Is the room made of hard surfaces that will bounce sound around?  Is the room wide or deep or both?  What is the typical size of the band (ex: a simple 3-piece ensemble, or full band with 6 singers)?  What type of sound are you going for? (ex: coffee house, rock, or club?)  How skilled are your initial soundboard operators?  How far is it from the stage to where the sound board will be?  Are the sermons going to be recorded for podcast?  Some projection considerations are:  How much ambient light is in the room (ex: a gymnasium with skylights or a theater with no windows)?  How far is it from the projector to the screen?  How far is it from the projector to where the projectionist will sit?  Is there room for rear projections (preferable), or will the projector need to be in front of the screen?  What output jack does the computer used for projection have (e.g. HDMI, DVI, RJ-45)? ...and does that match the jack(s) on the projector?  How much video will you be using?', 'Start with Passion for Planting''s <a title="equipment list template" href="/resources/item/74">equipment list template</a> and/or an actual church plant equipment order from a friend.  Add and remove items to get to the list that supports the vision.  Note quality expectations for entire sections and/or individual items.  Use the list to get quotes for equipment costs.  This action is complete when you have a rough draft list of equipment.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 content & resource link updated --pb&  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 112& to 142 & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 134, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a8edbbb1-144b-5d41-b70a-5b4e0482941c', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Add dates and dollars to the equipment list', 'Using quotes from vendors for specific pieces of equipment, add cost figures and ordering lead times to your rough draft equipment list.', 'The total price tag for everything you dreamed of may surprise you. And the time it takes to get everything ordered, delivered and assembled is probably longer than you''re thinking.  As the vendors'' quote(s) come in, or as your team leaders submit their wish lists, add dollar amounts to the rough draft equipment list. Keep a running total.  Also add ordering lead times to the rough draft equipment list. Your all-in-one package vendor will need some time to order everything, assemble it, and get it in the trailer. And it''s common for various pieces of AVL equipment to be back-ordered for 60 days regardless of whether you''re using an equipment vendor or going DIY.  Walk back from the dry run/training event you''re planning (see subsequent PlanterPlan task) and add ordering deadline reminders to your calendar. Everyone needs to have practiced on the equipment before the first preview worship gathering.', 'Based on quotes, add dollar amounts to your rough draft equipment list.  Add ordering lead times for items as well.  This action is complete when you have reviewed the second-draft list and made both budgetary and deadline decisions.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 content reviewed --pb&  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 112& to 142 --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 141, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('84296101-ab28-591e-be77-bcfb1602f581', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Determine spare equipment and supply list', 'Create a list of supplies, tools and equipment to have on hand that may very well avert a Sunday morning emergency.', 'You won''t be able to have all of the spare parts, supplies and equipment you could ever possibly need. That would be expensive and wasteful.  But you can have a common sense ''first aid'' kit that has what you''ll need to address the kinds of emergencies many church plants run into.  Purchase Based on Risk  There are two major components to risk: how much distraction a particular failure would cause, and how likely it is to happen.  For example, the preacher''s mic battery pack dying 5-minutes before the worship gathering starts wouldn''t be unusual, and it would be a huge distraction. So have a box of batteries ready to go.  In addition to batteries, here are other common items to consider:  a roll of duct tape or gaff tape (fixes anything, right?)  a roll of painter''s tape (to temporarily mark things)  a handful of zip ties  a basic toolkit with screwdrivers, wrenches and a hammer; be sure it includes a tiny screwdriver for battery packs and other electronics  scissors', 'Draft a list of spare equipment and tools to have on hand.  Add desired spare parts to the equipment list.  Put someone in charge of ordering those items.  This action is complete when the spare parts, supplies and tools have been ordered.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 content reviewed --pb&  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 126& to 151& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 141, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('67ee8280-c157-5b71-83e5-d7018edddc50', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Create a map for strategic sign placement', 'Make strategic decisions about where signs will go at the facility and nearby intersections, and create a map as reference for your signage team.', 'Location, Location, Location. The mantra of the Real Estate agent is very applicable to church signage. Unless you want your location to be invisible, be intentional about putting out the right number of signs at the right places.  Drive the area surrounding the facility. By observing traffic patterns, determine the best locations to place signs. Consider high visibility areas as well as areas where drivers may be stopped at lights or stop signs.  The orientation of your sign can be as important as the location of the sign. Often angling the sign toward traffic (like in a median strip) is more effective than having it point directly down the street.  Here is a sample of a map showing where to place signage at major intersections around the facility:  Here is a sample map showing where to place signage in front of the facility:', 'Become familiar with traffic patterns.  Determine which intersections people are most likely to use when driving to your facility.  Decide which intersections will include signs.  Determine where in the intersections the signs will be most visible.  Stand on the street opposite the worship gathering facility.  Determine how much signage you''ll need to make the entrance to the parking lot obvious, as well as where the main entrance to the facility is.  Create a paper or <a href="https://mymaps.google.com">digital map</a> that marks where the signs should be set up each weekend.  This action is completed when you have developed the map of sign locations.', 'template: standard  2017-05-23 updated content --pb  2018-06-27 additional resources subsection added --pb  2020-01-13 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 196& to 186 --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 171, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0e386427-d10e-5b9e-8feb-5655915e6be5', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Finalize the equipment list', 'Settle on the final list of equipment you will order.', 'You''ve worked up a rough draft, modified it and gotten quotes from vendors. If you''re working with an equipment package vendor, you have probably gone back and forth on the quote a few times, adding and removing things.  Now is the time to finalize all of that so you don''t run out of time to order it.', 'Combine all equipment needs into one comprehensive list.  Include purchase prices and lead times.  Prayerfully finalize the list and begin ordering (see subsequent PlanterPlan tasks).  This action is complete when you have distributed the finalized equipment list.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 content updated. --pb&  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 182& to 186& & Duration from 7 to 50& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 150, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('344a35ba-a4f7-5728-a31f-35f60691a6d8', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Purchase equipment', 'Order all of the equipment in time for it to arrive for the dry run/practice service.', 'Some items, especially sound equipment, will take longer than others to get in-hand. Because it''s expensive, you''ll be tempted to wait until the last possible moment to order it. Don''t! Unforeseen circumstances could set you up for an Opening Day catastrophe.  Subtasks that follow will walk you through:  soliciting donations through an online gift registry  purchasing the audio/visual/lighting (AVL) equipment  purchasing other non-AVL equipment for various ministries  purchasing a presentation computer and software  purchasing outdoor and indoor signs', 'Starting with your finalized equipment list, work through each of this task''s subtasks.  This action is complete when you have completed each of the subtasks that follow this task.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 content reviewed --pb&  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 161& to 166& & Duration from 14& to 30 --pb&  ', 6, 'todo', 259, 200, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('8c49dce4-3dcc-5030-ac85-6f822dd998e4', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Add equipment and trailer to insurance policy', 'Add newly purchased equipment and transportation to the insurance policy so that they''re covered in the event of a loss.', 'One church planter showed up to the RV storage lot on Sunday morning to find that the church''s trailer full of equipment had been stolen. What a rough way to start a Sunday!  But it got worse. He called the insurance company to file a claim, and all they could say was, "What trailer?" That was the moment the planter remembered that he''d never circled back and added it to the insurance policy. The insurance had been purchased months before when finalizing the facility lease.  Increasing your replacement coverage is an easy phone call to your church insurance agent. Including a truck or trailer (anything with a VIN) will require adding an auto policy to your church insurance, which is also usually easy to do.  Be sure to ask your agent about whether the contents in the trailer are covered for loss while in transit. Some insurance carriers may require you to purchase an "Inland Marine" rider for that.', 'Call your insurance agent and let them know about your recent purchases.  Provide invoices or other documentation to substantiate the replacement value.  Get the policy change in writing.  Don''t forget to pay the premium increase!  This action is complete when you get written confirmation that the equipment and trailer are now covered by your church insurance policy.', 'template:  2019-12-10 date fields found empty  2019-12-11 date fields re-entered manually --pb  2020-12-14 changed Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 7, 'todo', 195, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b7cd9fcf-2ed7-5659-8b02-8e52cceb5627', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Conduct a dry run prior to first preview', 'Stage, assemble and test all of the equipment to be ready for the first preview service (worship gathering).', 'After you order all of your equipment, you have to assemble it and practice setting it up the first time. A dry run or practice service is that event.  Have no expectation that you''ll run an actual worship gathering. Just have everyone show up and learn how to set everything up and plug everything in. Be sure that  everything  is practiced once, from AVL to signs to coffee pots to whatever.  Of course, you can break for a minute and offering a devotional thought, cast vision and/or sign a song. But the setup will take twice to three times as long as normal, so don''t try this the morning of your first preview service.  While you''re at it, assign someone on each team to label and/or color code things to make the weekly set up easier. Buy a label maker, different colors of duct tape, and different colored permanent markers.', 'Plan a date and book a facility for the dry run. It''s best if you can be in your same facility where you''ll gather for worship.  Invite everyone on your Launch Team to come, even if they won''t have anything to do with set up most weeks. Cross-training is invaluable.  Get all of the equipment there. Unwrap and unbox items as much as you can ahead of time.  Put it all together and test to make sure it works.  Jot down all of the things you need to buy to fill any gaps.  This action is complete when you have staged, assembled, and tested all of the ministry equipment.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 content updated --pb&  2020-01-21 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 224& to 219& & Duration from 14& to 7& --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 211, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('4eb1c792-934c-5fb9-84e6-4bf974b10344', '8ca53ea7-37ec-5a4e-b862-fabf9e5dfbac', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Make sure equipment fits into storage space', 'Make sure everything fits into the rolling carts, and that the carts fit into your trailer or truck.', 'If you''ve purchased an equipment package from an all-in-one vendor, this has been done for you.  If you''ve piece-mealed your package together and ordered or built your own rolling carts, you have to make sure they accommodate all the rest of your equipment. And you have to make sure your rolling carts actually fit into whatever your larger storage is: typically a trailer, a box truck or an on-site closet.  Real-World Woes  One planter had been stockpiling all of the equipment in a storage unit as it came in. But when he finally moved the equipment from the storage unit into the trailer, it didn''t fit. He had to purchase a bigger trailer (and lose money on reselling the first one), or buy a second trailer (and try to find more volunteers to tow it every week).  Another planter measured the trailer that was given to the church and ordered custom-made rolling carts based on measurements he took. Unfortunately, he hadn''t taken into account that as the carts roll up on a slanted ramp, they''re taller that when they''re on a flat surface. He''d ordered them too tall! They wouldn''t actually load onto the trailer. So he had to re-order new carts or order a different trailer, either of which costs thousands of dollars.', 'Make sure you have all of your equipment at the dry run/practice service (see previous PlanterPlan task).  After tearing it all down, load all the equipment into the appropriate bins, totes and rolling carts.  Load the trailer or storage unit to be sure all of the carts fit.  This action is complete when you have fit all of the equipment into its carts and fit the carts into your storage.', 'template: standard  2018-08-21 shortened name --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 245& to 211& & Duration from 45& to 52& --pb&  ', 9, 'todo', 218, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('91acf7eb-1a87-58cd-b839-f3726c392122', '8db8ea3a-5e3d-535a-a35b-9ca390f78b59', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this Groups Strategy overview', 'Brief yourself on what goes into a Groups Strategy and the process you''ll follow to create one.', 'True discipleship doesn''t happen in an hour on Sunday mornings. The  strategies  you developed as part of your Vision Frame will have included some smaller group unit to foster community, relationships and disciple-making.  The tasks in this milestone will help you articulate the way that God is calling you to structure your particular flavor of small groups. It''s important to have it clearly in mind so that you can train apprentices and leaders. It will also be important for de-programming churched people that come with differing assumptions about what groups should look like.  Your  Groups Strategy  will include:  A brief philosophy of groups  Type(s) of groups  How group will be promoted and people invited to groups  How leaders will be identified and trained  Benchmarks of health/success', 'Read the content above.  Quantify your own assumptions about groups.  Begin praying about what God wants to do in and through the church''s groups.  This task is complete when you''ve read the content above.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated, audience changed to coach --pb  2018-04-20 updated content, changed audience to planter --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 53& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 46, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('bf306ca5-91df-58bc-9ac2-20d51ed70263', '8db8ea3a-5e3d-535a-a35b-9ca390f78b59', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about launching groups', 'Open a conversation with your coach about launching a groups ministry.', 'Your coach is a practitioner in church planting, which includes starting Groups. They come in all shapes and sizes, but your church will need some kind of groups structure to foster community and disciple-making.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Group size and structure  Content and format  Measuring success  Group leader expectations  Promoting groups  Overcoming objections to joining a group', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about launching groups.', 'template: standard  2017-12-29 content updated --pb  2018-04-20 moved to Launch Team milestone --pb  2018-11-20 moved to DNA milestone, demoted to child, changed Due in days from 114, changed parent ID from #375 --pb  2019-11-25 content updated --pb ', 1, 'todo', 52, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b1a2cf82-7e4f-5888-92c2-ec8c9d1c8179', '8db8ea3a-5e3d-535a-a35b-9ca390f78b59', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Groups Strategy', 'Draft a comprehensive strategy for groups at your church.', 'Disciple-making and community don''t happen during an hour on Sunday morning. And they don''t happen when a believer is a Lone Ranger. Groups create environments where discipleship and community can flourish.  There are many different ways to do church groups. As the leader you get to decide how groups will start and function at the church.  Using the  Church Groups Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/357">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/359">Google Doc</a>), you will work through the following:  A brief philosophy of groups  Define what kind(s) of groups to start  Set a goal for groups at Launch  Establish expectations of group leaders  Develop group leader training plan  Select group curriculum or content  Decide when to start groups', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Church Groups Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/357">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/359">Google Doc</a>).  Work through the content above and the subsequent PlanterPlan subtasks; record your thoughts & decisions in the template.  Interview other churches you respect about their groups structure and systems.  Finalize your Church Groups Strategy.  Send the completed Groups Strategy to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have submitted your written Church Groups Strategy to your coach.', 'template: standard  2018-03-28 content overhauled --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 147 to 60& & Duration from 14& to 7& --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 59, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('cd362cd5-09c0-58e6-901a-e67e52aa7f00', '8db8ea3a-5e3d-535a-a35b-9ca390f78b59', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Groups Strategy', 'Make sure that the planter has thought through and developed a Groups Strategy.', 'After you get the planter''s Groups Strategy document, either encourage the planter to fix its weaknesses or affirm that is a sufficient plan.  A solid Groups Strategy will cover:  description of kind(s) of groups  group curriculum or content  expectations of group leaders  training plan for group leaders  a target date for launching the first group(s)  a goal for number of groups at launch', 'Review the planter''s Groups Strategy.  Offer the planter feedback.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Groups Strategy.', 'template: standard  2018-03-29 content update --pb  2018-11-19 title changed from "implement discipleship strategy" --pb  2019-12-03 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 175& to 105& & Duration from 42& to 45& --pb  &  ', 3, 'todo', 66, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('70e80497-768d-519f-b517-6ae836395fa1', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this Staffing Strategy overview', 'Understand the impact your initial hiring decisions and HR systems have on your church plant.', 'Even if your first hire isn''t immediate, there are some things you need to know about hiring church staff. The following tasks included in this Milestone will help you think through timing, hiring order, and setting up HR systems for your church.  You Need a Process  You need to follow a disciplined hiring process for several reasons:  It helps you explain and set expectations with the candidate(s)  It keeps you from skipping important steps  It helps you avoid discrimination lawsuits  In addition to having a good process, be sure to add an  Employment Practices  rider to your church insurance policy.  Ministers and Housing Allowance  Ministerial housing allowance is perhaps the last great tax advantage available to clergy. Calculating it and administering it can be tricky, so it will be important to learn some of the basics:  The Management Team or oversight needs to approve housing allowance requests in writing in advance (never retroactively)  The church should have some record of the pastor''s ordination, commission or license to substantiate designating part of their pay as housing allowance  Housing allowance income is only exempt from income taxes, not social security tax (technically self-employment tax)  If they were a non-clergy employee, the church and the employee would each pay 7.65% tax for social security; on at least the housing allowance, the pastor has to pay the entire 15.3% themselves  The church cannot withhold social security tax from the pastor''s paycheck, but they  can  withhold extra income tax at the employee''s request; that overpayment washes out the social security (self-employment) tax when the employees file their own taxes  There are Hidden Costs  If you''ve never been a hiring manager and budget creator before, you need to know that the price tag of each employee is higher than the pay package you''ll offer them:  The church must pay a 7.65% social security tax on the salary portion of their pay (not any housing allowance)  In most every state, you''ll also be paying for Workers'' Comp insurance  You may have software subscriptions that are per user; those costs will increase with a new hire (ex: email accounts)  A good rule of thumb is to gross up their pay by 10% to estimate their true price tag for budgeting purposes (ballpark). So the cost of a part-time hire of $1,000/mo will cost your church closer to $1,100/mo.  A Bad Hire Could Derail Your Church Plant  It''s crucial to make the right decisions the first time. An employee that goes rogue could split the church. An employee who consistently underperforms will create a financial and relational drag. But an employee with the right heart and team chemistry will grow your church''s capacity to make an impact in your community.  Calling, Character, Competency, Chemistry  Hire slow and fire fast. Chemistry is the hardest of  the 4 C''s of Hiring  to figure out in the hiring process (calling, character, competency & chemistry). Just remember that new skills can be learned. If the chemistry is bad, working with them will be like sandpaper. Churches tend to hire based Competency and fire based on Chemistry.  Passion for Planting strongly recommends having all final-round candidates go through an online church planter pre-assessment (see tasks in the previous Milestone  Affirm the Calling ). You''ll get personality profiles and other important insights into your candidate. And if they''re a full-time hire or someone who will be the ''face'' of the church like your worship leader, consider sending them through a full assessment process prior to making a job offer.', 'Watch the <a href="/resources/item/98">Hire Staff training video</a> by Dr. Ed Stetzer.  Take notes on what you learn; include your resulting actions steps into your written Staffing Strategy.  This action is complete when you have watched the Hire Staff training video.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated, audience changed to coach --pb  2018-04-20 content updated, audience changed back to planter --pb  2018-11-12 title changed from "Call your coach about hiring staff" --pb  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 63& to 57 --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 50, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('70d1df4a-c3b4-56de-b787-bf8c8637a296', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about staffing', 'Open a conversation with your coach about finding and hiring staff.', 'Staffing is one of the most important things you will do during the pre-launch period. Staffing should come directly out of the vision for the new church. If the vision is to reach young families in the community, then an appropriate staff hire may be a children''s pastor. Each staff hire should support the overall vision of the new church.  In addition, each person hired should be sold out to the vision, beliefs and values of the new church. Staff members will be key players in setting the DNA of the church. A bad hire can cripple the new church and kill momentum.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Where to find staff  How to set staff hiring priority order  Creating a hiring time line  Using interns  Avoiding hiring mistakes', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about hiring staff.', 'template: standard  2017-10-30 content and links validated --pb  2018-03-07 Additional Resources subsection added --pb  2018-06-01& gdoc& template added --pb&  2019-12-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 77& to 71& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb  2022-11-21 updated links --sc ', 1, 'todo', 56, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('848afa6b-66d8-5652-afe9-884785cd1a72', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Staffing Strategy', 'Put together a document that includes everything about when and how you''ll hire staff.', 'The Staffing Strategy will help you identify your initial plans for hiring. It takes all of the key output from the following sub-tasks tasks and puts it into a single document. Work through the following sub-tasks and put your completed answers in the  Staffing Strategy Template  (below).  Identify which staff positions to pursue  Determine hiring timeline  Decide on staff fundraising expectations  Decide on which benefits to offer, especially whether or not to offer health care insurance  Create a step-by-step hiring process  Be sure to include the following key information:  Which roles you''ll fill with paid staff  Which roles you''ll fill with volunteers  How you might use interns  Which jobs can be grouped together into a full-time staff role  Prospective hire dates for each role', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Staffing Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/67">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/377">Google Doc</a>).  Fill in the blanks to develop your own Staffing Strategy.  Complete all the subordinate PlanterPlan tasks.  Send the written Staffing Strategy to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete after you have sent your written staffing strategy to your coach for feedback.', 'template: standard  2017-06-20 updated resource links --pb  2017-10-30 content updated --pb  2018-04-15 moved blog link to new Additional Resources subsection --pb&  2019-12-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 70 to 64 --pb&  2022-11-21 updated links --sc ', 2, 'todo', 77, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('9c6b4cdb-1e7f-516d-ae4a-6ee9065352c6', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Staffing Strategy', 'Ensure that the planter is equipped to hire staff.', 'Many church planters have never been a hiring manager before. It may come as second nature what position they should hire for next, or they may be making default assumptions that don''t necessarily work in their context.  Many more have never been involved in budgeting for hires nor making sure that basic HR procedures are followed in the hiring process. Most planters need a good check-up when it comes to staffing.  Read the planter''s Staffing Strategy document. The who and when of hiring should come directly out of the vision for the new church - each  hire should support the vision.  The planter should only hire candidates that are sold out to the vision, beliefs and values of the new church. Staff members will be key players in setting the DNA of the church. A ''bad hire'' can cripple the new church and kill momentum.  Given a planter''s entrepreneurial wiring, they may be tempted to cut corners and rush the hiring process. Poke around and find out how they''ll test the chemistry and really get to know the candidate before calling them to join the staff.  The planter''s Staffing Strategy should include:  Staff positions to pursue  A hiring time line  Staff fundraising expectations  Content of compensation package  A step-by-step hiring process  Consider the values and strategies included in the planter''s Launch Strategy document and make sure that their Staffing Strategy adequately supports it.', 'Review the planter''s completed Staffing Strategy.  Challenge their assumptions and test their understanding.  Give the planter feedback.  This action is complete after you, the coach, have given the planter feedback on the Staffing Strategy.', 'template: standard  2017-11-10 content updated and new resource link added --pb  2018-11-12 renamed from "Initiate personnel records filing system" to "create & secure personnel files" --pb  &  ', 3, 'todo', 77, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('cb74ab7e-0769-5321-be1f-35c7553d82c6', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Create initial HR forms', 'Compile a library of forms you''ll use in the hiring process for prospective employees.', 'One of the disadvantages of establishing the church as a new, legally autonomous legal entity is that you have to create new HR systems from scratch.  If you''re hiring staff, they will be employees of the new church. You have legal and tax responsibilities to cover. And if a disgruntled employee sues, they''re suing the new church, not some other entity.  Do things right from the beginning by setting the new church up with responsible hiring practices that honor the employee and protect the church.  HR forms you will need include:  <a href="/resources/item/382">Job Description Template</a>  <a href="/resources/item/385">Employment Application Template</a>  <a href="/resources/item/245">Interview Questionnaire</a>  <a href="/resources/item/248">Reference Check Questions</a>  <a href="/resources/item/72">Job Offer Letter Template</a>  <a href="/resources/item/384">Authorization to Release Information form</a>  <a href="/resources/item/344">Personnel File Checklist</a>', 'Compile your library of HR forms by downloading and customizing each of the forms above.  File the electronic versions of the forms where hiring managers and church leadership can access them.  Commit to using these forms in every hiring process.  This action is complete when you have created a starter library of HR forms in an electronic file/folder where leaders can access it.', 'template:  2018-11-19 new task  2012-12-02 content validated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 148& to 155 --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 77, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('dccbc524-f90f-594c-8299-03c57c6da2de', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Create and secure personnel files', 'Comply with legal requirements by creating and maintaining a personnel file on each employee.', 'Begin personnel files for each of your employees on the date they are hired. Personnel files are used to keep track of important legal documents regarding the employee, as well as to keep a record of the employee''s performance.  What do you need to keep in the personnel files? You''ll actually need 3 folders for each employee and 1 common file for the Federal I-9s. You have to do that because there are certain records that shouldn''t be seen by supervisors but do need to be seen by an HR manager:  Employee Personnel File  Completed onboarding checklist  R&eacute;sum&eacute; and cover letter  Job application  Job description  Signed acknowledgements (policies, etc.)  Performance reviews, awards & commendations  Copies of ordination paperwork  Training records  Complaints against employee  Disciplinary records  Separation documents  Confidential Records File  Signed authorization to perform background check  ADA accommodation records  Anything that might identify a protected class (age, race, etc.)  Compensation Records File  Job offer letter  Benefits information  Employee''s signed W4  Employee''s signed State Withholding form (as applicable)  Housing Allowance designation requests  Direct deposit forms  Vacation requests and/or records (salaried employees)  Time cards (hourly employees)  Federal I-9''s  one common file for all employees'' completed I-9s  In a church, it may seem overkill to keep all of this in personnel files. However, remember that as a pastor, part of your job is to train and equip. Keeping a detailed record of each employee''s evaluations, yearly goals/plans, and even complaints can help you to maximize their potential. Accountability for performance should be taken just as seriously in the church as in the business world.', 'Download the <a href="/resources/item/344">Sample Personnel File Checklist</a> which includes all of the above.  Determine where to house personnel files. If you don''t have them already, purchase files and a locking file cabinet.  Gather documents for any existing employee of the church and file them.  This action is complete when you have created personnel files for each employee and developed a system for keeping them up to date.', 'template: standard  2017-11-10 content updated --pb  2018-11-12 added "...for Current Staff" to title --pb  2019-03-25 additional resources subsection added --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 154& to 58 --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 134, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('408fc05d-a6e4-5f64-937f-27473b6e2877', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Create a Staff Policy Manual', 'Create a written Staff Policy Manual to set clear staff expectations and meet various legal requirements.', 'Clear expectations are critical to forming healthy staff relationships. A staff policy manual not only serves legal purposes, but helps the entire staff to know what is expected. It is far easier to proactively set and communicate expectations than to deal with controversy later.  Having to let a staff member go is never easy. It will be harder if there is ambiguity or controversy surrounding expectations.  You have several options for developing a staff policy:  Borrow and adapt a handbook from another church  Customize Passion for Planting''s <a href="/resources/item/247">Staff Policy Handbook Template</a>.  Develop a Staff Policy Manual from scratch  Purchase a template from a commercial vendor and customize it  Hire a church HR support ministry to help you craft it  Consider policies on vacation, hours worked, and days off. As a manager, be very clear with new hires about the expectations of work at the church.  Below is a sample index of topics recommended to be included in a staff policy manual:  Major Topics  Basics  Housing Allowance  Social Security  Medical Allowance  Salary Packages  Travel  Transportation  Business Expenses  Vacation, Work Days, and Work Hours  Basic Expectations for All Staff  Tax Reporting  Policies and Forms  Annual Housing and Medical Allowance Designation Form  Mid-Year Amendment to Housing or Medical Allowance Request  Medical Plan/Policy  Travel Reimbursement Plan/Policy  Travel/Vacation Request Form  Travel Reimbursement Request Form  Transportation Reimbursement Log  Expense Reimbursement Plan/Policy  Expense Reimbursement Request Form', 'Decide which option to pursue for developing a staff policy manual.  Customize it.  Adopt it by vote of your board or oversight team (several policies are required by the IRS to be approved by the Church Board).  This action is complete when the Staff Policy Manual is approved by the Board and issued for use.', 'template: standard  2017-11-13 content validated --pb  2019-11-20 title updated from "Develop a Reproducing Leader Culture" --pb  2019-12-03 content validated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 168& to 159& & Duration from 14& to 111& --pb&  ', 6, 'todo', 134, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0eae241a-3787-5d38-879d-bd960ddffa18', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop Social Media Policies', 'Create clear boundaries for staff social media engagement.', 'Eventually you''ll need to have more than one person, whether staff or volunteer, actively participating in the church''s social media. Before that happens, create some boundaries for consistency and safety.  Promoting Community Impact  Write out a clear set of expectations and boundaries so that anyone participating in social media on the church''s behalf won''t damage the church''s reputation. Social media creates an impression. Careless, callous or prejudicial words have no place on a church''s page.  Nor does a tirade against the church''s leadership belong on a staff member''s personal page. Staff members represent the church even when they are not ''on the clock''.  But simple maintenance can affect your impact, too. Just like a website that is poorly maintained creates a negative impression, a poorly maintained social media page will also create a negative impression. If someone comments on the church Facebook page and does not get a response for two weeks, they''ll think you don''t care about them.  Safety  Restrictions are important as well, especially for kids'' sake. We all love posting about our own kids, but posting pictures of kids at church could reveal the location of certain kids to people who shouldn''t know. Foster families are often legally restrained from posting images of their kids online. Just as we go the extra mile to protect kids with secure sign-in and sign-out procedures, we need to protect kids with good social media policies.  That also means you can''t have a public RSVP for events for youth or children. This is a safety hazard -it alerts sexual predators, estranged parents and others who would harm a child to the child''s location.  The policies should fall into two broad categories:  Sample expectations:  Posts should be made (daily/weekly)  Spend at least (1 hour a week) maintaining the church''s profile & feeds  Publish all scheduled events to social media and the church website  Sample restrictions:  No pictures of kids without parental consent  Never give out members'' contact information  No public RSVPs for events for youth or children', 'Create a list of social media expectations. These expectations should support the goals created in a previous PlanterPlan action.  Create a list of social media restrictions, giving special attention to children.  Create a social media policy for staff members. <a href="/resources/item/319">Here''s a template to get you started</a>. Consider including it in your Staff Policy Manual.  Communicate these policies with the staff and social media team.  This action is complete when everyone participating in social media on the church''s behalf understands the expectations and boundaries of their participation.', 'template: standard  2018-07-13 updated title & tweaked content --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 128& to 77& & Duration from 7 to 14; name changed from "create pages on social media sites" --pb&  ', 7, 'todo', 134, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('1317f18d-71e8-50c6-a3d8-9eef4ccf10ce', '92c46dbf-2a14-57a9-8ad1-a9340c781243', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Plan for effective staff meetings', 'Create a rhythm and format for regular staff meetings, whether with volunteer or paid staff.', 'Death by Meeting. It''s such a common plague that business author Patrick Lencioni wrote a book about it. Does that sound like staff meetings you''ve been a part of in the past?  You have the chance to set a new DNA for healthy, useful staff meetings in this new church. What you establish now will become the norm for years to come.  Lencioni''s <a href="https://files.tablegroup.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/12/14163149/Avoid-Death-by-Meetings.pdf">meeting model</a>, easily found online, is:  Daily Check-Ins  Weekly Staff Meeting  Adhoc Topical  Quarterly Off-site Review  Whether you have paid staff or key volunteer leaders, you have the opportunity to create a culture of meetings that inspire and energize.', 'Decide how often to have staff meetings.  Decide how long the meetings should last.  Decide whom to invite to the meetings.  Put the meetings on your calendar and invite your staff.  This action is complete when you have recurring staff meetings on the calendar. "', 'template:  2019-12-03 due date fields found empty --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 55& to 49& & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 170, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('34262855-591e-5051-a66c-c201ca5d8cb0', '942699a3-c0a6-51a8-82f6-53ac61e15252', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this teaching and preaching overview', 'Brief yourself on what goes into sermon planning and writing that reaches the unconvinced.', 'According to a <a href="https://news.gallup.com/poll/208529/sermon-content-appeals-churchgoers.aspx">2017 Gallup poll</a>, the top 2 reasons people attend churches are:  sermons that teach scripture  sermons that connect religion to real life  Preaching matters.  "&hellip;those for whom sermons were being dumbed down aren''t dumb. They are interested in the truth or else they''d be out golfing." -Ed Stetzer  Preaching to the Unconvinced  Church plants should be full of people who don''t necessarily buy in to this whole ''God thing''. Preaching with this in mind requires an awareness and sensitivity that many pastors have not yet developed. In the video below, Dr. Ed Stetzer has some great thoughts to help you understand how you can prepare to reach the disconnected and introduce them to Jesus Christ.  <a href="https://multiplication.org/product/preaching-to-the-unconvinced/">Preaching to the Unconvinced</a> by Vince Antonucci on Exponential.org  <a href="https://multiplication.org/product/sermons-for-the-unconvinced/">Sermons for the Unconvinced</a> by Vince Antonucci on Exponential.org  <a href="https://outreachmagazine.com/features/18123-preach-for-seekers-without-dumbing-down.html">Seeker Comprehensible Preaching&hellip; Without Dumbing Down</a> by Ed Stetzer on ChristianityToday.com  <a href="https://careynieuwhof.com/episode197/">How To Preach In A Way That Reaches Unchurched People And Maintains Biblical Integrity</a> on CareyNieuwhof.com  Styles of Preaching  And God has placed within you a teaching style which is unique to you. But be sensitive to the people God brings to you and leverage your style to maximize the impact you have.  <a href="https://www.propreacher.com/5-styles-of-preachers/">The 5 Styles of Preachers - Which Are You?</a> on ProPreacher.com  <a href="https://churchleaders.com/pastors/pastor-articles/162679-11-kinds-of-preacher-which-one-are-you.html">11 Kinds of Preacher: Which One Are You?</a> on ChurchLeaders.com  Sharing Ministry  You need to plan your sermon topics out months in advance and begin drafting each sermon weeks in advance. When you do that, you reduce panic and 11th-hour just-barely sermons. You also let others participate in the worship planning process, giving them time to give their best on song slides, videos, music practice, etc.  You also need to prepare ahead in a special way for the Launch. The first several weeks after launch will be very busy like no other time in the life of your church. You''re going to need the extra bandwidth for bolstering team leaders, following up with the flood of guests, and counseling hurting people (among other things). Writing your entire first sermon series well in advance and then brushing it up in the week leading up to preaching it will give you some extra breathing room.  Preaching in an Age of Tech  Another thing you need to be aware of as you plan sermons is that everyone who comes has access to the sermons of all the best preachers in the country. Don''t feel like you have to compete with or mimic them, but know that the bar is set high, so continue to grow in preaching with excellence.  Also know that with smart phones in hand during the sermon, they can fact check your claims while you''re still preaching. Be sure you''ve done your homework and checked your own facts.', 'Familiarize yourself with the topics above.  Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="/resources/item/213">Prepare for Teaching / Preaching</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.  This task is finished when you''ve read the content above and the supplemental blogs, and watched the video(s).', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated, audience changed to coach --pb&  2020-01-24 content validated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 200& to 166& --pb  ', 0, 'todo', 159, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('2d1efc0d-a88a-5fa0-a435-1e8f805be4c6', '942699a3-c0a6-51a8-82f6-53ac61e15252', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about sermon planning & writing', 'Open a conversation with your coach about writing sermons and planning a sermon calendar.', 'Writing sermons is an important part of casting vision and discipling the new church. There are a lot of weekly demands on you. In the early days, you''ll often shoulder a greater portion of the work until volunteer leaders are trained and equipped. Because of this reality, it is important to work ahead on your sermon writing.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Philosophy of preaching  Incorporating your primary gift in your preaching  Beliefs about the power of preaching in church planting  Creating culture through preaching  Which sermon series to launch with  How far in advance to plan sermons  Creative ways to deliver messages  Coordinating your planning with the worship and creative arts teams  Protecting your sermon writing time  Making your sermons practical  Soberly gauging your preaching ability', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about sermon planning and writing.', 'template: standard  2017-12-28 content updated --pb  2020-01-24 content validated --pb  2020-06-26 changed title from "plan first 3 months'' sermon topics" --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 231& to 180& --pb  ', 1, 'todo', 165, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('5908ee96-1d3f-561d-b5e2-68535e6afc83', '942699a3-c0a6-51a8-82f6-53ac61e15252', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a sermon calendar', 'Well prior to your launch, plan the first 3 months of sermon topics so that you can include others in the process and get ahead of the curve.', 'As you think through how best to make disciples, cast vision, and develop the culture of the new church, plan out the first 3 months'' sermons. The grand opening is a unique time in the life of the church. You never get another chance for this church to be brand new again.  So bathe this in prayer, and maybe take a day or two away for planning. Put significant time and effort into your preaching calendar. The first year of the church will determine its trajectory for may years to come.', 'Contact other planters and your coach about how they cast vision at their grand opening.  Brainstorm potential sermon series and topics; keep in mind the season of the church and your Vision Frame.  Pray about each series and topic.  Using the <a href="/resources/item/355">Preaching Calendar Template</a>, write down the topics for at least the first 3 months.  Send the list to your coach and get some feedback.  Make adjustments.  This action is complete when you have gotten feedback on your schedule of sermon topics for the first 3 months.', 'template: standard  2017-12-28 content updated --pb&  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 245& to 211& --pb  ', 2, 'todo', 179, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('aab329f3-f512-5bef-921a-024a1aab4249', '942699a3-c0a6-51a8-82f6-53ac61e15252', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Plan church-wide financial stewardship training/series during the first year', 'Plan a financial stewardship lesson or series during the first year of the new church to make generosity and giving part of the new church''s DNA.', 'When you do an effective job of reaching people with little or no church background, their giving disciplines won''t be fully developed immediately. Helping them grow in generosity and stewardship will help them, and it will help fuel the mission of the church. The members and attenders of this new church should participate in its financial life.  Financial stewardship training is a matter of discipleship. Conducting that training during the first year will help the congregation understand the cost of what they are undertaking. It may even be a good outreach event to serve people in your community who are struggling financially.  Consider these financial training resources:  <a href="https://www.ramseysolutions.com/ramseyplus/organization">Financial Peace University</a>  <a href="https://goodsensemovement.org/">Good Sense</a>  <a href="https://www.crown.org/">Crown Financial Ministry</a>', 'Discern the attitude of your congregation about giving.  Select an appropriate financial training resource or plan your own sermon series.  Put the sermon/training date(s) on the calendar.  This task is complete when you have put the first financial stewardship training/series on the church calendar.', 'template: standard  2017-12-29 content updated --pb  2018-03-28 content overhauled --pb  2018-05-07 added& google& doc template version --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 147 to 60& & Duration from 14& to 7& --pb&  2020-12-22 While merging it with Decide When To Start Groups I cut a couple sentences that didn''t seem necessary. --sc ', 3, 'todo', 179, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('504d9e3d-1b61-5640-887e-cfc9b9f78750', '942699a3-c0a6-51a8-82f6-53ac61e15252', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Write all of the sermons for your opening series', 'Finalize each sermon for your first series at least 6 weeks before the Opening Day of worship gatherings.', 'Be as prepared as possible for the influx of new people to the church. There will be tons of new people to follow up with and connect with. There are few better ways to love those newcomers than to set aside priority time to follow up with them. The best way to make sure you have that bandwidth is writing sermons ahead of time.  Whether you manuscript sermons or build detailed outlines, now is the time to do it.  Plus, it''s a good discipline to write sermons in advance. If you can start with this discipline, it will be easier to keep it going. Avoid short-changing the sermon when busy weeks or crises arise.', 'Schedule time to write all of the sermons for your opening series.  Write them.  Send them to your coach and get some feedback.  This action is complete when you have written the first sermon series.', 'template: standard  2017-12-28 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 238& to 188& --pb &  ', 4, 'todo', 210, 45, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('08321528-f301-5136-b35b-9ebf9790961b', '942699a3-c0a6-51a8-82f6-53ac61e15252', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm sermon schedule', 'Review the planter''s sermon calendar and provide feedback on the appropriateness and pace of the topics.', 'The planter has prayerfully created a list of sermons for at least the first 3 months of the new church. Review the sermons and provide feedback to the planter.  Specifically, the sermons topics should provide opportunity to cast the vision for the new church and to connect well with the planter''s context.', 'Review the planter''s sermon calendar.  Provide feedback to the planter.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s sermon calendar.', 'template: standard  2017-12-27 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 208& to 213& & Duration from 77 to 92& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 187, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a308582e-1aee-581b-9181-29b8ee88927b', '98d4b9df-64f2-5b1c-bc36-923cc09c8418', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this facility selection overview', 'Open your eyes to the various complicated things you have to consider when hunting for a facility.', 'When setting out to find your worship gathering facility, there are lots of things to consider:  Capacity Constraints (what will you run out of first: seating? parking? etc)  Atmosphere  Reputation in the Community (How is this building perceived?)  Location, Location, Location  Accessibility for the Community  Hidden Make-or-Break Topics  Just as important as that initial checklist are some hidden make-it-or-break-it items:  electrical capacity  - is the whole worship room wired on one circuit? You''ll trip the breaker for sure with all your AVL equipment  competing events  - how likely is it that your church would get moved to another room or bumped entirely by another event?  included equipment  - if they allow you to use their sound, projector, etc., is it worth the risk that a volunteer might break it?  perception  - would your target families be endeared or repelled by how they perceive the facility?  restrooms  - are they far, too close (flushing can be heard), without HVAC, permanently stinky, or have small-sized toilets for kindergarteners?  cleanliness  - does the school custodian clean the facility Friday after school or Sunday night before school starts the next week?  aroma  - Nightclubs, gymnasiums and older YMCAs can have a lingering or stale odor that is difficult to mask with aerosols and air fresheners  social space  - is there a big enough lobby, patio, etc. that people will linger and make friends?  layout  - is the parking on the opposite side of the building from the entrance? Will the children''s ministry area be a day''s walk from the worship gathering room?  Pros & Cons of Different Facility Types  Facility Type  Pros  Cons  Schools  High Schools are typically well-known locations  Schools are typically well-respected in their community  Diverse room sizes typically available - both for adults & children  Sufficient electrical capacity  Elementary schools are often tucked away in residential neighborhoods  Elementary schools typical maximum capacity is 200/service  Middle schools typical maximum capacity is 400/service  High schools typical maximum capacity is 600-1600/service  Movie Theaters  No school boards or  Separation of Church & State  misunderstandings to overcome  Large video screen already built-in  Movie theaters are generally well-known locations  Seeker friendly  Refreshments allowed in worship gathering area  Large parking lot  Worship gathering area may be too dark to read handouts  "High traction" flooring often included  May have limited electrical capacity  May have tight time constraints (have to be out before matinees start)  Space for children''s ministry is often a challenge  Church Buildings  You might get the space cheap or even free  Can be a great partnership with another congregation  Older buildings especially may have a hip, ancient-future vibe  Probably a barrier for people who have never been to church  May create confusion about which church is which  Older buildings particularly may be worn/tired or not ADA-compliant  Other Facilities  Can attract young professionals not ready to ''go back to grade school''  Can be more suitable for artisan/experiential worship  Might be confusing or send mixed signals  If it''s not designed for audiences or presentation, it may have limited sight lines or insufficient stage area  Can have limited options for children''s ministry', 'Read the excerpt above from the Portable Church Industries blog.  Read the article <a href="/resources/item/90">Finding a Facility</a> by Mark Driscoll (still a good read).  Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="/resources/item/89">Select a Facility</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.  Optional: Create a interactive map with <a href="https://support.google.com/mymaps/answer/3024454?hl=en">Google Maps </a>and share it with your Launch Team and Management Team. Create a secondary layer for potential worship facilities (layers can be toggled on/off).  This action is complete when you have read the overview above.  Some of this task description was adapted from "<a href="https://portablechurch.blogspot.com/2006/03/how-to-choose-right-facility-for-your.html">How to Choose the Right Facility for Your Portable Ministry</a>" by Portable Church Industries.', 'template: standard  2017-05-22 content updated --pb  2017-05-31 audience changed to coach --pb  2019-12-17 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 98& to 38 --pb &  ', 0, 'todo', 31, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('f2b3dbd3-e291-5e31-8f53-0bee82902109', '98d4b9df-64f2-5b1c-bc36-923cc09c8418', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about finding a facility', 'Open a conversation with your coach about finding a worship facility.', 'Identifying a worship gathering facility can be the biggest bottleneck in a church plant timeline. So many other decisions hinge on where you''ll meet.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  A facility''s effect on the church''s DNA  How to narrow the list  Choosing between 2 imperfect options  What do do about office space', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about finding a facility.', 'template: standard  2017-05-22 content & resource links updated --pb  2019-12-17 content updated & links verified --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 98& to 93; name changed from "Decide what''s most important in a worship facility" --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 37, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a762ac1f-f32f-5d86-a434-cff88d0266e8', '98d4b9df-64f2-5b1c-bc36-923cc09c8418', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set your worship facility selection criteria', 'Use this worksheet to decide what''s most important in a worship facility before touring any potentials.', 'Sometimes selecting a facility comes down to choosing between 2 or 3 imperfect options. The  Facility Selection Worksheet  will help you think through your priorities before getting enamored with a particular facility that might not be your best choice.  The worksheet has 2 simple steps. This PlanterPlan task guides you through completing the first:  Step 1 - Rank Criteria : Decide in advance which criteria are most important to you in selecting a facility, such as children''s space, parking, visibility of location, etc.  The second step will be completed in the subsequent PlanterPlan task  Rank Facilities Using the Facility Selection Worksheet .', 'Download the <a href="/resources/item/87">Facility Selection Worksheet</a> and rank your criteria for the perfect worship facility.  This action is complete when you have decided on the most important deciding factor in choosing a worship facility.', 'template: standard  2018-10-10 added ''additional resources'' subsection --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 98& to 76& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 92, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7d121173-9a82-5343-9d57-b60459b5a4bf', '98d4b9df-64f2-5b1c-bc36-923cc09c8418', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Decide whether to rent or build out', 'Make an early decision on whether to hunt for rented Sunday-only worship space or lease a 24/7 facility you''ll build out.', 'Finding a meeting place is a major issue for most new churches. Though some new churches might like to  buy  a facility, it''s not possible for most. Usually the decision comes down to leasing a 24/7 facility or renting a one-day-a-week facility.  In summary, the options include:  Leasing a 24/7 facility  - This can be very expensive, but may be necessary in certain contexts to establish credibility in the community. Construction  always  comes in late and over budget - more than one church planter has had to delay Opening Day of worship gatherings due to construction delays.  Renting Space just for Worship  - This is the less expensive option but it only gives you space for several hours on Sunday (or whatever day you meet). Some churches that take this path also rent 24/7 office space. For examples of Sunday space, download Passion for Planting''s <a href="/resources/item/83">Facility Brainstorming Worksheet</a>.', 'Prayerfully consider the primary facility options in light of your financial resources and contextual needs.  Decide whether to rent a worship-only facility or a lease a 24/7 facility for worship gatherings.  This action is complete when you have made an initial decision on whether to rent or lease a facility.', 'template: standard  2019-12-17 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 127& to 143& & Duration from 90& to 82& --pb&  2020-12-23 name changed from "Secure a worship gathering facility" --pb ', 3, 'todo', 75, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7d330165-eec8-5d0d-9423-596395a21873', '98d4b9df-64f2-5b1c-bc36-923cc09c8418', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify a worship gathering facility', 'Work through the necessary due diligence to get to a signed worship facility contract.', 'The facility you choose will impact the church''s ability to grow for years to come. Find a facility which is safe for newcomers and easy to find.  Your facility also speaks volumes about who you are as a church and significantly shapes your community''s first impression of the church.  The subtasks following this will walk you step-by-step through:  making contact with management  as appropriate, getting on a waiting list  touring top facilities  prioritizing and narrow your list  ranking the top prospects  assessing demographics near top facilities  making a final choice  negotiating and signing a contract  Start Making a List  Start with the obvious choices you have undoubtedly been cataloging in your mind. Work the steps and you may just end up with an ideal facility.  If you exhaust that list, brainstorm every possible facility option you can think of (schools, colleges, community centers, movie theatres, etc).  Find out whether any new schools are being built and add them to your list.  Visit your local county or city planning office and get a list of every organization with an occupancy permit of over 200 (or a lower number dependent on your expected attendance). This list will help you identify facilities in your area where large groups are allowed to meet.  If you need more ideas, download Passion for Planting''s <a href="/resources/item/83">Facility Brainstorming Worksheet</a>.', 'Jot down the obvious choices you''ve already been considering.  If there are no obvious choices, or none of your first options are available, brainstorm a list of all possible meeting locations.  Work through the following subtasks until you have a signed facility contract.  This action is complete when you have a signed facility contract for the church''s worship gatherings.', 'template: standard  2017-05-22 content updated --pb  2019-12-17 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 108& to 110& & Duration from 48& to 49& --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 134, 74, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('437a9f6c-b7da-56af-9f0e-abc59743a934', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this branding overview', 'Understand some basic principles of branding so you can begin distinguishing your church within your community.', 'There is more to a brand than a logo and a color scheme. These are important pieces, but there are other factors that help a good brand stand out in an already crowded market.  The bigger question is, "What do you want your church to be known for?" Your brand is the story people tell themselves about you. It is your promise to your community.  The Ed Stetzer video below provides a brief overview that will get you up to speed on church branding.', 'Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="/resources/item/16">Branding - Define Church Identity</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.', 'template: standard  Need to ensure video works (needs updated link). -----ds  Just updated to our new media page:& <a href="https://planterplan.com/app/#/tutorial/media/16">http://planterplan.com/app/#/tutorial/media/16</a>  Had a reference to dev& site...removed.  2017-10-26 content validated & link verified --pb  2019-12-09 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 84& to 54& & Duration from 7 to 1& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 53, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('5b2d153a-7ad3-56e6-abe1-0fb08f8f8ca5', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Buy a domain name for the church', 'Buy the rights to a website address (domain name) that will be easy for people to remember and associate with your church.', 'Once you''ve finalized the name of the new church, one of your first steps is to buy a domain name.  You will buy the domain name from a  registrar  like GoDaddy or NameCheap; other options abound.  Here are 8 tips from the post  <a href="https://www.wpbeginner.com/beginners-guide/tips-and-tools-to-pick-the-best-domain-for-your-blog/">How to Choose the Best Domain Name (8 Tips and Tools)</a> :  Stick with .com [it''s everyone''s default guess]  Use keywords [like "church", so search engines know what your site is about]  Keep it short (  Make it easy to pronounce and spell  Keep it unique and brandable  Avoid hyphens  Avoiddoubled letters  Leave room to expand  We also recommend testing your top choices for alternate interpretations:  Is www.bethelame.com "Bethel AME" or "Be The Lame"?  How would you interpret "kidsexchange.com"?  Power Tip:  consider a domain name that can also become your social username. For example, XYZchurch could become your website at www.xyzchurch.com and used for you Facebook page at facebook.com/xyzchurch, etc. Sites like <a href="https://www.namecheckr.com">www.namecheckr.com</a> will check for available domain names and social usernames simultaneously.', 'Brainstorm possible names and name combinations.  Determine which possible names are available.  Select your primary web name and any additional aliases desired (.net, .org, etc).  Purchase the domain name(s).  This action is complete when have purchased the church''s new domain name.', 'template: standard  2017-09-26 changed Parent ID from 228 to 225 in order to move this from child task to regular task --pb  2017-09-26 content updated --pb  2019-12-09 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 35 to 60 --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 59, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('8594d95e-8941-5d8a-887d-8a48c73ae753', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up email accounts with new domain name', 'Set up a church email account for each staff member to facilitate branded communication.', 'As soon as you purchase your church''s domain name, you can set up email accounts. Your website and your email addresses will share the domain name, but they are unrelated services and one doesn''t depend on the other.  Popular Options  There are plenty of options, but the common choices are:  Your Registrar''s Service  Whoever you bought your domain name through commonly offers an email service. For example, GoDaddy will sell you <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/email/professional-business-email">email service</a> for as little as $2/user/month (teaser rate)  PRO: simple setup since it''s from your registrar; may be cheaper than the other options below  CON: may not include state-of-the-art spam filter; may not include other services (see others below)  Google Workspace  If you''ve ever used gmail, google calendar, google drive, etc. you already know <a href="https://workspace.google.com/pricing.html?tab_activeEl=tabset-companies">Google Workspace</a>. It runs as little as $6/user/month. The difference is that you get to brand it all with your own domain name.  PRO: comes with an entire suite of productivity apps plus 30GB of cloud storage per user; easy-to-use; best spam filter available  CON: they can scan your email content to sell you ads  NOTE: Google Workspace is free for approved nonprofits (once your get your 501c3 Determination Letter back from the IRS), but you have to agree to their non-discrimination policy  Microsoft''s Office365  You may be able to purchase this at a discount through your registrar, or you can purchase it directly from <a href="https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365/business/compare-all-microsoft-365-business-products">Microsoft</a> for as little as $8.25/user/month.  PRO: comes with an entire suite of productivity apps plus 1TB of cloud storage; excellent spam filter; they do not scan your content to sell you ads  CON: higher cost  NOTE: Office365 is also free for approved nonprofits (once your get your 501c3 Determination Letter back from the IRS), but you likewise have to agree to their non-discrimination policy  Pick the option that suits your budget and tech needs and either set it up yourself or get help from a tech-savvy friend.', 'Set up new email accounts based on the new website name.  Decide whether to keep any existing email accounts. If so, decide whether to have all your email accounts forwarded to a single account or to set up multiple inboxes on your various devices.  Create a generic address like info@ for publishing on your website.  This action is complete when valid email addresses associated with the new domain name are properly functioning.', 'template: standard  2017-09-21 content updated --pb  2017-09-26 changed Parent ID from 228 to 229 to keep as a child task --pb  2018-04-20 changed Parent ID to 225 & promoted to "task"  2019-12-09 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 42& to 60& & Duration from 28& to 7& --pb&  2022-12-23 change "G Suite" to new brand "Google Workspace", added Office365 grant language --pb ', 2, 'todo', 59, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('cfc4e792-9b14-5097-8e77-36d60e0edc6f', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Establish a relationship with a branding company', 'Choose a branding company that can guide you through the hard work of translating the church''s identity into a new brand.', 'Since the church''s name flowed out of your contextualization work, as soon as you choose the name you''ve already done the hard work to be ready to begin the branding process.  Branding is  way  more than just a logo. Your brand is your story. Your brand is your promise to your community. Your brand is your identity.  The first step, which is a big one, is to create the church''s brand. Your brand will include:  your colors, picked specifically for their psychology and style  your official font  your logo in multiple formats  a tag line or brand promise  a style guide that compiles all of these in one place  An initial branding package may also include:  business card design  letterhead design  social media cover image & thumbnail  a fundraising brochure or booklet design  vinyl event banner design  But you''ll have ongoing design needs even before your launch:  website  direct mail and/or door hangers  facility signage  sermon slides  You can get various pieces from various designers, but consider the long game. Pick a branding company that will be able to help with ongoing design needs, which also helps with brand consistency.  Be cautious of having a friend do the design for you for free. It might work out great. But common experience is that the friendship gets strained because of unmet expectations, missed deadlines, and hurt feelings on both sides.  Only hire a friend or relative that you''d be willing to fire .  Branding & Graphic Design Vendors  Here are some companies that have served our planters in the past:  <a href="https://www.brandarmy.org/">Brand Army</a>  <a href="https://www.amywaggs.com">Waggoner</a>  <a href="https://catalystchurchcreative.com">Catalyst Church Creative</a>  <a href="https://outreach.com">Outreach Marketing</a>  <a href="https://www.browncowdesign.com">Brown Cow Design</a>  <a href="https://churchmediasquad.com/">Church Media Company</a>  Other options abound.', 'Get referrals from friends and colleagues.  Refer back to your budget for how much you allocated for branding.  Determine what what you need in an initial design package.  Look at each designer''s portfolio to determine which designer''s ''look'' is a match.  Get an initial quote for the work that needs to be done.  This actions is complete when you have engaged a branding company to begin the branding process.', 'template: standard  2017-10-27 content udpated& --pb  2018-02-09 vendors subsection added --pb  2019-12-09 content updated & links verified--pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 84& to 74 --pb&  2022-11-22 undated links --sc ', 3, 'todo', 73, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c6f2ac55-7c40-5e94-9961-0e5e8fe938e5', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a brand style guide', 'Develop a consistent look and feel to your communication materials so that you can be effective in connecting with the people God is calling you to reach.', 'Brand recognition allows people to quickly identify your church and experience positive feelings about your marketing.  Have you ever noticed that all McDonald''s restaurants look basically the same? This is brand identity. Even young children know that at the restaurant with the golden arches they can order a Happy Meal and get a free toy.  Eventually, people who see your marketing and attend events need something to tie everything together, something to relate all the messages they are hearing to the same place. They ought to know when they see your logo that ''this is the church where __________''.  Based on your demographics research and Vision Frame, you''ll develop a core identity to be communicated in all marketing materials and throughout all outreach events.  The specific products of your brand identity include:  your colors, picked specifically for their psychology and style  your official font  your logo in multiple formats (see subsequent PlanterPlan action)  a tagline or brand promise (see subsequent PlanterPlan action)  a style guide that compiles all of these in one place (the primary product of this task)  Where to Start  Your branding company may give you similar homework. Here are some great pre-work exercises that will make your branding process faster & smoother:  Find 5 magazine ads that you like. Write down what you like about them.  Find 5 logos that you really like. Write down what you like about them.  Find 5 web sites that you really like. Write down what you like about them.  Collect 5-10 pieces of direct mail advertising that you really like. Write down what you like about them.  Download the <a href="https://churchbrandguide.com/how-to-create-your-churchs-brand/">How to Create Your Church''s Brand</a> guide.  The Style Guide  A style guide serves as a standard for maintaining the integrity of your brand. The style guide lists the approved ways to use your logo, tagline, colors and fonts on marketing and promotional pieces. It includes things such as:  A short description of the brand in qualitative terms. This paragraph highlights the uniqueness of the organization, its niche, etc.  Primary colors of the organization (in both full color and gray scale)  Primary logo of the organization and the ways it can be used / displayed including any allowed alterations  Primary fonts / typefaces of the organization  Primary tagline of the organization  Other images used by the organization  Any reputable branding company will offer you at least a simple style guide as part of your branding package.  Great samples to learn from:  <a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/15NG4shAE8xBPMCFGR6xbmtLtZ8S5YbMV/view?usp=sharing">Connect Church brand book</a>  <a href="https://open.life.church/items/122018-lifechurch-branding-guidelines-pdf">Life.Church style guide</a>  <a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/13n6x8fXr0I2RXAzFmzUcn-NVeB9Qqivv/view?usp=share_link">Village Church style guide</a>', 'Work with your branding company to translate your church''s story and identity into a visual brand.  This action is complete when you have the logo files and brand style guide in-hand.', 'template: standard  2017-10-27 content and links updated --pb  2019-12-09 content updated --pb  2020-06-08 new sample & resource bullet points added --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 98& to 95 --pb&  2022-11-21 links updated --sc ', 4, 'todo', 94, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('d42c1aef-6728-5eaf-9fc3-98db7128b5c9', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a tagline', 'Summarize your church''s identity and brand promise in a short tagline.', 'The tagline is a short motto or saying that conveys your church''s identity and brand promise. It''s usually 10 words or less (shorter is better), memorable, distinct, and catchy. It will become the mantra of the new congregation.  Your tagline should flow from your Vision Frame (see previous PlanterPlan task). Your tagline is a key piece of your brand identity that literally says something about who you are. The other pieces of your brand identity stimulate the emotion through images (logo, font, color, etc...). The tagline is your chance to use words to communicate succinctly who you are. These may be 6 of the most powerful words you speak.  Here are sample church taglines that are already taken:  No perfect people allowed  Church for the rest of us  A place to discover God', 'Brainstorm potential themes for taglines.  Group and prioritize similar concepts.  Discuss with some unchurched friends what concepts they relate to.  Develop a short tagline which communicates to not-yet-believers that key piece of vision you want them to know about your church.  Test the finished product with the unchurched and seek their feedback on what the tagline communicates to them. Make adjustments as necessary.  This action is complete when you have finalized the church''s tagline.', 'template: standard  2017-10-27 content updated --pb  2019-12-09 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 98& to 81 --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 80, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('91f115a9-fcf4-5f8a-9997-c314340a84e0', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Design your logo', 'Create a logo that encapsulates your church''s brand for use in your community.', 'A logo helps people quickly connect all your marketing efforts to your church. Your logo is a key part of your brand and should be included in your style guide (see previous PlanterPlan action). It may be the single most distinguishable part of your brand.  Consider Google and Starbucks. You can see the Starbucks logo in your mind right now, can''t you?  Your logo should tell a story and capture the feel of your congregation. And no, not every church logo must include both a cross  and  a dove.  Check out this super-helpful <a href="https://www.companyfolders.com/blog/design-perfect-business-logo-infographic">How to Design the Perfect Business Logo</a> infographic.  Work with your branding company back and forth through several rounds of concepts and revisions.  More than Just One Logo  But you need more than just one logo. You need the same logo in 12 variations so you can use it in different contexts:  the primary logo (typically in color and landscape-oriented)  the reverse logo (if your logo is light-colored, this will be a dark version, and vice versa)  the primary logo in B&W  a reverse B&W  a square version (color)  a square reverse  a square in B&W  a square in reverse B&W  just the icon in color (no words, just the ''mark'')  just the icon in reverse color  just the icon in B&W  just the icon in reverse B&W  And more than that, you''ll want the source file for each of these along with a JPG and PNG version of each. Yes, that''s 36 files!', 'Hammer out the logo with your branding company.  Make sure you get all the versions and file types you''ll need.  Save the original source files to your computer and to the cloud.  This action is complete once you have backed up the final logo files to the cloud.', 'template: standard  2017-10-27 content updated --pb  2019-10-31 additional resources subsection added--pb  2019-12-09 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 112& to 95& & Duration from 30& to 21& --pb&  ', 6, 'todo', 94, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('39264088-183e-543e-af87-4896d669792d', '99442f16-d1fa-56a6-bd7f-a426977ba176', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Buy branded promo giveaways', 'Develop promotional materials to help communicate that a new church is being started.', 'A great way to get the word out is by buying branded promotional materials. These giveaways can range from bookmarks to frisbees. The idea is to use the promotional materials to help spread the word about the new church.  Initially you may have to order items with no logo. That''s actually OK if you include a website, social media address or other contact information.  Key principles when deciding what to order:  Life Expectancy : frisbees and ink pens might last for years but a disposable water bottle will get tossed the same day (that''s not necessarily bad, but it should inform how much you''re willing to pay per item)  Bulk Discount:  branded promo items are almost universally cheaper when purchased in quantity  Plan Ahead : give yourself the better part of a month for design, production and shipment; rush fees are expensive  Partner with Other Nonprofits : sometimes there are opportunities to co-brand items and split the expense with another group  Set a Budget : you will be developing an overall church planting budget - be sure to include branded promo items  Include Contact Info : it''s easy to overlook, but your website should be on everything you print  Branded promo items to consider:  <a href="https://www.gotprint.com/products/club-flyers/order.html">club flyers</a>  <a href="https://www.4imprint.com/sale?ss=pen">ink pens</a>  <a href="https://www.4imprint.com/sale?ss=balloon">balloons</a> (don''t forget the helium)  fidget spinners  disposable water bottles (custom branded or apply your own waterproof stickers)  t-shirts  sportpack, tote or shopping back  sunglasses (make sure they block UV)  Find a local vendor to order branded promotional items from. This will help you meet new people in the community and may save you on shipping costs. But always compare local quotes to the big online outlets to ensure you are getting the most from your dollar.', 'Brainstorm a list of ideas for promotional materials that will connect well in the community.  Contact a local promo company and/or a national group like 4imprint to get some price quotes.  Work with the vendor to get items designed; be sure to include website or other contact information.  Order initial promotional materials.  This action is complete when you have ordered initial promotional materials.', 'template: standard  2017-09-15 content updated --pb  2020-01-24 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 60& to 109& & Duration from 28& to 14& --pb&  ', 7, 'todo', 108, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('699ba2b6-3497-514e-adc0-a85dc04f8ae8', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Create Launch Vision prospectus', 'Create a Launch Vision Prospectus (aka Vision Book) to clarify your vision and provide a resource for your fundraising and Launch Team recruiting.', 'You have been called to plant a church. You have been praying and God has given you a vision that is growing more exciting each day.  You are eager to turn this vision into action.  3 Levels of Detail  There are 3 different launch documents you''ll create that increase in their level of detail:  Launch Vision Prospectus  This is a shorter, big-picture document. It''s intended to be a colorful and compelling quick read that gives prospective donors and Launch Team members a glimpse at the vision of the church plant.  Launch Strategy Document  This is a lengthy document that lays out in detail how you''ll go about launching the new church. It is content-driven with few images, focusing on philosophy, strategies and goals. It''s the business plan to pitch to venture capitalists. Think  Shark Tank .  Launch Plan  The Launch Plan goes further by spelling out specific actions that need to be accomplished to execute the strategies. It also assigns dates and doers for each action. PlanterPlan is your Launch Plan!  The Launch Vision Prospectus  Creating the prospectus will help you focus and refine your vision. It will help you think in stories and pictures, and challenge you to attach some dates and numbers to the project. The printed Launch Vision will become an important tool in your fundraising efforts. It can also be a great piece to hand out at your info nights or at Chamber of Commerce mixers, for example.  Here are the things to include in your Launch Vision content:  Summary information about your target community; consider telling the story of a typical individual or family that lives there  Reasons to plant a church there now  Bio of the planter and picture of the planter''s family  Brief overview of your mission, vision and values (it''s OK if you don''t have the language formalized at this point; get it roughly right)  An overview time line, especially as a graphic  A high-level budget; demonstrate as you''re able that there are already funds committed - people hesitate to be the first one in the water  Endorsements from respected pastors and/or organizations  Clear next steps that the reader can take to get involved  Use the template linked below to assemble your content for delivery to a graphic designer. A professionally designed and printed prospectus may cost a few bucks, but can bring significant returns on the investment.', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Launch Vision Contents Template  (<a href="/resources/item/328">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/369">Google Doc</a>).  Fill in the blanks to craft the content that a designer will use to draft your Launch Vision.  Work with a graphic designer to create a colorful, compelling Launch Vision document.  Ask your coach and several other experienced church planting leaders to review your Launch Vision and give you feedback. Incorporate their suggestions.  Print/produce the final Launch Vision document.  This action is complete when the final Launch Vision document is printed and in hand.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 completely overhauled content from "Launch Plan, including Launch Strategy" to simply the Launch Vision document --pb  2018-07-26 changed title from "vision document" to "vision prospectus" --pb  2018-11-02 content updated --pb  2020-06-24 added ''send to coach'' language --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb ', 0, 'todo', 45, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('222c675f-acb8-59a4-bc35-4a75dbbd6c3b', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up supporter web page', 'Set up a simple initial/preliminary web page to communicate with outside supporters and to accept online donations.', 'By the time you get to the launch of your regular worship gatherings, your church plant website will have gone through several stages. This task walks you through the first stage. Note the other stages so you can transition intentionally instead of accidentally when the time comes.  Your major website stages will take their cues from your changing audience. Whenever you''re writing website content, always ask and remind yourself, "Who''s my audience?" And you''ll have to rewrite your content at least twice.  Stage 1: Your Supporters  Very early in your church planting process, you''re going to need a web page to direct your supporters to. You probably only need a single page, so keep it simple. But a website will be really handy for accepting online donations as you raise funds.  You may not have even named your church yet, so here are some options at this stage:  Get a dedicated page on a supporting church or planting organization''s site  Use drag and drop website builder like <a href="https://www.squarespace.com/">SquareSpace</a>, <a href="https://www.weebly.com">Weebly</a>, <a href="https://mailchimp.com/features/website-builder/">MailChimp</a> or <a href="https://www.wix.com">Wix</a> that assigns you a subdomain (it''ll usually look like mychurchplant.[nameofservice].com)  Buy a temporary domain name to use for a year (like "thecheboyganproject.com") and host your own page  Nobody is going to be stumbling onto your site through internet searches at this stage, so you don''t have to worry too much about SEO (getting found). You''ll send your supporters a direct, clickable link through email or text.  Stage 2: Your Team  As you network in the community and begin gathering a team, you''re going to want a site to establish your credibility. At that point you will need to de-emphasize the ''money talk'' and emphasize vision, community involvement, and recruitment. You''ll write new content addressed not to the community at large, but to people that you''re meeting personally.  The subsequent PlanterPlan task  <a href="/projects/project-tasks/[[project_id]]/all-tasks/1390">Publish simple 1-page website</a>  will walk you through this.  Stage 3: Your Community  Several months before your grand opening of regular worship gatherings, you''ll need to transition the website to its permanent audience: your community.  That is covered in more detail in the subsequent PlanterPlan task  <a href="/projects/project-tasks/[[project_id]]/all-tasks/584">Publish your website</a> .', 'Choose a publication path as described above.  Determine initial content for web page.  Design initial web page. If necessary, find someone to help.  Publish initial page to the internet.  This action is complete when the basic one-page website is up and functioning.', 'template: standard  Need Pat''s review to determine which of these tools/sites to ditch (too old) and which new ones to add based on current technology.&  -----ds  2017-09-15 content updated --pb  2017-09-26 content overhauled; Due in # of Days changed from 49 to 42 to coincide& with other fundraising activities --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed& title from "set up supporter website" --pb  2020-01-26 content updated --pb ', 1, 'todo', 42, 28, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('922b6691-b397-5adc-bf64-7b7256524019', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up online giving', 'Sign up for an online giving solution so that outside supporters and local team members can give electronically.', 'Paper checks may not completely go away any time soon, but having an electronic giving option for your church is no longer negotiable.  Online giving solutions come in many different shapes and sizes designed to meet the needs of all types of churches. Each solution has pros and cons for a church plant.  Pricing  Each provider will charge you with some combination of the following:  Transaction rate - every vendor will charge some percentage of the donation; rates may differ between credit, debit & ACH (bank account) options  Transaction fee - many providers charge a percentage plus 25&cent; or 40&cent; per transaction; again, these may differ between credit, debit & ACH  Set up fee - only a few vendors charge one  Monthly fee - some vendors offer you lower transaction rates & fees offset by a monthly fee  Annual or Compliance fees - some vendors also charge fees annually  A Collision Course  As of 2020, church management software (ChMS) platforms have begun the collision with both online giving and mobile apps. Soon you''ll picking just one provider that does all 3 in an integrated fashion. But there are still some options, so it makes sense to consider even briefly how these will all line up so you can pick solutions that play nice together.  Mobile App Provider In-House Options  Think long game. Many church plants don''t need a church app prior to launch, but knowing your options could line you up to make that easy/er someday. Top picks include:  <a href="https://www.planningcenter.com/church-center">Planning Center Church App</a>  <a href="https://www.subsplash.com/giving">Subsplash</a>  <a href="https://aware3.com/pricing/">Aware3</a>  <a href="https://get.tithe.ly/product/church-giving">Tithe.ly</a>  ChMS Compatible Options  These are the respective providers that integrate with the top ChMS platforms:  Church Community Builder (now owned by PushPay)  full integration option: <a href="https://pushpay.com/">PushPay</a>  options that sync: <a href="https://get.tithe.ly">Tithe.ly</a>, <a href="https://aware3.com/ccb/?utm_source=ccb&utm_medium=uri&utm_campaign=ccbcom">Aware3</a>, <a href="https://www.thechurchapp.org/ccb">Subsplash</a>, <a href="https://gyve.com/">Gyve</a>, <a href="https://www.securegive.com">SecureGive</a>  Planning Center Online  full integration option: <a href="https://www.planningcenter.com/giving">Stripe</a>  options that sync: <a href="https://get.tithe.ly">Tithe.ly</a>, <a href="https://aware3.com/pricing/">Aware3</a>, <a href="https://www.kindrid.com/">Kindrid*</a>, <a href="https://pushpay.com/">PushPay</a>  Tithely CMS (formerly  Elvanto )  full integration option: <a href="https://get.tithe.ly">Tithe.ly Giving</a>  options that sync: <a href="https://www.continuetogive.com">Continue to Give</a>, <a href="https://www.mogiv.com">MoGiv*</a>, <a href="https://pushpay.com">PushPay</a>  Stand Alone Options  There are truly too many to list. The following options may or may not play nice with your other software platforms:  <a href="https://www.onlinegiving.org/">OnlineGiving.org</a>  <a href="https://www.paypal.com/us/non-profit/fundraising/fundraising-online">PayPal Donations</a>  <a href="https://www.authorize.net/">Authorize.net</a>  *These providers have been purchased by the conglomerate <a href="https://www.ministrybrands.com/our-brands/">Ministry Brands</a>:  Kindrid  EasyTithe  eGiving  SimpleGive  Giving Kiosk  MoGiv  EFT Plus  HaloPays', 'Ask around of other church plants and friends in ministry what they think of their online giving.  Consider which platforms will line up best with your church management software.  Consider which platforms will line up best with your long-range mobile app development plans.  Purchase and set up the giving solution that is the best match.  Share online giving options with your launch team and financial supporters.  This task is complete when the first gift has been given through the new online giving platform.', 'template:  New Milestone  2018-08-21 name tweaked --pb  2019-10-14 content rewritten --pb ', 2, 'todo', 73, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('890a9e1c-89eb-5fb7-8a78-328aa54bf136', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop promotional materials for recruiting partners', 'Develop high-quality, first-touch promotional materials that you will use to recruit financial supporters and partners.', 'Create a fundraising packet or kit that you will send to potential partners. Your packet should include basic information about the church plant as well as information about you, the planter.  Be strategic about what you stuff in the envelope. Will you use?:  a letter  a homemade brochure  a professionally printed brochure  a commitment card (this is discouraged; read more in the task  Develop a Donor Commitment Card )  something tactile (see below)  Especially for churches, organizations and other high-capacity givers, consider mailing something 3-dimensional (more than just printed paper). It will significantly increase the ''open rate'' and may lead to more conversations than otherwise. For example, use a padded envelope or small box and include something your target community is famous for. Or include something that demonstrates the need for more churches in your region. Record a video and load it onto an inexpensive thumb drive. Even a simple ink pen in an envelope will get the recipient''s attention. Get creative!  Remember though that the point of a mailing is to set up a meeting or call with the prospect, not get them to make a decision on the spot with no conversation. They need to hear your heart. These packets just buy that opportunity.  If you have children at home, having them help assemble the packets for mailing can be a great way to involve them in the early stages of the church plant!', 'Decide what you''ll put into each fundraising packet.  Write the content for any print pieces and get them printed.  Design and otherwise order creative elements you''ll include.  Assemble the fundraising packets.  This action is complete when several packets are assembled and ready to send out.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content validated --pb  2018-11-02 content updated --pb  2019-12-11 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 42& to 43 --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 45, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('d6ff70a8-339d-5033-882f-8ba4cec9f423', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a donor Commitment Card for your maybes', 'Design and print a commitment card to leave with potential donors  after you''ve met with them  in person or in large groups.', 'A commitment card is a simple tool that is widely used by nonprofits as they solicit donations. You''ve probably seen them in nonprofit solicitations in the mail. They can be printed professionally or on a home computer.  Don''t Lead with It  Don''t mail out a commitment card. Fundraising is about relationships first, not transactions. Whenever possible, make the ask in person. If you start with the commitment card, it potentially sends all kinds of  negative messages:  I''m too afraid to ask you myself  I don''t believe in the vision enough to be bothered  I''m more interested in your money  There''s just too many of you to ask (you''re just a number)  etc.  This also means don''t go into a meeting and hand out a commitment card first thing. They''ll be reading the card instead of listening to you. And again, it could send the wrong message.  Leave your prospects with a commitment card only if they are unable or unwilling to commit to your while you''re still together. Then set an expectation for when you''ll follow up with them to get their commitment.  Do''s  Include the following to increase your commitment card''s effectiveness:  Commitment language stated in the first person; something like, "As God provides, I commit to:" or "For the next 2 years I will:"  White space - leave at least 33% or your card as ''white space'' and it will be much easier to read  Spaces to fill in their contact info  Your phone number and email address so that they can contact you  A short website address (vanity URL) where they can go to give online  Don''ts  Here are some common mistakes and poor design that decrease effectiveness:  Include a prayer commitment option (don''t give them the easy out; make them tell you ''no'')  Use the phrase "One-Time Gift" instead of "Up Front Gift"  Give them a crazy short fill-in line for their email address - it won''t fit  Give them a crazy long website address for online giving (like www.mychurch.onlinegivingprovider.com/246810/church/secure-portal.htm)  Fill up every square inch with text  Make it hard or confusing to get the commitment back to you', 'Have a graphic designer draft your cards, or do it yourself if you have to.  Have the cards professionally printed or print them yourself and cut them apart.  This action is complete when the cards are ready to be handed out or shared online in digital form to potential donors.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated --pb  2018-11-02 content updated --pb  2019-08-09 additional resources subsection created --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 42& to 46 --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 45, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a5b1d911-2097-5151-b1d4-a419471464eb', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Initiate contact with potential partners', 'Open the lines of communication with potential support partners.', 'You need to get past any psychological or emotional barriers and make initial contact with everyone on your potential partners list.  Don''t Spray and Pray  Send letters to everyone on the list in smaller batches so you can follow up in a reasonable amount of time. If you mail 200 letters at once but can only call 40 people a week, it will be as much as 5 weeks (more than a month) before the last donors hear from you! Better to create a rhythm of mailing 40 letters each week and calling on the 40 from the previous week''s mailing.  Decide who on the list is a high-capacity donor to meet with in person. Follow up the letter to those donors with a request for a meeting to share the vision God is calling him to. Remember that money follows vision and relationship, not need.', 'Practice pitching your vision at least 25 times before getting in any situation where you''ll need to pitch it to a potential support partner.  Send out the first communication piece to the first batch of prospects following the instructions in the subsequent child task.  Schedule in-person meetings following the instructions in the subsequent child task.  This action is complete when you have sent a support letter to at least the first 40 prospects on your potential partner list.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 49& to 71& & Duration from 14& to 21& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 70, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('9f7af409-3cd4-5437-85e1-76e8749b5240', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Formalize partner commitments', 'Solidify your relationship and everyone''s expectations by formalizing financial commitments.', 'Especially with support organizations such as church planting groups, denominations or other churches, it may take months of cultivation before a financial commitment is made. There will be lots of communication and intentions in the mean time, but at some point you will want (and should expect) a firm decision. You cannot take good intentions to the bank.  And the timing of the gift is important for you to know, too. If they commit $10,000, there is a huge difference between $1,000 per quarter and $10,000 up front. It''s reasonable for you to ask for specifics once they''ve made a commitment.', 'Continue to follow up with each support organization lead. Do not give up until you get a firm answer one way or the other.  During each interaction, be sure to ask when you can expect a decision and when you should follow up.  Be sure to ask for referrals and leads to other organizations that you should approach for support.  This action is complete when you have received a firm ''yes'' or ''no'' from each support organization you have been pursuing.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content validated --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 60& to 74& & Duration from 30& to 42& --pb ', 6, 'todo', 73, 42, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('1bc38dcc-a37d-575c-b87a-463367b16d02', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Create a schedule for sending ongoing communication to potential partners', 'Keep lines of communication open with every one of your potential supporters whether they have committed to some kind of support or not.', 'Perhaps the worst things you can do in the support raising process is to send one support letter and then never follow up or send any other communication. You never know when the supporter''s circumstances or heart may change. There will be several recipients who are waiting to see if you are serious and willing to follow through. And we could share countless stories of supporters who started sending in support only after having received letters for 4, 5, and 6 months.  You have to be disciplined about sending out communication. It will be easy to put this on the back burner when crunched for time. Relationships with financial supporters are no less important than relationships you develop with the locals. Plan on spending about one full work day each month managing your fundraising process.  Consider this: in terms of return on time invested, spending one day a month on support raising can net several thousand dollars for the ministry each month. That support enables all of the rest of the ministry that happens on the other days of the month. Time well spent.', 'Review your fundraising strategy. Look at the how frequently you have planned to use each communication method.  For each communication method, schedule time on your calendar for accomplishing each. For example, if you have committed to send weekly emails to supporters, schedule a recurring appointment each week on your calendar to accomplish this.  This action is complete when you have scheduled time to create and distribute each method of communication from the fundraising strategy.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content validated --pb  2019-04-23 additional resources subsection added --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb ', 7, 'todo', 45, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('accaead2-5a34-5db3-9fe4-4ec054484cd0', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Add financial partners to your group distribution list', 'Keep financial partners informed about your church and inspired with stories of life change.', 'Good communication is key to keeping financial supporters included and connected. They are your co-laborers in the work of the new church. Keeping them out of the loop or just plain ignoring them doesn''t honor their sacrifice and willingness to buy in to the vision.  Earlier, you chose a communication channel for your intercessory prayer team. Decide whether to use that same tool or something else to keep your supporters in the loop. Options abound:  group email  group SMS  social media (private groups)  group messaging apps  printed letters  etc.', 'Compile the list of all your financial supporters and make sure you have current contact information for each.  Import them into your distribution list (Mailchimp, ConstantContact, group SMS, etc.).  Optional: segment the list by flagging the financial supporters. That way they will be part of the overall list, but you will also be able to send custom emails to just your supporters should the need arise.  This action is complete when each financial supporter is uploaded or input into your group communication channel.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb ', 8, 'todo', 60, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('acf8faff-ea53-54cb-b8fd-07bee08d16ef', '9aec9608-58d8-5be3-9fa8-1ba89313eff1', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Establish an initial donor management system for fundraising', 'Set up a clear, secure, and reliable donations receipt process to honor your donors and comply with IRS requirements.', 'For legal reasons and for accountability, you absolutely must have a clear, secure, and reliable donations receipt process. This includes keeping documentation of who donated what money or goods to the church and what, if anything, they received in return.  To keep the donations coming in, you have to accurately track donations, keep donors informed of church status, and to report the donations (as appropriate) to the IRS. Determine how donations will be tracked and followed up.  Two Main Options  Sponsor: The fast and easy way is to piggyback on another organization''s systems. Often church planting groups or mother churches will handle this process until the church has been launched.  In-House: If that''s not an option, you''ll have to process and track everything in-house. That requires the church to have its own bank account, which in turns requires the church to be legally established in its state. Reference the Milestone that covers legal issues for further help on these steps.  More Than Just Receipts  Once again, fundraising is about relationships. It''s important to keep track of giving so you can provide giving statements, but donor management should be about way more than that. A good donor management system will help you keep track of when you contacted each donor last, what they''ve committed, and space for important notes like birthdays, spouse''s and children''s names, etc.  The long game for your donor tracking will certainly be some kind of church management software (ChMS). Today''s ChMS apps do all of the above, so Passion for Planting recommends getting that started sooner rather than later (see subsequent PlanterPlan task for recommendations).  At the very least, keep everything together in one place, like a doc or spreadsheet.', 'Decide whether to piggyback or process in-house.  If doing it in-house, choose which software to use.  Determine what additional records/copies should be maintained.  This action is complete when you have implemented the donor relationship management system.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content updated --pb  2018-05-07 added& google& doc template version --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb ', 9, 'todo', 60, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('50b45905-56c5-5bea-9002-f503313742b1', '9f197a08-281e-5163-aaad-3779da3b11a4', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this affirming the calling overview', 'Understand the importance of being called to plant a church and how to affirm that calling from God.', 'Before starting a church, you should have a clear calling from God. If there''s  anything  else you can do and be happy, do that instead.  Part of understanding a calling to plant a church is hearing the calling affirmed from other mature Christians. One of the best affirming processes available is a church planter assessment. In the post  <a href="https://churchleaders.com/outreach-missions/outreach-missions-articles/138305-church-planters-who-succeed.html">Church Planters Who Succeed</a>  from ChurchLeaders.com, the first 2 success factors are:  calling, and  assessment  Assessment has become an industry standard. For many church planting networks, it is a non-negotiable.', 'Talk to mature Christians whom you respect. Get their wisdom and ask their feedback on your calling to plant a church.  Talk to peers in ministry and ask their feedback on your calling to plant a church.  Read  <a href="https://voices.lifeway.com/church-ministry-leadership/are-you-actually-called-to-plant-a-church/">Are You Actually Called To Plant A Church?</a>  by Daniel Im  Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="/resources/item/3">Affirm Your Calling</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.  This action is complete after you have finished watching the training video.', 'template: standard  2017-07-28 content updated --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 7 to 1  2022-11-21 Replaced Are You Called To Plant (expired) by Ed Stetzer with the Daniel Im article --sc ', 0, 'todo', 0, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7eae4609-37a9-5338-afbf-8fb41554decf', '9f197a08-281e-5163-aaad-3779da3b11a4', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Select approximate geographic area for new church', 'Identify the approximate geographic area for the new church so you can begin proper planning.', 'God''s call for you to plant a church will include being called to a people and/or a place. In the early stages of the plant, you may not have clarity on  exactly  where to plant, but you need to begin discerning  roughly  where God is calling you if you''re to make any plans. Your approximate geographic area might be a region, a county, or a metro area.  In some cases, the area is chosen by a sending church or church planting network before they even call you to plant with them. In other cases, you may identify the area collaboratively after you''ve been called by the church planting network.  The location you settle on should be informed by prayer and initial demographic profiles/studies. Here are things to consider in selecting a location:  The demographics  - Who lives in the area? Who will you be reaching in the area?  Population density  - How many people of your target demographic live within a reasonable driving distance?  Who you are  - You will attract others like yourself.  Other churches  - What other healthy, growing churches exist in the area?  Growth patterns  - Over the past 5 years, has the area been growing or declining? What are the projections for the next 5-10 years?  Other new churches  - Are other church planting networks targeting the same area? Most church planting networks have a priority list of locations.  God''s calling  - Is The Spirit leading you to a specific place?  Setting  - are your skills and experiences a better match for an urban, suburban, or rural setting?  You will refine your target area in a subsequent PlanterPlan action.', 'Seek God''s counsel for the general area the church is to be planted.  Review and consider the factors listed above.  Select a general area to target for starting the new church.  This action is complete once you have prayerfully selected the general area for the church plant.', 'template: standard  Need to move PPT resource to our server.&  Pat will do.&  --ds  Resource id#236  2017-07-28 content & resource link updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Duration& from 30 to 7 --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb ', 1, 'todo', 6, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('62709b20-dc98-5b4d-82d8-2c39df25fc8e', '9f197a08-281e-5163-aaad-3779da3b11a4', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Assess your calling to church planting', 'Confirm and have rock-solid confidence in your calling to plant a church.', 'Church planting is so difficult that your calling will come into question at least once along the journey. You need to have an unshakable conviction, supported by evidence, that God has called you to plant this church. On the hard days, you will need to point back to that evidence and tell yourself, "This is so incredibly hard, but I know that God has called me plant this church because ______. I am not giving up."  Assessment is a process that will give you that evidence.  You''ll typically go through an initial screening and then travel to an on-site assessment center. It is a multi-day panel interview of you and your spouse. It will culminate in mature Christian leaders giving you verbal and/or written affirmation of your calling.  The following subtasks will guide you to:  Assess your own passion for reaching lost people  Complete self and pre-assessments  Undergo a formal assessment  Get a copy of your church planter assessment report  No circumstance or earthly power will be able to steal away the affirmation you receive. It happened. It is fact.', 'Complete each of the subsequent child tasks.  This action is complete when you have been positively affirmed by an established church planting assessment center.', 'template:  2019-12-03 due date fields found empty --pb  2019-12-03 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 35& to 29 & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb ', 2, 'todo', 233, 220, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('6aa46b22-8776-5a00-9834-a8a9562522f4', 'a11e086c-043b-5749-8119-414c01e8478b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this demographics overview', 'Understand why it''s important to articulate the key distinctives of your community and contextualize the Good News.', 'The language you use, the stories you tell, and the metaphors you employ won''t work in every context. For instance:  Sharing stories about your hunting escapades to an anti-gun crowd  Wearing a suit and tie to church in Hawaii  Saying  y''all  just about anywhere in New England  Talking Yankee-fast and bypassing conversational pleasantries in the South  Having a  cookout  anywhere west of the Rockies  Hosting a  BBQ  anywhere east of the Rockies but serving only hot dogs  More than that, you need to understand what really makes the locals tick. What''s their worldview? What are their idols? And where do you find elements of the Gospel already woven into the community?  Learning your culture and your context is one of the primary jobs in the early days of the church plant. Demographics are a great starting point, especially when when you follow them up with personal investigation and experience.', 'Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="../../../resources/item/271">Understand Your Focus Group</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.  This task is complete when you''ve read the description and listened to the training resources above.', 'template: standard  Valid once videos are transferred over.&  ----ds  2017-09-26 content updated --pb  2019-09-03 additional resources subsection added --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 56& to 30 & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2021-01-28 took out& Additional Resource article Why Contextualization Trumps& Methodology In Church Planting because the link was broken and I couldn''t find it& elsewhere --sc  2022-11-21 updated links --sc ', 0, 'todo', 29, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('81920879-58e4-574b-ba36-d7d09d772f6a', 'a11e086c-043b-5749-8119-414c01e8478b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about exegeting your community', 'Open a conversation with your coach about doing the missionary homework required to exegete your community.', 'Making disciple-makers has the power to break through every social, racial and economic barrier. You need to quickly learn how to present the Gospel in a contextual way, one that makes sense to the people in your community.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  The fastest way to understand your community  How to discover the community''s top needs  Describing the average family living in your community  Differentiating this new church from other healthy churches and church plants in the community  Cross-cultural discomfort and apprehension', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about exegeting your community.', 'template: standard  2017-05-30 content updated,  audience changed to coach  --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 56& to 36& --pb ', 1, 'todo', 35, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('34f582ec-a138-57c7-8fe0-4b030c8119cb', 'a11e086c-043b-5749-8119-414c01e8478b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Define your target area', 'Maximize your impact by drawing a boundary line around the geography where you will concentrate your evangelism and your outreach, community service & marketing resources.', 'You don''t have unlimited resources. As much as you''d like to do everything and serve everyone, you won''t have enough money and manpower to do it.  At this point, you''ve already identified your approximate geographic area. You know which city, metro area or region you''ll be planting in. But even that geography is too broad to reach everyone.  So you''ll have to make some tough choices. It''s better to focus your resources like a laser than to spread yourself thin like a shotgun spray.  Defining your target area is a back-and-forth process of refining your understanding about:  the people group God has called and equipped you to reach (average target family)  where they live (geography)  where there are available facilities for worship gatherings  You will want to refine your target area in parallel with crafting your Target Area Report (see subsequent PlanterPlan action).  As you learn more about your adopted people group(s), you will have a better understanding of where they live. As you learn more about your community, you will have a better understanding of where your people group is concentrated.  Plot out the things you''re learning either on a large paper map or an online digital map. Pray that the Spirit would reveal common patterns and connections that make it clear which side of town or specific geography to focus your initial efforts on.  When you''re done with this action, you''ll have a literal boundary drawn on a literal map. It will be the area where you''ll commit to focus your time, talent & treasure in the early years of the church. That''s not to say that you can''t ever do anything outside of the target area, given compelling circumstances. But your default will be reaching the people group God has called you to within that geography.  However, all the demographics in the world are meaningless without God''s calling. God''s leading should not be put aside for better demographics. The demographics are a great indicator of your potential impact, but ultimately if God is leading you to a different area, you must follow His will. Bathed this entire process in prayer.', 'Review all the data you''ve collected & validated to this point.  Get counsel from your coach and others that are familiar with your situation.  Seek God''s will for whom you are to target.  Draw a literal boundary on a map defining where you will target your resources.  This action is complete when you understand your target area well enough to draw a line on a map surrounding it.', 'template: standard  2017-10-23 content updated --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb ', 2, 'todo', 77, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0c04f5fc-2aca-5f9a-a65b-0fd18991526b', 'a11e086c-043b-5749-8119-414c01e8478b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Target Area Report', 'Produce a summary report documenting your demographic findings and cultural exegesis.', 'To get a full picture of your target area and average target family, you must answer the following questions:  Who lives there?  What is their worldview?  What hobbies, personal preferences and values do they have? And what are both the felt needs and real needs?  What is important locally (e.g. golf, aviation history, etc)? What history, heritage and other local factors shape this (e.g. location of the annual Master''s Golf Tournament, home town of the Wright Brother''s, etc)? What are the ''hot topics'' that either divide or unify people there?  Where and how is the city planning to grow?  How many dwellings are in the geography?  What are the commuting and major traffic patterns? Where are the major commercial and retail stores locating to?  What other churches are in the area? Any other new churches starting? Location? Reputation? What real and felt needs are they trying to meet? How effectively? Style? Niche?  What is the media writing about the area?  Which businesses are influencers in the region?  How are the neighborhoods different?  What is the spiritual temperature?  You''ll work through these questions in the subsequent subtasks here in PlanterPlan.  After completing each of the subtasks, compile the results into a written Target Area Report. This biography of your community will be used in formulating your church''s Vision Frame (subsequent Milestone in PlanterPlan).  Also pull in information learned through the community needs assessment (covered in the  Networking  milestone here in PlanterPlan).', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Target Area Report Worksheet  (<a href="/resources/item/345">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/380">Google Doc</a>).  Work through each of this task''s subtasks.  Compile and summarize your results.  Send your completed Target Area Report to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have written a descriptive Target Area Report.', 'template: standard  2017-10-23 task updated --pb  2017-10-23 title changed --pb  2018-06-01& gdoc& template added --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Duration from 45& to 77& --pb ', 3, 'todo', 91, 77, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('1a446b6c-d9f3-569a-a76f-f25db1694a4c', 'a11e086c-043b-5749-8119-414c01e8478b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm demographic findings', 'Ensure that both the planter''s Target Area Report and Average Target Family documents are thorough and actionable.', 'The Target Area Report should include hard demographics, soft demographics, and the results of surveys and personal interactions in the community.  The Average Target Family can be narrative or bullet points, but it needs to be thorough enough to get inside their heads and hearts.  After you, the Coach, have reviewed the planter''s Community Profile and Average Target Family documents, provide the planter with feedback. Challenge the planter to do more research, and/or confirm that the planter is a good match to reach that specific target.', 'Reviews the planter''s Target Area Report and Average Target Family documents.  Provide feedback to the planter as appropriate.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Target Area Report and Average Target Family documents.', 'template: standard  2019-11-25 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 97& to 99& --pb ', 4, 'todo', 98, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('4e936397-a3e6-5f71-883c-40d54e3c2507', 'a11e086c-043b-5749-8119-414c01e8478b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Describe the gospel in your context', 'Define how the good news of Jesus changes everything in your context.', 'The gospel of Jesus never changes, even though it can be defined in many different ways. Simply put the gospel is the good news that Jesus has bridged the gap between God and man. However, good news is only good news because of bad news. The bad news is sin not only resulted in separation between man and God, it''s also led to a breakdown in every other relationship in the world. Since sin, the bad news, is felt all throughout our world, so too must the gospel. It ought to saturate every crack and crevice of our broken world as well.  The role of a church planter is to communicate the gospel in a way that it becomes good news in their life and transforms them. Since sin has infected every human heart and has also spilled over to infect entire communities and cultures your goal as a church planter is just to preach good sermons, baptize people, and send them out with the reassurance that their sins have been forgiven. You get to invite your people to partner with God as he restores all things through Jesus.  For instance, if your community is segregated and divided by racial tension, your church can take the gospel to the community by working to heal these divisions, so the community experiences the reconciling power of God''s grace. If half of your community is addicted to heroin, the gospel your church can offer the community should speak to freedom from drug addiction. If half of your community is divorced, your church can help people find healing and train people to love each other like Christ loves his bride.  The gospel is not just Jesus died on the cross from your sins, so you can go to heaven someday. The gospel brings heaven to earth. For this to happen it must be contextualized to penetrate the darkness starting in people''s hearts and spilling over into their community.', 'Read <a href="https://gccollective.org/article/relevance-is-not-the-primary-goal-of-contextualization/">Relevance Is Not The Goal of Contextualization</a> by Brian White  After studying your community think about what aspects of your community don''t reflect the Kingdom of God. What''s broken in your community that the gospel of Jesus can fix (marriages; poverty; homelessness; racism; drug addiction; promiscuity; etc.)?  Write out (either in a list or a paragraph) how you see the gospel mending what''s broken and offering your community hope.  This action is complete once you have written out that description of the gospel''s ramifications in your context.', 'template:  ', 5, 'todo', 98, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c9d2c7ff-a731-5eb8-b09e-2619061c5c2a', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this marketing implementation overview', 'Execute your marketing strategies so that everyone you''ve been interacting with in the community gets invited to the launch of worship gatherings.', 'Marketing your church''s grand opening of worship gatherings is both a sprint and a marathon. Some media you selected may be months in the execution. You''ve got one chance to celebrate the launch of your worship gatherings. Now is the time to make the most of it.  Marketing done poorly will hurt you. Put the time and effort into the design process to ensure all your marketing efforts are coordinated and effective.  Delegate as much as possible. There are many things in church marketing your capable staff and volunteers could do well so you can spend your time building teams, investing in leaders, and staying out in the community.', 'Put important design, production and delivery deadlines on your calendar.  Delegate as many tasks as possible.  Follow up with all marketing actions to be sure that they are carried out on time and within budget.  This action is complete when you have an accountability process in place and have pulled the trigger on all of your marketing media.', 'template: standard  2017-05-15 overwrite legacy "press release" content with new online review content --pb  2017-05-15 changed "due in # of days" from 231 down to 171 to push it earlier in the process --pb  2018-08-02 updated bing & apple maps with strikethroughs& --pb  2019-12-11 additional resources subsection added --pb  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  2020-05-29 ''disappearing reviews'' section added, image added --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 171& to 196& & Duration from 14& to 30& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 166, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('adbc3016-1383-5bbc-a053-fa0d0a21cc7f', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get 50 professional photos of team members and events', 'Capture high-quality photos at launch team events and gatherings to highlight in your marketing efforts.', 'You want to be able to share your church''s story with your community. While you''ll be able to do this through personal conversations, you''ll also be able to do this through various mediums like your website, social media and other marketing tools. Since a picture is worth a thousand words, it''s helpful to have high quality photos of your team to help you share your story with the community.  From your very first team gathering have a photographer snaps some pictures of you and the team. Whether it''s at a Bible study, a community service event, or a launch team party, make sure you''re capturing these events with photos.  Unfortunately, there are many new churches that have to fill their website and social media platforms with stock photos because they overlooked this task. Their website ends up looking like a Sears catalog, instead of a unique, authentic, life-giving spiritual community. Don''t settle for bland marketing. Share what''s really going on with your church through photography.', 'Identify someone on your team or a friend who''s a professional photographer.  Ask them to come to some of your first events to take pictures.  Get 50 pictures from the photographer showcasing your events that you can use for marketing purposes.  This action is complete when you have these 50 photos.', 'template:  ', 1, 'todo', 97, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('224c75c5-b7f3-514c-addc-84242a976760', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Finalize your marketing schedule and budget', 'Lay out a calendar and budget for the specific marketing methods you are committing to.', 'Previous PlanterPlan tasks walked you through brainstorming marketing methods you might use. This task helps you commit to specific methods through the lens of time and money.  There are lots of free ways to get the word out. Use those  and  commit some of your church plant budget to a few paid media. It matters a lot less what your total budget is if you set yourself up to be your community''s best-kept secret.  Timing is important not only for being strategic about the window of delivery, but also for cash flow. For example, if you have a $10,000 donation coming in September, but you need to pay a bill for marketing in August, you might have a problem.  By scheduling each marketing method and determining how much it costs, you can determine if the timing works within the overall budget of the church.', 'Download Passion for Planting''s Marketing Plan Template (<a href="/resources/item/391">Google Doc</a>) and fill in the specifics for each of the marketing methods you have decided to use.  Make sure the amounts you need to spend  and when  are already covered in your church budget. If not, work with your oversight team to approve a new budget or to approve extra-budgetary spending.  Confirm that the church''s projected cash flow is still healthy after adding these expenses to the budget.  This action is complete when you have clear design & productions deadlines on a calendar and have confirmed that your cash flow supports the timing of your media buys.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 created Debugle& trouble ticket for content overwrite error --pb  2017-04-02 updated the description from backup -- dp  2017-12-15 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 149& --pb&  &  2019-12-23 content updated --pb  ', 2, 'todo', 150, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('ab8301bc-6bcf-5063-84e5-7d3105209622', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Publish your website', 'Publish and promote your website as the front door and first impression of your church.', 'Now that you have written all the content and worked with your designer to customize your site and build out its functionality, it''s time to publish your site and announce it to the world!  As soon as it goes live, make sure to update all the church''s social media pages with the website address. Celebrate its launch across social media with your friends and followers. Make sure you include the website address on everything your print, publish or brand going forward.', 'Build out the site''s menu and page structure  Paste your content in to each page (paste raw, unformatted text; pasting from MS Word will ruin your site)  Select stock photos, custom photos and/or videos  Optimize your site for search engines  Publish your site  Link your church social media pages to the new site and vice versa  Publish fresh, ongoing content regularly to your site (blog, pictures, etc.)  This action is complete when you''ve published and announced your website that appeals to your target audience.', 'template: standard  2017-11-16 content updated --pb  2019-12-09 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 135& to 105& & Duration from 14& to 21& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 226, 183, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('49e3b758-4630-5736-84ec-bf015921b6cc', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Kick off Facebook campaign', 'Create an integrated, ongoing approach to interacting with individuals and your community through Facebook.', 'Facebook is the world''s most popular social media app. And as you''ve experienced, it changes all the time.  But first and foremost, it''s meant to be about people interacting.  "Facebook is no longer just a stage for making announcements. It''s your coffee table for building relationships." - <a href="https://churchm.ag/new-facebook-news-feed-will-affect-church-pages/">ChurchMag</a>  Facebook Building Blocks  You''ll need each of the following:  Your own personal account (do NOT create a profile with first name "[Name of]" and last name "Church"!)  A church Page  At least one Group related to your church Page  You will log is as yourself, then create the Page and Group(s) which will set you as an admin for each of them. You can add other people on your team as admins to the Page and Group(s) as appropriate.  The 2018 Newsfeedpocalypse  Facebook is a marketing company masquerading as a social media platform. They make their billions from advertisers paying to put their ads and boosted content in your newsfeed. Several years prior, Facebook already intentionally reduced the amount of posts/content from businesses in people''s newsfeeds. So they could increase ad revenue.  But so many people complained about the number of ads and boosted posts in their newsfeeds that Facebook reduced that even further at the beginning of 2018. Basically, even if a user has ''liked'' and even then ''followed'' your church Page, nothing you post to your church Page will show up organically in their newsfeed. It is pay to play.  Content is Still King  But you still need to have a church Page because that''s where people will check you out before their first visit.  Your best bet is to post videos, ''go live'' and start conversations. Engaging content that goes viral is your best bet for showing up organically in your fans'' newsfeeds. Bullhorn-style announcements are dead.  Create a rhythm for regularly posting content. Your church should be posting several times a week - but you can create the posts in batches and schedule them to publish throughout the week.', 'Find your favorite churches'' and nonprofits'' Pages and learn from what they''ve done well.  Create a Facebook Page for your church.  Create at least one Group to complement your Page.  Recruit an outside support or Launch Team member to manage and post content to both.  This action is complete when a Facebook Page and Group have been created for the church and a first post is made.', 'template: standard  2017-12-15 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 149& & Duration from 22& to 35& --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 226, 183, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('2b105712-8701-5f78-9822-8532c1d58aa3', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get listed on Google, Yelp and Apple Maps', 'Make your church easy to find online by getting listed on various directory sites.', 'As a brand new church with no previous digital footprint, search engines will need a little help finding you before they''ll serve your website and information up for people to find.  One of the best ways to do that is get listed on the sites where people already go to look for things.  Getting your church listed on these directories should be a non-negotiable:  <a href="https://www.google.com/business/">Google My Business</a> (for Google Maps)  <a href="https://www.bingplaces.com">Bing Places</a>  <a href="https://businessconnect.apple.com/">Apple Maps</a>  <a href="https://business.yelp.com/">Yelp</a>  If you have a capable volunteer, you may want to get listed on these directories as well:  <a href="https://www.churchfinder.com/church-staff/register">ChurchFinder</a>  <a href="https://www.churchangel.com/members/">Church Angel</a>  <a href="https://marketing.yellowpages.com/en/claim-your-listing?from=advertise-with-us-YP">Yellowpages</a>  <a href="https://www.whitepages.com/">Whitepages</a>  <a href="https://www.yellowbook.com/">Yellowbook</a>  <a href="https://advertise.local.com/">local.com</a>  <a href="https://www.citysearch.com/aboutcitysearch/advertise_with_us">City Search</a> [not free]  Postcard Validation  At least Google Maps and Bing Places will mail a postcard to the address you provided as an anti-fraud measure. For most church plants, that means the postcard is being addressed to the church but being mailed to the theater or school where you''ll hold worship gatherings. So wait until you''re on good terms with your facility''s management and give them a heads up that the postcard is coming.  KEEP GOOD RECORDS  Make a list of every site where you added the church and any logins that were created to post those listings. If you ever change your worship gathering location, phone number, web address, etc. you''ll need to go back and update each one of your listings. Otherwise, the old information will linger and haunt you for years.', 'Place free listings on the bare minimum 4 directories above.  Make sure they are set up in such a way that the church is notified of anyone online reviews or comments.  Consider finding a volunteer to place listings on other directories as well.  Keep records of every site and every login created.  This action is complete when the church has been listed on at least the 4 non-negotiable online directories.', 'template: standard  2017-11-17 content updated --pb  2018-01-26 additional resource added --pb  2020-06-15 additional resource added --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 105& to 142& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 165, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b3c8ca3e-4710-5028-aac6-54134f1be9cb', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Jumpstart online ratings and reviews', 'Raise the church''s website ranking by getting 50 reviews on  each  of a few important websites.', 'The democracy of the internet is significant in getting your website found. Search engines aren''t just looking for your website content; they''re trying to corroborate its credibility by looking for:  social media references  other websites that have linked to the church site  map listings  online ratings and reviews  Another PlanterPlan task walks you through getting the church listed on several prominent directory-type websites. One of the first, best things you can do is to get your team to write positive but honest reviews on:  Google Business (Google maps)  your church''s Facebook page  Yelp!  Initially, you need  at least 6 positive reviews  on each of these directories; but probably not the same  exact  six reviews just copied & pasted.  On an ongoing basis, you''ll need about 10:1 positive reviews to negative reviews. Consider posting a grace- and love-filled response to each negative review to demonstrate that the church is listening and that it cares.  Disappearing Reviews  Especially on Yelp!, if your team member creates a new account to leave the review and then doesn''t use Yelp! any further, the review will likely be pulled down as fraudulent. So if your team member is creating a new online account to leave a review, coach them to leave other reviews for their favorite restaurants, shops, etc, to establish credibility as a reviewer.  Press Releases  In your local context, if your city, town or community has an online newspaper or community blog that is widely read, also consider submitting a press release to announce an outreach event or the grand opening. For an example, read <a href="https://www.fredericknewspost.com/news/lifestyle/religion/church-for-the-rest-of-us-collective-church-brings-alternative/article_c45fc11c-f62f-5477-bb60-5a6b00017dfa.html">this online article</a> that stemmed from a press release.  A Case Study  An established church finally got around to doing this only to find that on Yelp! there was already one review of the church. It had been posted 2 years prior and was extremely negative of the church. How many people decided not to visit that church because of that negative review? They will never know.', 'Confirm that your directory listings are live and accurate.  Invite team members to leave reviews and ratings on the sites above; avoid having the exact same reviews by the same people on every site.  Confirm that the church is getting notifications when each of the reviews are posted.  This action is complete when at least 6 positive reviews have been posted on  each  of the sites above.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' --pb  2017-12-15 content updated --pb  2018-02-09 vendor subsection added --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 215& to 227& --pb&  2019-08-30 Truth Advertising replaced with MailWorks --pb  2018-03-16 additional resources subsection added --pb  &  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  ', 6, 'todo', 195, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c3997b91-2d5e-5026-95ed-b6e3f186d4b8', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up online re-marketing ads', 'Reach people in your community through targeted online ads.', 'Types of Online Ads  There are two basic types of online ads regardless of which site you post them on:  cost-per-thousand viewable impressions (CPM or vCPM) and  pay-per-click (PPC)  With CPM, you set a price you''re willing to pay for each 1,000 views of your ad. This is an effective strategy to increase your brand awareness.  With PPC, you do not pay unless someone clicks on your ad. This is a better strategy if you want to drive people to your church website  Pricing  Online ads are priced through a bidding system: you compete against other advertisers for your ads to show up to a specific audience.  First, you''ll define and refine your audience based on geography and even demographic information.  Then within that audience you''ll place your bids on specific keyword phrases. To figure out which keywords to bid on, ask yourself, "What will people be googling when we want our ads to appear?" or, "What keywords on their profile should trigger our ad?" There''s an art to picking keyword phrases and you may have to experiment a little.  Lastly, you''ll set a budget for your entire campaign and/or a daily budget, then a max price per click or impression. If you bid higher than your competitors, your ads will appear for your audience. If you spend through your daily budget, your ads will stop appearing for that day.  $10,000 per Month in Free Ads  Once you get your church''s 501c3 Determination Letter back from the IRS, you may be eligible for <a href="https://www.google.com/nonprofits/">Google for Nonprofits</a>. Among other things, they offer nonprofits $10,000 per month in free ads. For real!  Messaging  Your first instinct may be to promote the grand opening of your worship gatherings. While this is helpful, chances are good that these ads will reach already-churched people looking for a church. Consider placing ads around community needs.  For example, if you are doing a <a href="https://www.ramseysolutions.com/ramseyplus/organization">Financial Peace Seminar</a>, place ads that target an audience searching online about debt, financial advisors, credit cards, foreclosure, etc.  You could also place ads around felt-need sermon series such as parenting, marriage or sexuality. These types of ads are more likely to reach a non-churched audience.  Advertising Sites  Top advertising sites include:  <a href="https://adwords.google.com/home/#?modal_active=none">Google Adwords</a>  <a href="https://www.facebook.com/business/ads">Facebook Ads</a> (different than boosting a post, which is also a great idea)  <a href="https://business.instagram.com/advertising">Instagram Ads</a>  <a href="https://business.twitter.com/en/advertising.html">Twitter Ads</a>  Track and Refine  When you place online ads, be sure that you are tracking their effectiveness. You''ll be provided analytics/metrics so that you can measure the results from your ads. Without measuring your effectiveness, you could be throwing money away without even knowing.  Consider placing multiple ads, so that you can determine which ones are most effective.', 'Set your online ad budget.  Determine which sites to place ads on.  Design and write the ads.  Publish the ads.  Develop a plan for evaluating the effectiveness of the ads.  This action is complete when you have placed targeted online ads.', 'template: standard  2017-12-29 content updated --pb  2018-11-19 content updated, title changed from "Develop a Discipleship Strategy"& --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 147& to 67& & Duration from 44& to 21& --pb&  ', 7, 'todo', 211, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('6fd27733-21a8-55f0-ab4c-bba7b675ffc5', 'a6f1d38b-6e68-5a78-825c-495ff8a01366', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Conduct your mass marketing campaign', 'Plan and execute your mass marketing method(s) as broad ''air support'' for your ground campaign.', 'One of your methods for getting the word out needs to be a mass marketing medium that blankets the community. Physical media that get to every door is still a powerful way invite people to the launch of your worship gatherings.  Mass marketing is generally more expensive but requires no/low time investment from your team.  It''s critical to establish name recognition in the community prior to spending the money on a mass marketing campaign. If the first time they''ve heard of your church is reading the marketing piece, chances are high that it''s going right in the trash.  But if they get it and say to themselves, "Oh yeah, this is that church I ran into at the ______," it can be a very effective deal closer.  Direct Mail  Strongly consider conducting a direct mail campaign prior to the launch of worship gatherings. For many, it''s one of the most expensive things they do during pre-launch. And many planters will tell you that it''s one of the most effective things they did to invite people to the grand opening.  Hire a company that specializes in church direct mail. They''ll walk you through the entire process and make sure everything gets done on time for the least possible cost. And you''ll be able to sleep at night.  Here are some companies that have served our planters in the past:  <a href="https://outreach.com/p4p">Outreach Marketing</a> --> <a href="https://www.d2design.com/">D2Design</a>  <a href="https://mailworksii.com">MailWorks II</a>  Door Hangers  Depending on your context, door hangers put on every door may get you as high or higher a return on investment.  Work with your graphic designer to design the door hangers and have them printed yourself at shops like:  <a href="https://www.gotprint.com/products/door-hangers/order.html?fid=2682165">gotprint.com</a>  <a href="https://www.printdirtcheap.com/en/door-hangers/categories/">printdirtcheap.com</a>  THE TRAP  in using door hangers is wanting to save money by using your Launch Team to put them out. Don''t. You''ll keep them so busy with door hangers that they will neglect outreach & inviting. So your two viable options are:  recruit a missions team or youth group from a supporting church  hire out the delivery from reputable vendors like <a href="https://www.gotdelivered.com">gotdelivered.com</a>', 'Commit to establish broad name recognition in the community through a "6 to stick" approach prior to spending significant money on a mass marketing campaign.  Contract with vendor(s).  Make sure you understand important deadlines and add them to a calendar with reminders.  This action is complete when you have finalized the mass marketing campaign with the vendor.', 'template: standard  2017-12-22 content overhauled --pb&  2020-01-24 content & links& validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 215 to 212& & Duration from 21& to 14& --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 226, 60, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('81d42006-9ee5-5d7e-956d-ce6e24077985', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Purchase church management software', 'Select and purchase church management software to collaborate with your team, track important metrics, and communicate with people.', 'Whether it''s done intentionally or accidentally, keeping ministry information to yourself creates a silo that prevents other staff and key volunteer leaders from being included in ministry. Instead of each leader having their own information silo, wouldn''t it be great if there was a ''shared brain'' where important information could be securely stored & shared?  Enter Church Management Software (ChMS)  A good ChMS platform is built to do that and much more:  Compile a fuller picture of each person''s life story and discipleship journey through:  marking major life events  recording prayer requests and private pastoral notes  displaying a history of their involvement in various teams and groups  Keep track of everyone''s contact information  Track giving history for year-end giving statements (and even facilitate online giving)  Organizing and tracking small groups  Create and manage volunteer serving schedules  Standardize and reinforce repeatable people processes (like guest followup)  Produce reports that reveal the church''s effectiveness at accomplishing its mission  A Collision Course  As of 2020, ChMS platforms are well into a collision course with 2 other church software tools: online giving and mobile apps. It makes sense to consider even briefly where you might want to end up with these other two so that you can pick a ChMS that will be compatible.  Power vs. Ease of Use  The other big determining factor is choosing between power and simplicity. A more powerful ChMS comes with more features and, often, a level of complexity that requires more training and patience of your staff & volunteers. A simpler, easier-to-use system can be easier for your team to adopt, but may come with limitations that prevent it from doing some of the advanced things you really need it to.  So choose between a complex system that risks not getting used and a simple system that risks frustrating you with its limitations.  Top Picks  Passion for Planting recommends the the following ChMS solutions:  <a href="https://www.planningcenter.com/">Planning Center</a> -  <a href="https://www.planningcenter.com/use-cases/church-planters">Click here to apply for Church Planter discount</a>  <a href="https://pushpay.com/">Push Pay (formerly Church Community Builder)</a>  <a href="https://get.tithe.ly/product/church-management">Tithe.ly ChMS (formerly Elvanto)</a> - an early 3-in-1 "collision-course" solution  <a href="https://faithteams.com/">FaithTeams</a>  <a href="https://go.churchteams.com">Church Teams</a>  Others to consider include:  <a href="https://www.acstechnologies.com">Realm</a> by ACS Technologies  <a href="https://www.rockrms.com">Rock RMS</a> (open source, self-hosted)  <a href="https://www.breezechms.com/">Breeze ChMS</a>  Supplemental Software  Here are a few other software solutions to consider that aren''t a ChMS, but have specific functionality that may supplement your ChMS:  <a href="https://textinchurch.com">Text in Church</a> (guest followup)  <a href="https://churchmetrics.com">Church Metrics</a>', 'Determine your feature requirements.  Research various ChMS solutions; consider sitting through sales demos and/or test-driving software.  Get recommendations from other church plants and friends in ministry.  Sign up for your top ChMS choice.  This action is complete when you''ve purchased a church management software solution.', 'template: standard  2017-12-26 content updated --pb  2018-11-16 content updated to match Greg Curtis'' content in our strategy template --pb  2012-12-02 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 137& to 155& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 73, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c76059cb-2729-5e69-b694-1c1a6d90cd61', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Build out followup processes in church management software', 'Customize the church management software settings and infrastructure so that it is ready, then empower and train your key leaders to use it.', 'Your church management software (ChMS) is powerful and solves many challenges of a new church that doesn''t have a physical church office. If all you do with the ChMS is keep contact information, you have a very expensive address book on your hands.  Recruit someone to be your ChMS champion and empower them to  spend time setting it up the way your church will use it. ChMS solutions aren''t written  only  for church plants, so there will be features that you will use, and some you won''t (like room and equipment reservations).  At a minimum, you need to set up the following processes:  Assimilation Processes  - Take the assimilation strategy and incorporate it into the ChMS. Its workflow or process queues will prompt you to take next actions steps to follow up with guests and new members.  Small Groups Processes  - Each small group should be entered into the ChMS. Record key information such as group leader, participants, time of meeting, and meeting location. In addition, develop a process to follow up with people that expresses interest in small groups.  Ministry Team Processes  - Each ministry team should be entered into the ChMS. Record key information such as team leader, serving roles, team members, etc. In addition, develop a process to follow up with people that expresses interest in serving on that team.  Church Calendar  - All of the events from the various groups, teams and worship gatherings should roll up to one master church calendar. Figure out how this calendar will get used in conjunction with the church website calendar and any other publicly published calendars.  You will also need to create user accounts for other staff and key volunteer leaders. Your ChMS will allow you to grant them various levels of access to different parts of the software. For instance, not every leader needs access to financial records and giving history.  Lastly, you''ll need to introduce them to the tool and make a case for why it''s important to use. Give them some pointers on how to use it and make sure they know where the help files and training videos can be found so they can train themselves further.', 'Set up assimilation processes in the ChMS, including followup for groups and ministry team interest.  Configure the master calendar.  Create other users and grant them appropriate levels of access.  Provide them live training or point them to help files for their areas of responsibility.  This action is complete when other users have begun using the church management software.', 'template: standard  2017-12-26 content update --pb  2018-01-17 new blog resource link added --pb  2018-11-19 content updated --pb  2019-12-05 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 168& to 171 --pb  ', 1, 'todo', 170, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('e858de4f-bc84-51be-8a18-3b5e1948eac6', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a connection card', 'Draft and print a communication card to be used at worship gatherings as a key element of the assimilation strategy.', 'The connection card (AKA communication card, welcome card) is an important tool in the followup process. If you don''t collect contact information, you won''t be able to follow up with guests. Have an intentional plan for getting the card into everyone''s hands at each worship gathering along with a pen for filling it out.  What to Ask For  Be sure to only include information on the card that you are going to use. People are more sensitive to privacy concerns and and increasingly hesitant to disclose every bit of information you may be asking for.  Place the most important information on the card at the top. Consider adding a check box for ''new contact info'' so that regulars don''t feel obligated to fill out the entire card each week.  Common connection card elements are:  Name  Mobile number  Email  Address  Next steps  Prayer Request', 'Read the brief post <a href="https://chucklawless.com/2015/08/why-i-may-not-fill-out-a-visitors-card-in-your-church/">Why I May Not Fill Out a Visitor''s Card in Your Church</a> by Chuck Lawless  Decide what elements to include on the connection card.  Design the connection card.  Print the connection card.  This action is complete when the connection cards have been printed.', 'template: standard  2017-12-26 content updated --pb  2018-11-19 content updated, title changed from "Schedule Post-launch Newcomer Gatherings" --pb  2019-12-05 content validated --pb ', 2, 'todo', 170, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('df6be1ab-6abf-520f-a5e2-f30fb4f9d46f', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Write guest followup communication templates', 'Write out what each email, text, letter and phone call should say so that followup communication is ready to send.', 'One of the first things your Connections Team should do to build out the assimilation strategy is to write the copy for each planned followup communication. That way the system is ready to fire when they begin practicing followup on guests. They should be practicing on people that show up to launch team meetings and preview services.  The church management software (ChMS) you chose may have placeholder text or factory default messages, but they''ll need tweaking before they''re ready to go out.  Don''t make the mistake one planter did when the very first guests at their preview services got followup emails that said, "Thanks for visiting NameofChurch. Sincerely, NameofPastor."  Wherever possible, include merge fields in the correspondence. That allows you to press send once but each recipient on the list gets an email, text or letter with their first name on it as if it had been personalized to them. Check your ChMS or communication software''s help files and test, test, test.  Include a Call to Action  Each communication, whether it''s an email, text, phone call or whatever, should focus on getting the reader to take one clear next step. That could include:  Follow us on social media  Let us know how we can pray for you  Come to our newcomers event  Leave us an online review  Come back next Sunday  You get the idea. If you include more than one call to action, chances plummet that they''ll take any action at all. Keep it to just one.', 'Write the copy for each followup text, email, letter and phone call specified in the Assimilation Strategy.  Review each to make sure it''s written with the audience in mind.  Review each to make sure appropriate merge fields are included for a personal touch.  Send yourself or a teammate a test of each followup message; review and adjust the templates as necessary.  This task is complete when all of the followup communication has been written and each communication channel has been tested.', 'template: standard  2017-12-26 content updated --pb  2018-11-19 title changed from "Implement Church Mgmt System" --pb  2019-12-03 additional resources subsection added -pb  2019-12-05 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 168& to 171 --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 170, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('ce870ab2-b739-504d-8719-a5a7ec619d14', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up kids'' pre-registration on website', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'template:  ', 4, 'todo', 180, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('6141b719-efd1-5ed0-9063-c14197166391', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Write scripts for announcing guest connections', 'Decide in advance what & how you''ll announce the connection cards and the "One Place" where guests will turn the cards in.', 'The connection card is the weakest link in your followup system. If you don''t get their contact info, it''s going to be pretty hard to follow up.  Be sure to ask people multiple times during the worship gathering to fill out the card. Don''t make the mistake of only mentioning the card during the opening welcome statement! People will come in late and miss the announcement. Find ways to mention the card three or more times during the gathering. For example, mention the card during the opening welcome, during the sermon, and during the announcement time.  Include in your announcement what the church will be doing with the information. Transparency is key to creating trust with the cards.  Also give them clear instructions on how and when to turn the cards in at the "One Place".', 'Review the  Assimilation Strategy  you created in the previous PlanterPlan Milestone.  Consider the typical building blocks of your weekly worship gatherings to determine strategic times to announce the connection cards and the "One Place".  Write at least 2 different scripts for stage announcements and make sure they get to the person doing the announcements.  This task is complete when you have finalized at least 2 announcement scripts for the guest connection process.', 'template:  2018-11-20 new task --pb  2019-12-05 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 52& to 159 --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 177, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('4f54c026-973d-5ecf-8647-47f26844b817', 'aa6cbfb8-f885-5664-8aac-a344cb41f325', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get recurring "One Program" guest connection events on the calendar', 'Calendarize the "One Program" events that will create easy onramps to your church for guests.', 'The "One Program" events you dreamed up in your  Assimilation Strategy  will remain a dream until they get on the church calendar. Plan a rhythm, like second Sundays, so that everyone can count on when the next event will be. It''s also important to get the calendar events published online where people can find them for reference/more information.  Consider inviting a few of your regulars to show up to each event as bridge-builders.', 'Put several meetings on the calendar in the first few weeks after launch.  Put more meetings on the calendar with regular recurrence: once a month, every-other month, etc...  Invite a friend to find the events online to test their accessibility.  This action is complete when an ongoing schedule of "One Program" events have been added to the church calendar.', 'template: standard  2017-05-22 content & resource links updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 217& to 151& & Duration from 180& to 30 --pb  &  &  ', 6, 'todo', 180, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7785ec95-d038-5f5d-82ce-51d6fa4673b7', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this budget and financial systems overview', 'Understand the key processes that make up a solid financial system.', 'Financial controls in the church are aimed at preventing two types of problems:  Actual loss of proper control of finances  Losing money, improper disclosure of personal information, theft, violation of IRS or other legal requirements, writing checks with insufficient funds  Perception of loss of adequate control of finances  Individuals carrying weekly offering through the lobby in a see-through plastic bag, offering left in an unlocked car, church staff renting luxury sports car rather than economy car  Avoiding both of these types of problems is very important. The easiest way to get audited/investigated by the IRS is a public scandal involving money. Worst case scenario, a church can lose its 501c3 status, be fined, and prosecuted. A lack of confidence by members in the church''s ability to manage finances will impact financial giving.  At a minimum, the new church''s financial system should include:  A checking account  Ongoing reconciliation of monthly account statements  Financial accounting including processing and tracking accounts payable (expenses) and accounts receivable (income) (i.e. writing checks and making deposits)  An accountable reimbursement process  Generating ongoing financial reports including cash flow and budget variance  Payroll process for staff (including filing required reports and paying all required taxes)  Maintaining financial records and files  Keeping track of all donations and providing tax receipts  Receiving, counting, tracking and reporting weekly Tithes and Offerings  Each of these processes is covered by a separate PlanterPlan action.', 'Read and understand this action. The development of the processes listed above is covered in subsequent PlanterPlan actions.  This action is complete once you have read the entirety of this task.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content updated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 42& to 37& & Duration from 7 to 1& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 36, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('510d1ca4-c9ee-59bd-a70d-565a03143d6d', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about setting up financial systems', 'Open a conversation with your coach about what needs to be in place for properly handling church finances.', 'If you have already been provided bookkeeping by a sponsoring church or church planting network, you don''t need to call your coach about this.  If you haven''t, initiate a call to your coach about your own arrangements for a bookkeeper.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Lessons the coach learned the hard way  How to insure the integrity of church finances  Typical financial system weak spots  How to work with a virtual bookkeeper  How to recruit a finance team', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about setting up financial systems.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content validated --pb  2017-05-30 audience changed to coach --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  &  ', 1, 'todo', 45, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0bf0bfd4-a25e-5d74-a106-bb99f1f141c4', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read IRS Tax Publication for Churches', 'Gain a better understanding of the benefits and responsibilities of churches under federal tax law.', 'This IRS publication covers:  Tax-Exempt Status and what may jeopardize it  Employment tax  Special rules for compensation of ministers  Record keeping requirements  Tax return filing requirements  Charitable contributions - substantiating and disclosing  IRS''s authority to audit a church', 'Download the free <a href="https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/p1828.pdf">IRS Publication 1828</a>:  Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations  Read the publication  Make any necessary changes to your financial processes based on what you learned  This action is complete once the planter read IRS Publication 1828:  Tax Guide for Church and Religious Organizations .', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content and link validated --pb  2019-12-12 content and link validated --pb ', 2, 'todo', 42, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('5078a912-0f34-5a0f-abe8-9ad973ae03d0', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Buy the Church and Clergy Tax Guide by Richard Hammar', 'Have an easy-to-understand reference book on hand that covers church and clergy tax concerns.', 'This guide will help you:  Determine and properly record pastoral housing allowances  Understand self-employment and social security taxes  ...and much more.', 'Purchase this book online or from a local bookstore.  Read the Table of Contents to get an overview of the Guide.  Keep the Guide for reference in the church office.  This action is complete once you have obtained a reference copy of <a href="https://store.churchlawandtax.com/2023-church-clergy-tax-guide-book/">The Church and Clergy Tax Guide</a> by Richard Hammar.', 'template: standard  2019-12-12 content and link validated --pb  2022-11-21 update link --sc ', 3, 'todo', 42, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('ca052488-c1fc-587f-b6f4-40580249ab13', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a church plant budget', 'Develop an income and spending plan (budget) to focus and prioritize expenses, and to support your fundraising efforts.', 'A budget is a plan for spending money to accomplish God''s will. The process forces you to choose priorities and "put your money where your mouth is". You''ll quickly discover that a budget is really a vision document.  Consider Theology  Before you sit down to hammer out the budget, take a moment to be honest about your attitude(s) toward money. How you handle money and attitudes you''ve developed are rooted in your theology. Or at least, good theology and an honest conversation with Jesus can correct a broken relationship with money.  One of the most dangerous attitudes in the church budgeting process is a scarcity mindset. You may not initially know where the money is coming from, but you can''t take a posture of protection and still plant a healthy church.  Of course, you still want to make wise decisions and not waste money on frivolous spending. But creating a budget based on the vision God is giving you will stretch your faith. And it will often result in your getting a front row seat to God''s miraculous provision.  Common Mistakes  Here are some mistakes that happen a lot in the church plant budgeting process:  vague time frames  not including income projections  not considering cash flow  confusing recurring expenses and one-time startup costs  Fiscal Year  When does your "first year" start? When you move on site? When you come on payroll? January 1 of any given year? Maybe when you launch worship gatherings?  Whether you call it a fiscal year or not, you''ll have one. Being clear on when it starts each year removes any vagueness. Your budget spreadsheet will have 12 columns for each fiscal year.  For simplicity, Passion for Planting recommends using the calendar year as your fiscal year. So your 12 columns run from January to December.  But maybe you want your fiscal year to line up with the anniversary of the launch of your worship gatherings. For instance, if you launch your worship gatherings in September, then your 12 columns will run from September to August for each budget year.  Income  A budget without projected income is just a spending plan. Where is the money coming from?  As you hammer out the budget, even if you don''t know precisely who will be giving how much, you can make some prayerful estimates.  First, break your income into categories or streams of income. Commonly those will be outside support and local giving. You may want to split outside support into two categories: organizations and individuals.  Then you can include commitments you  have  received. And you can enter some local giving estimates based on  per capita  giving and projected attendance figures.  Solvency  After your first pass at the budget, verify that your total expenses each year are less than or equal to your total income each year.  For example, if your expenses for next calendar year are $250k but your projected income is only $200k, you''re headed for a train wreck.  Cash Flow  Having one column for each year of your budget is very handy for summaries and reports. But if you never consider the timing of the income compared to when you need to spend it, you''ll be sorry. You can''t spend the money until it comes in.  An annual budget figure presumes that your income and expenses will each be divided by 12 and spread evenly across the year. That''s not usually how it happens. If you have a donor that''s going to write you a check for $50k to cover your equipment  but not until September , you probably can''t buy the equipment in May.', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Church Plant Budget Worksheet Template  (<a href="/resources/item/25">MS Excel</a> or <a href="/resources/item/366">Google Sheet</a>) or develop your own format.  Follow the instructions in the file:  fill in assumed dates & dollar amounts  tweak income & expense figures  use fundraising  commitments  (not goals)  Double-check the cash flow on the bottom line; make sure there are no negative bank balance projections  Submit the finalized budget to your Management Team or oversight.  This action is complete when the budget has been approved by the Management Team or appropriate oversight.', 'template: standard  2017-05-30 contents & resource links updated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 75& to 50 --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 49, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('67ad108e-8367-5247-848c-0216ce53a9a0', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Open a church checking account', 'Open a church checking account to transact all of the church''s income and expenses.', 'Find a bank that has convenient locations in your community. You may have to stop in from time to time and your team will be dropping deposit bags after worship gatherings.  Some banks still offer free nonprofit accounts, but some banks have seen the high maintenance and low balances associated with nonprofits and don''t offer them any more. Most banks still offer accounts where the fees can be waived by maintaining minimum balances. Shop around for a bank that offers accounts that meet your needs.  If you''re hiring a virtual church bookkeeper outside of your area, consider shopping for a bank that also has a branch near them. They may need to stop in for customer service support as well.  Opening a church bank account is a little different than opening a personal account. With the ever-increasing anti-fraud and anti-terrorism regulations, the bank will be concerned about:  Whether your corporation is a  real  entity or a fraudulent front company  The physical location of the corporation  Whether your corporation is truly a tax-exempt nonprofit  Who the legitimate authorized signers are for the account  Whether those authorized signers have legitimate identification or are impostors  Why your bookkeeper is in another state  To satisfy their concerns, take with you all of the following when you go to open the account:  Your approved Articles of Incorporation and Certificate of Incorporation  The printed EIN issuance letter from the Feds  The physical and mailing addresses of your church  Corporate meeting minutes that include a resolution to open an account with that bank specifically, and with the authorized signers named  The authorized signers themselves - make sure they each have 2 forms of ID  A list of the names & addresses of each Board Member  A list of the names & addresses of the chief corporate officers: president, secretary & treasurer  An opening deposit  IMPORTANT : whenever possible, the church planter and his relatives should  not  be signers on the church accounts. This also means that they cannot have a debit card that accesses the church account, either. It''s not illegal or immoral for the planter to be a signer, but it protects the planter from accusation and suspicion, as well as unnecessary administrative duties.  Lastly, don''t underestimate the value of establishing a working relationship with the banker and/or branch manager, both for the church''s sake and as an evangelistic opportunity.', 'Determine which bank provides the best locations and features.  Find out what documentation they require to open nonprofit corporation account.  Open a checking account in the church name.  This action is complete when the church checking account has been opened.', 'template: standard  2017-05-25 content updated --pb  2018-07-13 content updated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 140& to 58& & Duration from 14& to 7& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 66, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('9f9dece4-4454-50ae-a0ee-92fb30c8c841', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up payroll for staff', 'Take care of all the legal responsibilities associated with paying staff.', 'As a brand new, independent legal entity, you get the dubious privilege of creating entire Human Resource (HR) systems from scratch, including everything that has to be done to hire staff.  The subsequent child tasks will walk you step-by-step through these major requirements:  Completing hiring paperwork  Signing up for payroll processing  Getting tax withholding accounts opened  Getting workers'' comp insurance (if applicable)  The church''s employees depend on the church getting all of this right. And the church depends on getting it right to avoid very real fines and penalties. This is too important to get wrong.', 'Work through each of the subtasks that follow.  Process the first payroll.  This action is complete when employees have received their first payroll.', 'template:  2020-01-24 content updated --pb  ', 6, 'todo', 233, 212, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c4e96790-006f-5dc8-aa55-3995379ec04e', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify or hire a bookkeeper/accountant', 'Formally engage a bookkeeper to process and track all of the church''s financial transactions.', 'You have to have a bookkeeper to keep track of the church finances. Period.  Common options include:  Your church planting network provides one for you  A sponsoring church is willing to keep your books for you (usually only for a season)  A qualified volunteer from your church  Hiring a local bookkeeping firm  Hiring a virtual bookkeeper that specializes in church accounting  To remain above reproach, this person really should  not  be the planter or anyone related to the planter by blood or marriage.  A bookkeeper will perform the following functions for the church:  Reconciling monthly bank account statements  Processing and tracking accounts payable (expenses/writing checks)  Processing and tracking accounts receivable (income/making deposits)  Maintaining an accountable reimbursement process  Generating ongoing financial reports including cash flow and budget variance  Maintaining financial records and files  Tracking Weekly Tithes and Offerings with donor management software  Processing payroll for staff (including filing required reports and paying all required taxes)  Consider these virtual church bookkeeping vendors:  <a href="https://www.luke923ministries.org/bookkeeping-payroll">Luke 9:23 Ministries</a>  <a href="https://belaysolutions.com">Belay</a>  <a href="https://www.startchurch.com/services/bookkeeping">StartChurch</a>  <a href="https://simplifychurch.com">Simplify Church</a>  <a href="https://tenfoldbpo.org/">Ten Fold</a>  <a href="https://churchaccountingservices.com/">Church Accounting Services</a>', 'Identify a bookkeeper through referral or research.  Negotiate a reasonable fee for services.  Contract with the bookkeeper to perform functions listed above.  Maintain regular, open communication with the bookkeeper.  This action is complete once you have contracted with a bookkeeper.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content & vendor links updated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated and links verified --pb  2022-09-16 removed recommendation hyperlink for Belay, added Luke 9:23 --pb ', 7, 'todo', 63, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7611e519-f846-50b2-85f3-b30391780514', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm bookkeeping plans', 'Make sure that the planter has engaged a competent and reliable bookkeeper to keep the church financial records in order and above reproach.', 'Once the planter has identified a bookkeeper, he will initiate a call to you, the coach, to review and affirm bookkeeping plans.', 'Reviews the planter''s bookkeeping plans.  Affirm that the plan is workable and accountable.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s bookkeeping plan.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content validated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 63& to 74 --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 73, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('3c6c010b-49f5-5c37-bf2a-1ae331521a90', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Purchase and set up financial software', 'Keep an orderly account of church finances by purchasing and implementing a financial software solution.', 'Purchasing a financial software solution should be delayed until after you have identified your bookkeeper. Financial software solutions, being about the same, can be selected based on what the bookkeeper prefers. They will have expertise in one brand of software and you can often purchase a software license through them.  When considering accounting software (such as <a href="https://quickbooks.intuit.com/">QuickBooks</a> and <a href="https://www.xero.com/us/">Xero</a>) in conjunction with the bookkeeper, consider the following factors:  Initial or recurring costs of software  Whether it is online - if you are using a virtual bookkeeper, insist on online software  Whether the software will accommodate donation tracking and charitable giving statements  Accounting Software vs. Church Management Software  One wrinkle is that accounting software is typically a clumsy tool for donor management. Today''s church management software (ChMS) solutions are specifically designed to track your donors'' gifts along with their prayer requests, group participation, and a host of other important ministry information. See subsequent PlanterPlan task  Implement church management software .  Keep your someday ChMS in mind as you consider accounting software. Investigate whether the system integrates with your ChMS and which ChMS your bookkeeper has experience using for donor tracking.', 'Ask which software solution your bookkeeping uses.  Determine if that solution will meet your requirements.  If not, ask for and seek recommendations from other churches.  Select and purchase an financial software solution.  Do the initial set up of things like the  chart of accounts .  Train additional staff and/or necessary volunteers in the use of the system.  This action is complete when the financial software is purchased and set up.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content & links updated --pb  2018-02-22 additional resources section added --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb ', 9, 'todo', 63, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('46e493a3-08d5-5bbc-bcdf-2df47d94a4f6', 'ade0ccf7-7ce6-52fa-823e-4cf88bf65f62', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Implement financial accounting processes', 'Set up solid, reliable accounting processes for the new church.', 'Accounting processes will keep all the money straight and reduce chances for people to steal or embezzle.  The following specific processes are covered in detail in subtasks:  Process for receiving, tracking and reporting donations  Financial checks & balances, and cash counting  Reimbursing expenses  Keeping good records  In addition to those, consider the following:  Selling T-Shirts  If you sell any goods or services, you are required to report that income to the IRS and your state tax agency. Check your state requirements for specifics. You may be subject to sales and use tax on these transactions.  Church Credit Cards  Some churches use church credit cards. If you do, pay them off every month. DO NOT USE A CREDIT CARD IF IT CAN''T BE PAID OFF EACH MONTH! Also, avoid cards that charge yearly fees. Credit cards do have several benefits if used properly:  You write one check to pay your bills rather than many checks.  You have a summary/record of all transactions via your monthly statement.  Some charge companies give ''cash back'' (like 2% of total purchases back) based on your total charges.  It makes credits for returns and refunds easier to administer (if you write a check and then return a product, you have to deal with handling cash back).  Where a charge card is used, users should be required to keep and submit receipts. You will need to implement a process for  reconciling  the charge bill each month. For example, you could have each staff member fill out a form documenting what each expenditure was for, its budget category and attaching the receipts.', 'Work through each of the subtasks.  Coordinate setting up bullet-proof processes for each with your bookkeeper.  This action is complete when you have a functioning financial accounting process.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content updated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb ', 10, 'todo', 68, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('bda21a4e-cafd-5917-97d9-241380d3e5d6', 'c1bf46aa-4e62-5612-ba1c-7a43b3a88e78', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this assimilation overview', 'Brief yourself on what goes into an Assimilation Strategy and the process you''ll follow to create one.', 'Assimilation is the process where someone moves from being your guest to being an active participant in the life of the church. An assimilation strategy is designed to move people forward along a clear, simple process to get and keep them connected to your church community.  There will be a lot to think through and work through, but the goal is to have a process that is easy to understand with uncomplicated next steps. If it''s confusing, they won''t know what to do, what''s expected, or (more importantly) how to get others to come along the path, too.  The ''Why''  Are they visitors or guests? Your answer will determine much of how you approach assimilation.  Everyone who shows up is coming from a different place. They may be in a great season of life or really hurting. Develop the attitude that anyone who comes to the new church is under the church''s spiritual care. Simply sending a newcomer a welcome letter will not cut it. You need repeatable processes that create opportunities to learn people''s stories and help them connect relationally.  Prepare for the Spike  In the first few weeks, the you should see lots of first-time guests. You''ll spend a disproportionate amount of time in the first few weeks following up with new people. The tasks in this milestone will help you put together a team to help. You will also need to prepare sermons and creative content ahead of time so you have extra bandwidth.  Keeping Everything Straight  If you''re following up with 5 families, you can probably just remember all that in your head. But if you have 30 or even 50 families, that system will come down like a house of cards. Your team members won''t be able to share the load and new families will fall through the cracks.  This Milestone  The tasks in this milestone will walk you step-by-step through crafting an assimilation strategy that makes sense for your church.  Your assimilation strategy will contain:  A system for getting guests connected into both a group and a serving team  A process for getting contact information so follow-up can happen  Benchmarks for measuring effectiveness', 'Read the brief description above.  Read one or more of the  Additional Resources  listed below.  This task is finished when you''ve read the content above and at least one additional resource.', 'template:  2018-10-12 new task --pb  2019-12-10 date fields found empty  2019-12-11 date fields re-entered manually --pb  &  2019-12-20 content updated --pb  ', 0, 'todo', 134, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('bf5124b5-075e-5c84-a759-4c7d133c50b3', 'c1bf46aa-4e62-5612-ba1c-7a43b3a88e78', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about assimilation', 'Open a conversation with your coach about getting people plugged in to the life of your church.', 'Assimilation is an important strategy for connecting people with God and growing the church. Discuss assimilation with your coach and get their feedback.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Gauging where people are at spiritually and crafting next steps  The relationship between assimilation and disciple-making  Typical process breakdown points  Keeping track of everyone  Keeping the follow-up system relational  Activating benchwarmers', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about assimilation.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 changed plan to strategy --pb  2017-12-26 content updated --pb  2018-05-15 additional resources subsection added --pb  2018-06-01 gdoc template added --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 143& to 155& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  2018-11-16 content updated to match Greg Curtis'' content in our strategy template; moved additional resource to task #780 --pb  2012-12-02 content validated --pb ', 1, 'todo', 140, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('148e0b6e-bc1f-5cd5-b8d5-2e0ba25e00dd', 'c1bf46aa-4e62-5612-ba1c-7a43b3a88e78', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft an Assimilation Strategy', 'Write down specific strategies toward a repeatable process that gets people plugged in to the life of the church.', 'People don''t intrinsically know how to get plugged in to the life of your church. In too many churches, the regulars don''t even know how to tell a guest what they can do to get connected. A clear, intentional strategy can keep things simple for your guests and empower your regulars to help others get connected.  Using the  Assimilation  Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/320">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/381">Google Doc</a>), you will work through the following:  A system for getting guests connected into both a small group and a serving team  A process for getting contact information so follow-up can happen  Benchmarks for measuring effectiveness', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Assimilation  Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/320">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/381">Google Doc</a>).  Work through the content above and subsequent PlanterPlan subtasks; record your thoughts & decisions in the template.  Finalize your Assimilation Strategy.  Send the completed Assimilation Strategy to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have submitted your written Assimilation Strategy to your coach.', 'template: standard  2017-12-26 content updated --pb  2018-04-20 moved to Implement Assimilation milestone --pb  2018-10-12 outdented from child to parent task --pb  2019-12-05 content and links validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 74& & Duration from 14& to 30& --pb&  2021-10-05 content updated --pb  2022-11-03& Added church planter discount link to Planning Center option -- NZ  2022-11-21 update links --sc  &  ', 2, 'todo', 180, 150, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('1a8f3fb4-c531-5c3d-bb5e-f8f739a62ad4', 'c1bf46aa-4e62-5612-ba1c-7a43b3a88e78', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Assimilation Strategy', 'Review the planter''s Assimilation Strategy document and provide feedback on the ideas for getting people relationally connected to the new church.', 'The planter has prayed and thought through effective strategies for following up with guests and getting them plugged in to the life of the church. Those strategies, tools and goals will be compiled into an  Assimilation Strategy  document, which should include:  Design for the "One Place" guests will be directed to turn in their connections cards (info booth or the like)  Plan for the "One Program" events where guests will get more information and be invited into next steps  Steps for the "Two Processes" the church will use to get guests connected into a group and a serving team  Benchmarks to know whether guest connections are happening', 'Review the planter''s written Assimilation Strategy.  Affirm that the strategy for following up with guests is practical and sufficient.  Provide other feedback to the planter as appropriate.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Assimilation Strategy.', 'template: standard  2017-05-19 changed plan to strategy --pb  2017-12-26 content updated --pb ', 3, 'todo', 161, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a2f13624-3f62-5ea2-8e9e-b86f9b2edc29', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about building a Leadership Matrix', 'Open a conversation with your coach about deciding which ministry teams to form and what the volunteer org chart will look like.', 'Each ministry and ministry team needs a leader. The leadership matrix is a simple tool that helps you see each volunteer and leadership position that needs to be filled for opening day.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Keeping team structure simple  Staff vs. volunteer leadership  Staffing for growth  Apprenticing  How to utilize coaches', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about building a leadership matrix.', 'template: standard  2018-03-29 content overhauled --pb  2018-04-02 additional resources subsection added -pb  2018-07-25 Logan quote added --pb  2020-01-14 content validated --pb  2018-10-12 pushed due in # days out from 102 and duration from 7 --pb  2019-08-28 added James Clear quote --pb  2020-01-13 replaced broken& gdurl& link to image --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 224& to 228& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 127, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('aac1e845-eb1e-5689-ba07-80c638d5ff6a', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Draft a list of desired ministry teams', 'Develop the list of ministry teams you''ll need at the launch or worship gatherings to support the unique vision of the church.', 'Which ministry teams will you need to put together to pull off weekly worship gatherings?  Now is the time to challenge past ministry team org charts, especially if you''re coming from a ministry context that either didn''t really use teams, or one that had dozens of ministry teams. What worked there may very well not work in this new church. Contextualize even the kinds of teams, what you call them, and what their responsibilities will be.  The trick in starting from scratch is that the same kinds of jobs need to get done. It would be easy to let some important worship gathering functions fall through the cracks as you reinvent the wheel.  To help you, Passion for Planting has created an exercise that will challenge you to group over 40 essential responsibilities and assign them to the ministry teams you''ll use. Download the  Ministry Team Responsibilities Template  (<a href="/resources/item/174">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/372">Google Doc</a>) and get to work!  You will use the resulting list to create the Leadership Matrix in the next PlanterPlan action', 'Review your  Vision Frame , especially the Strategies you identified.  Review your previously created  Opening Day Expectations  document.  Download Passion for Planting''s  Ministry Team Responsibilities Template  (<a href="/resources/item/174">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/372">Google Doc</a>).  Rearrange the teams and responsibilities to match your stated strategies.  Rename the teams and team roles to fit your unique context.  This action is complete when you have drafted the list of initial ministry teams.', 'template: standard  2018-06-01& gdoc& template added --pb&  2020-01-13 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 102& to 142& --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 134, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a39f0434-24cf-50eb-a7a4-1744d8eabad2', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Leadership Matrix for Opening Day', 'Determine how many leaders and volunteers are needed to build out your ministry teams.', 'You need a big-picture view of all the church''s ministry teams. You need to know who leads each team and what the teams are in charge of every week. Where do you go to see all of that in one place?  Enter the Leadership Matrix, a chart/spreadsheet that helps you build all of that out.  As you begin forming the people of the Launch Team into ministry teams, you''ll use the Leadership Matrix to help place everyone based on their passions, gifts and abilities. And as you develop leaders, you can do the same for them.  Work with your leaders to fully flesh out the serving roles on their teams. Once the roles are identified, work out how big of a bench or bullpen you''ll need for each team to be fully staffed and allow for rotation. If everyone serves every week, burnout is not far behind. If you need 2 people to serve in a particular role every week, you need a bench of 3 to 5 people.  Your Leadership Matrix contains the building blocks that you''ll need to set up your volunteer scheduling software.', 'Review your previously created Ministry Team Responsibilities worksheet for the list of ministry teams.  Download Passion for Planting''s  Leadership Matrix Template  (<a href="/resources/item/156">MS Excel</a> or <a href="/resources/item/370">Google Sheet</a>) and follow the included instructions.  Reference the <a href="/resources/item/159">Sample Leadership Matrix</a> for insight and inspiration.  Send the completed Leadership Matrix to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have customized and completed the leadership and team structure of a Leadership Matrix. The specific workers and leaders will be recruited later.', 'template: standard  2017-06-05 content validated --pb&  2020-01-14 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 109& to 149& --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 141, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('41b3c4be-45f9-5cea-9e02-4b43e18b5639', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Leadership Matrix', 'Review the planter''s leadership matrix and provide feedback for how to better structure ministry teams.', 'The leadership matrix is a key tool to have in place for ensuring a healthy start of regular worship gatherings. The matrix is basically a spreadsheet with a list of ministry teams and each position needed to make the ministry team function.  Initially the planter will have lots of holes to fill in this matrix. As the launch team grows and develops, the planter will begin plugging more people into these leadership roles. At that point, the leadership matrix becomes a coaching tool.  Periodically, request the most updated matrix to ensure that the planter is continuing to plug people into leadership roles. As launch approaches, the leadership matrix serves as a tool to determine what outside help will be needed.  At this point, ensure that every ministry team needed to accomplish the vision for Opening Day of worship gatherings is represented on the matrix. Also ensure the teams are structured for reproduction. In other words, each leader should have an apprentice leader (subordinate) and coach (superior).  Finally, look through the matrix and determine if any ministry roles are missing that need to be added to the matrix.', 'Read over the leadership matrix provided by the planter.  Affirm that all ministry teams needed to carry out the vision for Opening Day of worship gatherings are represented.  Affirm that each ministry team is structured for reproduction.  Affirm that each ministry role needed to make that team successful is listed.  Determine how often to review the leadership matrix with the planter. Create a prompt in your calendar or to-do program as a reminder.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Leadership Matrix.', 'template: standard  2017-06-05 content validated --pb&  2020-01-14 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 224& to 228& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 148, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('93db9788-ce92-5f41-9310-8f8847dc385e', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Assign leader to each ministry team', 'Recruit a team leader for each ministry team to make sure teams are healthy and ready to execute.', 'Assign a team leader for each ministry team you put on your Leadership Matrix. Set expectations for team leaders in writing and communicate those to each leader.  Use the Leadership Matrix spreadsheet, church management software or volunteer scheduling software to track who is leading which team(s).', 'Identify a person to lead each team.  Get a commitment from each leader to own the processes in that team.  Enter each leader''s name in the Leadership Matrix or appropriate software.  This action is complete when you have assigned team leaders to each ministry and ministry team.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' --pb  2017-06-05 validated content & updated resource link --pb&  2020-01-14 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 231& to 204 & Duration from 21& to 38& --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 227, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('60ae367d-0419-5188-bb89-8ab52d6f466b', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get your teams to write down their processes', 'Empower your teams and volunteer leaders to create healthy systems by writing down the processes they''re in charge of.', 'At some level, you already know processes are important, even if only intuitively. How do you react when someone tells you, "That''s the way we''ve always done it!"?  "Use reproducible processes. What is obvious to you is quite likely not obvious to others. You may be able to lead a small group just by winging it and doing what comes naturally. However, if you look more carefully at what you have done, you may discover you are following a subconscious template of some kind. You just "know" to start with something relational, and then to move deeper. You just "know" when to encourage a quieter member of the group to speak. Examine your practices and discern the underlying principles. Then script out the principles and actions so you have a template for training others. Intuition is impossible to pass on to others; reproducible templates are easy to pass on to others. Learn how to translate the first into the second. Whatever you do, do it in a way that allows others to imitate it."   Bob Logan on the <a href="https://sparks.fuller.edu/global-reflections/2018/04/11/essentials-for-church-planters-who-want-to-start-well/">Fuller Theological Seminary blog</a>  In the same way that the human body is made up of systems (skeletal, muscular, etc), churches are made up of systems. Church systems are the groupings of like processes that work together for a common purpose.  Every church has systems and processes for everything that gets done. Some systems are intentional and healthy, and some are ineffective and broken. But they''re there.  "You do not rise to the level of your goals. You fall to the level of your systems."   James Clear, Atomic Habits  Consider the following 4 possible scenarios at any church:  Note that good systems are what move people from unskilled to skilled.  Every thing that gets done at a church is part of some process. Most churches have over 100 different processes functioning all at once. At first you might be able to survive without formal processes. Before too long, though, a lack of healthy processes will stunt your growth. And it''s easier to establish healthy processes before the launch of worship gatherings than to try and change established things later.  You will want intentional, solid processes for everything eventually. But for legal, compliance and accountability reasons, you''ll need tight processes right away for at least:  Staff hiring  Background checks for staff & children''s workers  Children''s ministry check-in and check-out  Offering counting and cash handling  Reimbursements and other accounting processes  It is also important early in the life of the church to establish reliable processes for:  Groups  Reproducing leaders  Guest follow-up  Communications to your team  Marketing to your community, especially social media & web  Worship gathering planning  Commission and empower your teams to write down the various processes that they own. As you work with them, consider:  Every process needs an owner, and teams are best suited to own processes  Processes start with expectations/outcomes - describe what the process is designed to accomplish but allow them to find their own path to that outcome  It''s important to write each process down - it will force the owner to understand it  That document becomes a training tool and reference manual for new volunteers  Allow volunteers who use the process, especially new volunteers, to give raw, honest feedback on how the process could be improved  The tyranny of the urgent will drive you to work harder. But things at the church won''t improve until you take a step back to figure out how to work smarter. That looks like improving your systems and investing in people.', 'Describe to each team the importance of systems and processes.  Identify the most important processes to start documenting.  Communicate the goal or desired outcome of each process.  Set due date expectations for having written processes in place.  This action is complete when you have delegated the writing down of processes to your teams.', 'template: standard  2017-03-17 updated hyperlink in Action #4 to point to new Google Drive spreadsheet --pb  2017-06-02 content validated, resource link in Description updated, resource link in Action step removed in favor of reference to subsequent action --pb  2018-06-01& gdoc& template added --pb  2020-01-13 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 102& to 135& --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 227, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('f57dc1ba-0c46-5cb2-93a8-8c97d6c953aa', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower worship band', 'Develop a band that is able to create an environment of worship in a style appropriate for your context.', 'Form the initial worship band as far ahead of the launch of worship gatherings as possible. Bands need to gel, and developing that chemistry takes time. And they need to develop a basic repertoire of songs they know and can play together.  Plus, how cool would it be if the band were available to play at outreach events in the community months before Launch Sunday?  Non-Christians in the Band?  Will you allow someone who hasn''t yet chosen to follow Jesus to play in the band? Perhaps you wouldn''t want the worship leader to be a not-yet-believer, but lots of drummers, bassists, etc. have played themselves into the Kingdom. Decide where you''ll draw that line.  Auditions?  Work out with your worship team leader whether the church will require auditions to be on the worship team. In desperation, you may be tempted to let anyone on the team who shows interest. Whether you choose formal auditions, assess each person''s musical skill; but more so their motivation for wanting to join the team.  Some worship teams require aspiring team members to show up 4 weeks in a row to serve but not perform. That tends to weed out those that are more interested in the spotlight than servant leadership.', 'Decide what your typical ensemble will look like (which pieces you usually have in the band).  Figure out how many people you''ll need to run the team each week.  Recruit a team leader. Provide them a coach and inspire them to find an apprentice quickly.  Recruit people to fill the team.  This action is complete when you have completed each of the subtasks that follow this task.', 'template: standard  2017-06-05 content updated --pb  2020-01-14 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 194& to 204& & Duration from 14& to 30 --pb&  ', 6, 'todo', 203, 38, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('f15ed469-852a-5595-8bcb-7f64b2805a33', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Recruit a church management software champion', 'Find a detail-oriented, tech-savvy person to champion the cause of having important data that can be used for leadership decisions.', 'Going through the hard work of setting up a church management system (ChMS) will be a waste of time if it is not utilized and maintained religiously. There is a tech industry acronym that applies here:  GIGO  ( noun )  1  garbage in = garbage out  You will only get out of the system what you put into it.  Find someone on your team to champion the data who:  Is administratively-minded  Is detail-oriented to a fault  Never settles for ''good enough''  Cares about guests at the church being lovingly welcomed and treated well  Can be trusted with sensitive personal information and confidential prayer requests  The Church Management System Champion should be tasked with:  Making sure that all data is entered promptly, accurately, and consistently  Making sure that staff and volunteers are following up with the assimilation workflow so that no guest falls through the cracks  Producing ministry reports that empower informed leadership decisions  Maintaining the software and data', 'Identify someone on the Launch Team who would make a good ChMS Champion.  Cast the vision of what a healthy, functioning follow-up system looks like and why it is critical.  Grant that person access to the ChMS.  Set expectations for timeliness and confidentiality.  This action is complete once the Church Management System Champion inputs data for the first time.', 'template: standard  2017-06-05 content updated --pb  2020-01-14 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 231 to 235& & Duration from 21& to 14& --pb&  ', 7, 'todo', 134, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('3d312559-47cb-5eba-bc26-3aa401ef5e62', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower communion/offering team', 'Recruit a team to be responsible for collecting offerings and serving communion.', 'Communion and offering are two key elements of worship in the church, regardless of frequency. They can also be misunderstood by people with no church background.  Develop a clear process for:  preparing and serving communion  collecting & counting offerings  communicating the mechanics and meaning to the target audience  Develop a leader who will build a team to carry out these processes.', 'Decide how you''re going to serve communion and collect the offering.  Develop a leader and empower them to build the team.  Ensure that leader trains the team on communion and offering processes.  This action is complete when the communion and offering team has run the communion and offering processes at a preview service.', 'template: standard  2017-06-05 content validated --pb  2020-01-14 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 224 to 228& --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 234, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('3cc1f2da-c0df-5b01-af2c-315c9f2b9f53', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower tech team', 'Form a technical team to oversee the audio/visual/lighting (AVL) production of worship services and events.', 'The tech team is responsible for sound, lighting and projection at the worship gatherings. The team may also be responsible for creating any videos or special content for use during church functions.  Typically, the tech team requires special training or skill sets. You''re going to need at least one very strong AVL tech leader. Ideally, you''ll also identify a backup, or someone at a sponsor/network church that could provide expertise.  Audio  The setup of the soundboard and sound equipment before a worship gathering has a demanding schedule. The audio has to be the first thing that gets set up so the band has time to warm up and sound check. For that reason and others, your soundboard operator should also be the one that sets up the system that week.  Video  The projectionist should run through the song slides with the band as they warm up in case there are any last-minute changes.  Lighting  You may be able to get away with having your sound operator or projectionist oversee the lighting if there is only 1 or 2 changes during the worship gathering. But if there are multiple changes between  scenes  (elements of the gathering), that will demand a 3rd tech operator. Those lighting scene changes usually come with changes for sound and projection as well.', 'Determine the specific roles and responsibilities to be included in the tech team.  Figure out how many people you''ll need to run the team each week.  Recruit a qualified team leader (see subtask). Provide them a coach and inspire them to find an apprentice quickly.  Recruit people to fill the team.  Train the tech team on setup and operation (see subtask).  This action is complete when the initial tech team has practiced with the equipment once.', 'template: standard  2017-06-06 content updated --pb  2020-01-17 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 217& to 220& --pb&  ', 9, 'todo', 234, 29, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('38210c4a-c634-5944-8964-d46ea8e58681', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower children''s ministry team', 'Form an effective children''s ministry team that leads many children to Christ.', 'If your new church is reaching young families, a thriving children''s ministry will support entire families and potentially lead many children to Jesus. After all, the Kingdom belongs to such as these, right?  "In the US, nearly 85% of conversions to Christ happen between the ages of 4 and 14" - <a href="https://childrensministryonline.com/the-4-14-window/">childrensministryonline.com</a>  For Children''s Sake  Children are valuable in and of themselves. They aren''t just the future of the Church, they  are  the Church of today, too.  Resist the temptation to use children''s ministry as bait to reach the parents. Of course, you want to see whole families come to Christ. But making children a means to an end can quickly devolve into babysitting that neglects their souls.  A Little Extra Time  Starting a children''s ministry takes longer than starting most other teams. There are lots of layers and moving parts to a weekly children''s ministry. Begin recruiting people for this ministry as soon as possible. This ministry team will is very often the largest and will require the most recruiting.  And after they''re recruited, they''ll need to be trained.  Preventing Child Abuse  It is sad that in our day and age so much abuse happens anywhere. We owe it to the children Jesus entrusts to us to take significant measures to prevent and detect abuse.  A non-negotiable for your ministry will be running background checks on all staff and any volunteer that works with minors.  You should also arrange for your children''s workers to take abuse awareness and reporting training. Have them do it up front and then require them to renew their training annually or even semi-annually. Your background check vendor and/or your church insurance company may provide training resources.', 'Subtasks that follow will walk you through each of these important steps:  Recruit a team leader for the children''s ministry. Provide them a coach and inspire them to find an apprentice quickly.  Figure out how many people you''ll need to run the team each week.  Purchase or develop children''s curriculum/programming.  Develop children''s ministry safety procedures.  Determine process for conducting background checks.  Train children''s ministry leaders and team members.  This action is complete when you have completed each of the subtasks that follow this task.', 'template: standard  2017-06-06 content updated --pb  2020-01-17 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 187& to 190& & Duration from 14& to 30& --pb&  ', 10, 'todo', 234, 75, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('02d259d8-601d-582d-94eb-ed60825537f8', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower hospitality team', 'Form a team that will serve guests at your worship gatherings well so that they have a great first impression and experience.', 'You only get to make a first impression once. Form a team who will connect with newcomers and provide them the information and resources they need to connect with the church.  This team goes by a lot of different names depending on the congregation:  Guest Services Team  First Impressions Team  Hospitality Team  Greeter Team  Call it what you will, the team is responsible for all the first touch or first contact with newcomers from the parking lot into the auditorium. This includes:  parking lot attendants  greeters  refreshment servers or attendants  info table attendants  Your team should be full of people with high emotional intelligence &mdash; people who just naturally smile, adapt and connect well with others.  Train your hospitality team to be aware of what their body language is sending to guests. And help them find the balance between being aloof and overly-eager.', 'Decide what to call the team.  Determine what the team will be responsible for.  Develop a leader and empower them to build the team.  Figure out how many people you''ll need to run the team each week.  Recruit additional people to serve as parking lot attendants, greeters, hospitality hosts, etc.  This action is complete when you have completed each of the subtasks that follow this task.', 'template: standard  2017-06-07 content updated --pb  2020-01-17 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 210& to 213& --pb&  ', 11, 'todo', 212, 72, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('5e481cbc-1ac7-525c-889d-bfdf1749d088', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower set up and tear down team(s)', 'Recruit a set up and tear down team (or 2 separate teams) so that equipment throughout the facility is staged before the gathering and packed up afterward.', 'Set Up  A set up team is responsible for unloading, plugging together, assembling and otherwise setting up all of the equipment required to carry out the regular worship gatherings:  Lobby, including:  info table (or similar)  hospitality  Children''s Ministry  Worship, including:  AVL equipment  Chairs  Staging & backdrops  Signage  The team should be committed to being there early to transform the rented facility into a place for worship. Lead your team to arrive early enough not to be rushed through setup, but to be able to talk and have relational time with each other as well.  All equipment should be completely set up well before people begin arriving.  Tear Down  A tear down team is responsible for the reverse of the above. They should not begin breaking down until after the bulk of the crowd has gone. This gives the team members relational time to connect with newcomers before becoming engrossed in tasks.  The tear down team returns the facility to the same or better condition as when the set up team arrived.', 'Determine what the set up and tear down team(s) will be responsible for.  Figure out how many people you''ll need to run the team each week.  Develop a leader and empower them to build the team.  Recruit people to fill the teams.  This action is complete when you have completed each of the subtasks that follow this task.', 'template: standard  2017-06-09 content validated --pb  2020-01-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 224& to 213& --pb&  ', 12, 'todo', 227, 29, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('9f15a0ec-83bd-52fb-9f8f-75bacf4b46b4', 'cdf897ce-bc8d-574f-a0f5-c53e6416816c', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Identify and empower safety team', 'Form a safety team to address safety issues and emergency response at worship gatherings.', 'One of your key responsibilities as the church planter is to provide a safe place for people to discover God.  That word "safe" has several meanings:  a safe place to ask questions without being judged  a safe place to come as I am (clothing, language) without being looked down upon  a safe place to bring my children knowing they will be loved and protected  a safe place to worship without threat of physical harm  You''ll have to adopt a proactive (vs reactive) approach to safety and security.  The safety team will be responsible for reducing and responding to safety threats during worship gatherings (#4 above). You need to have a plan and a team trained in security & response basics if you''re faced with a medical emergency, act of violence or natural disaster.  Your safety team leader should be someone with security, law enforcement and/or military experience. At least one team member should be medically trained in at least first aid and CPR.  Your church planting network and/or church insurance company may be able to provide guides and training materials for you safety team.', 'Determine what the safety team will be responsible for.  Figure out how many people you''ll need to run the team each week.  Develop a leader and empower them to build the team.  Recruit people to fill the teams.  This action is complete when you have completed each of the subtasks that follow this task.', 'template:  2020-10-19 found Due in # Days & Duration fields empty, repopulated --PB  2020-12-14 changed Duration from 14& to 28& --pb&  2021-01-18 found Due in # Days & Duration fields empty, repopulated --PB ', 13, 'todo', 227, 29, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('94e9a9d0-9114-55fd-a601-e91179f46585', 'd5837a4d-a4a1-55f1-8be0-8f4033b39ec3', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this Marketing Strategy overview', 'Brief yourself on what goes into a Marketing Strategy and the process you''ll follow to create one.', 'Before you jump into cooking up a marketing strategy, there''s some pre-work you need to do:  1. Uncover Your Assumptions  You have them. You need to be able to name them before you move forward so that you''ll be open to new ideas and the Spirit''s prompting.  2. Study Your Community  Get to know your community and the kinds of people God is calling you to reach. Understanding their lives, their stories, and their motivations will help you meet them where they are with your marketing.  And not every marketing medium works in every context. Research what works in your community and find creative ways to test your message before you spend big bucks on getting the word out.  Start vs Launch  "When you start something, you tiptoe in and quietly offer it to your community. When you launch something, you make a big deal and announce its arrival to the people in your community and beyond." Rich Birch on <a href="https://unseminary.com/5-lessons-church-leaders-can-learn-from-the-all-day-breakfast-trend/">unSeminary.com</a>  This Milestone  The tasks in this milestone will walk you step-by-step through crafting a marketing strategy that makes sense for your church, your community and your wallet.  Your marketing strategy will contain:  A brief philosophy of marketing  Description of the stages of connectedness  What your message will actually say  Potential methods brainstorm  Specific media choices', 'Read the brief overview above.  Watch the Passion for Planting training video "<a href="/resources/item/166">Marketing - Communicate Your Identity</a>" featuring Ed Stetzer.  This task is finished when you''ve read the content and watched the video.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' --pb  2017-05-31 updated content, changed audience to coach --pb&  2019-12-23 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 119& to 121 --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 114, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('3ff1fe27-dfcf-56b9-aba7-90f5eb476fa5', 'd5837a4d-a4a1-55f1-8be0-8f4033b39ec3', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about marketing', 'Open a conversation with your coach about marketing.', 'You have to get the word out about the new church. Gone are the days of putting out a shingle and waiting for people to show up. You need to have a well-thought-out plan of proactively communicating with the community about the new church.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Apprehensions or reservations about marketing  Affording marketing  What''s working right now  Measuring ROI  How to incorporate digital and social media marketing', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about marketing.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' and fixed hyperlinks --pb  2017-12-15 content overhauled & new links tested --pb  2018-06-01& gdoc& template added --pb  2018-07-09 content updated to reflect changes is subordinate task names --pb&  2019-12-23 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 142& & Duration from 7 to 28& --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 120, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('98be3e46-e330-55fe-b20c-c269ce5a465a', 'd5837a4d-a4a1-55f1-8be0-8f4033b39ec3', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Marketing Strategy', 'Create a strategy for marketing your new church to the community in a way that can be heard by the community.', 'The Marketing Strategy document is aimed at crafting a well-thought-through approach to telling your church''s story in a way that your community can relate to.  Work through the following sub-tasks and put your completed answers in the  Marketing Strategy Template  (below).  Wordsmith your messaging  Determine the best ways to get the word out in the community  Estimate marketing costs and lead times  Be sure to include the following key information:  A basic philosophy of church marketing  Who you audience is  What you''re going to say to them  What you want them to do (call to action)  How you''ll maximize word of mouth invitations  Which other media to use  What your post-launch marketing will look like  Repetition is Key  In your strategy, take a "six to stick" approach: get at least six positive touches to every household in your target area before you launch expensive media campaigns like direct mail postcards. It takes at least 6 positive touches to build name recognition. A touch is any interaction with a person including:  personal conversations  web pages views  service events (serving or being served)  social media engagement  signs & flyers  etc...  It doesn''t take tons of money to get 6 positive touches. It does take coordination and planning to ensure the networking, marketing and outreach strategies are integrated and complimentary. This is so important that you should consider postponing the launch if you''ve had only minimal marketing exposure in your community.', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Marketing Strategy Template  (<a href="../../../resources/item/169">MS Word</a> or <a href="../../../resources/item/371">Google Doc</a>).  Work through the subtasks which follow.  Compile all of your ideas and answers in the template.  Send your completed Marketing Strategy to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have sent your Marketing Strategy document to your coach for review.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' --pb  2017-12-15 content updated --pb  2019-12-23 content updated & links verified --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 125& to 142& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 226, 183, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('093e9ad6-6d29-586f-86a9-657326d8c19c', 'd5837a4d-a4a1-55f1-8be0-8f4033b39ec3', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Marketing Strategy', 'Review the planter''s Marketing Strategy and provide feedback on the ideas for getting the word out in his community.', 'The planter has done research to determine which marketing methods will be effective and affordable in the local context. That research and other key decisions will be compiled in the Marketing Strategy document, which should include:  A basic philosophy of church marketing  Who the audience is  What he''s going to say to them  What he wants them to do (call to action)  How he''ll maximize word of mouth invitations  Which other media to use  What post-launch marketing will look like  Read over the Marketing Strategy and provide feedback to the planter. Spend time talking through the strategy, providing your wisdom and insight.', 'Review the written marketing strategy.  Affirm that the messaging has been contextualized to the planter''s community.  Affirm that the volume of media chosen will be sufficient to reach the community.  Affirm that the variety of media chosen will be make the message unavoidable in the weeks leading up the grand opening of worship gatherings.  Affirm that the planter has planned out enough time and money to execute the strategy.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Marketing Strategy.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 245 to 227& & Duration from 170& to 153& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 148, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('45d56dd9-9802-5395-84c8-553f19c13300', 'd5837a4d-a4a1-55f1-8be0-8f4033b39ec3', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set initial marketing budget', 'Determine how much money your church will allocate for marketing.', 'The Coca-Cola company spends over 4 Billion dollars a year on marketing. That''s approximately 18% of its yearly earnings. That''s a lot of money, but yet again in business oftentimes you have to spend money to make money.  Like businesses, church can spend large portions of their budget on marketing. They can build and host dynamic websites, contract with digital marketing companies to manage their social media platforms, saturate their community with a direct mail campaign, and run countless online ads in every crack and crevice of the internet.  If your church wanted to spend thousands of dollars on marketing, there would be no shortage of ways to do that. The question you need to wrestle with is how much money you want to spend on marketing.  Spend time reviewing your church''s budget. Think about how much you''ve dedicated to budgeting. Once you''ve settled on a number you''re comfortable with (make sure you have the funds committed), then it''s time to develop an initial marketing budget. This budget will break down how you will spend money allocated for marketing. Don''t settle for a one line marketing budget. Break it down into specific categories. Identify how much money will be spent on which types of marketing (branding, website, promotional material, direct mail, social media ads, etc.).  Finally, once you''ve decided how much money to spend in each category it''s time to determine when you''ll spend that money. Most church planters don''t have a lump sum of money just waiting to be spent, so for cash flow purposes it''s important that you incorporate the marketing budgeting into the overall budget to make sure you''re not planning on spending money you don''t have.', 'Estimate the amount of money you will spend on marketing.  Break down that amount into what you''ll spend on specific marketing methods.  Schedule when you''ll be spending money on marketing and account for those by adding them into your church budget.  This action is complete when the marketing budget has been added to the church''s budget.', 'template:  ', 4, 'todo', 148, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('68d7c6ab-2a13-5abb-9ef0-7a01263b20de', 'dfabb190-164d-5a8f-9fe2-05ba3e01943d', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Rent a PO Box or other mailing address', 'Establish a permanent mailing address for the church that can be used on legal forms and won''t change when you move your family or the church meeting place.', 'You don''t usually start off with a physical building or mailing address, but various government forms, purchase invoices, etc. require an address. You have a couple of options:  Use your home address  - the problem is that your address becomes a matter of public record for people to stalk you & market to you. And it''s common to move your family at least once in the early years, which creates a lot of address change paperwork for the church.  Use a supporting church address  - the problem is that you won''t get your mail in a timely manner, and they''ll want this to be a short-term solution, which creates a lot of address change paperwork when you switch  Use your rented office address  - office space can be very expensive, but if you''ve already decided to go this route, having your mail sent there is a no-brainer  Rent a PO Box  Passion for Planting recommends renting a PO Box to use as the church address. Get it very early in the process so that you can use the address on forms, purchases and business filings.  The PO Box used to be problematic because UPS & FedEx wouldn''t deliver there, but the US Post Office fixed that in 2012 by allowing you to use the office''s street address along with your box number. <a href="https://www.mymoneyblog.com/po-boxes-real-street-address.html">Read more</a>.  PO Boxes are also  a lot  cheaper that postal service mailboxes (ex: UPS Store): you can usually rent a small PO Box for $50-$75 a year but will often pay $12-$25  a month  at a retail location.  Don''t use your home address if it is at all avoidable.', '<a href="https://tools.usps.com/find-location.htm">Locate a USPS location</a> near where the worship gathering facility is likely to be.  Rent a PO Box.  This action is complete when a PO Box or other physical address has been set up for the church.', 'template: standard  2017-08-10 content updated including removal of reference to UPS Stores --pb  2019-12-10 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Duration from 63& to 7 --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 6, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7a479f4c-6a8a-5344-b7d9-0f216ea93995', 'dfabb190-164d-5a8f-9fe2-05ba3e01943d', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Set up home office', 'Save the church plant thousands of dollars by not renting office space while still meeting the needs of your staff.', 'When deciding whether to set up office in your home or to go rent space, there are several things to consider. Passion for Planting recommends most planters set up a home office.  Here are the advantages to a home office:  It''s cost effective . In most suburban and city areas you will pay a minimum of $1,000 a month and upwards to $3,000 a month for rented office space. Add utilities to that cost and you can quickly be in the tens of thousands of dollars for rented office space. Cash flow is important. Spending it on rented office space can severely limit your ability to do ministry.  It forces you out into the community . A home office only works for a handful of hours during the week, but that''s good. Unavoidable distractions at home will drive you out into the community where the people that you''re trying to reach are.  It gives you more time for both work and family . Why? There is no commute involved. Not commuting would save the average American an hour a day. That''s an hour you could spend relaxing, spending time with God, exercising, hanging with the family; the possibilities are endless. One extra hour a day is nearly  11 extra days  of the course of year - having a home office is like getting an extra two weeks of vacation a year!  If you have young children, working out of the home can be difficult. Be sure to set clear boundaries such as, "If the door is closed, please do not disturb me. But if it is open, I''d love to have you come say hi" or something similar.  Or consider using someone else''s home. In many families, both the husband and wife work. You could use a desk or garage workstation in their empty home as your office during the day.', 'Determine the location for your home office.  Set up your office and get to work.  This action is complete when you have set up a home office.', 'template: standard  2017-08-10 content updated --pb  2019-12-10 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 77& to 30& & Duration from 14& to 30& --pb&  ', 1, 'todo', 29, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('826fe77b-77bf-5645-898d-809a2935bee8', 'dfabb190-164d-5a8f-9fe2-05ba3e01943d', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get a dedicated church phone number', 'Get a phone number for the church so you don''t have to publish your personal number to the public.', 'Communications are vital to the new church, but life-work boundaries are too easy to cross. Set up a phone number for the church  very  early in the process, but pick an option that is flexible and will eventually accommodate other staff and/or locations.  There are 3 main options for setting up a church phone number:  Dedicated Land Line  This old-school approach is the most expensive and least portable. This may be a good option if you''re building out a 24/7 leased facility, but Passion for Planting discourages this option for all other planters.  Cell Phone  This is an OK option, but is equally as expensive. And you have to pick the lesser of 3 evils:  use your personal cell (or let the church cell double as your personal cell)  carry 2 phones everywhere (or leave your personal cell phone at home)  buy a higher-end mobile phone that accepts to SIM cards (has 2 phone numbers)  Voice Over IP (VoIP)  Passion for Planting recommends picking one of the various internet phone options. Here''s why:  they are inexpensive or free (see below)  they are portable - it isn''t tied to a location or even a specific user  you may be able to answer calls through your computer/browser  they may offer sharing or multiple inboxes - press 1 for Joe, press 2 for Erica  Current best options (Winter 2019):  <a href="https://voice.google.com/about">Google Voice</a>  PRO: free (personal) or $10/mo (if you used GSuite), one number rings any/all of your devices, unlimited calling, send & receive SMS/MMS texts;  CON: no support, sometimes poor call quality, one inbox (no extensions); not available in some markets  <a href="https://www.magicjack.com">MagicJack</a>  PRO: $39/year, rings mobile app and/or phone connected to device, unlimited calling, send & receive SMS texts;  CON: no MMS texts, one inbox (no extensions)  <a href="https://www.skype.com/">Skype</a>  PRO: $3.59/mo, send & receive SMS texts, unlimited calling;  CON: one inbox (no extensions), only rings app (computer and/or mobile app)  <a href="https://www.godaddy.com/smartline">GoDaddy SmartLine</a>  PRO: $10/mo, rings any/all of your devices, set business hours, caller ID, send & receive SMS texts;  CON: one inbox (no extensions)  <a href="https://www.phone.com">Phone.com</a>  PRO: $10/mo, unlimited users, rings any/all of your devices, send & receive SMS texts;  CON: 300 minute monthly limit  <a href="https://www.sideline.com">Sideline</a>  PRO: $10/mo, one number rings any/all of your devices, unlimited calling, send & receive SMS/MMS texts;  CON: one inbox (no extensions)', 'Research costs associated with each option for phones  Determine which option is most cost effective and will serve the needs of the church the best  Obtain a phone number for the new church  This action is complete when you have a phone number for the church.', 'template: standard  Q:&  Should we remove this task altogether?&  ----ds&  No it still applies... some guys will still do this. It talks cellular and voip& as options.  2017-08-11 content updated --pb  2019-12-10 content updated & links verified--pb  2020-08-02 GoDaddy SmartLine& added --pb  2020-12-14 changed Duration from 7 to 14 --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 44, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c2699cce-e9d1-5025-b09d-e8e16b60ad35', 'dfabb190-164d-5a8f-9fe2-05ba3e01943d', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Beg, borrow or buy office equipment', 'Equip the church office with the tools and resources you need to create a productive environment.', 'There are several pieces of equipment that you''ll want to purchase or have donated to make your office efficient and effective:  Laptop computer  Wireless router  All-in-One printer  Smart phone  Productivity software  Other hardware you might consider includes:  Folding machine  Tablet (iOS or Android)  Laptop System Requirements  Figure out what the highest demands on your machine will be and get one that has at least that much power. Typically, those will be:  projection - does it have enough muscle to run the projection software? Does it have the right output jacks (tablets probably don''t)?  video editing - does it have enough RAM and drive space to edit & render video files with your preferred editing software?', 'Figure out which office equipment you''ll need to be productive.  Buy it or get it donated.  This action is complete when you have obtained the office equipment you need.', 'template: standard  2017-08-25 content updated --pb  2019-12-10 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 77& to 30& & Duration from 7 to 30& --pb&  2021-01-28 merged in content from task "Get a laptop computer" --pb ', 3, 'todo', 29, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('e07c41a1-bc97-54e6-b07f-bdb6e557a01e', 'dfabb190-164d-5a8f-9fe2-05ba3e01943d', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get these productivity apps', 'Get these church planting power apps to maximize your productivity.', 'Don''t break the bank, but don''t be penny-wise and pound-foolish either. Get the apps you need to be productive.  Office Suites  Microsoft Office (Word, Excel,Powerpoint, etc.)  the overall dominant choice but not free  $8/user/month until you get your 501c3 back from the IRS; then can be free thru TechSoup.org  PC and Mac  AppleiWork (Pages, Numbers, Keynote, etc.)  free with apple computers since late 2013  Mac only  Google apps (<a href="https://www.google.com/gmail/about/">Gmail</a>, <a href="https://docs.google.com">Docs</a>, <a href="https://sheets.google.com">Sheets</a>, <a href="https://slides.google.com">Slides</a>, etc.)  free  all platforms  <a href="https://workspace.google.com/">Google G-Suite</a> (Docs, Sheets, Slides, etc.)  same as google apps, but branded with your church''s domain name  $6/user/month until you get your 501c3 back from the IRS; then can be free thru the Google Grant program  all platforms  Cloud File Storage  These allow you to share files across devices and keep them safely backed up on a server in case your device(s) go down. Choose:  <a href="https://www.icloud.com/">iCloud</a> (Mac)  <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/">Dropbox</a> (PC and Mac)  <a href="https://drive.google.com">Google Drive</a> (PC and Mac)  another you prefer  Password Manager  Don''t just keep using the same password on all the different sites you use. Get a password manager that will create different passwords for each site and then auto-fill them for you. Your best options will allow you to sync your passwords across your devices so that they''re instantly accessible. Choose:  <a href="https://1password.com/">1Password</a>  <a href="https://www.lastpass.com/">LastPass</a>  <a href="https://www.dashlane.com">Dashlane</a>  another you prefer  Collaborative To-Do List  These apps help you keep track of what needs to get done. They also allow you to invite team members to share the same task list so you can delegate stuff out and see how it''s going. Choose:  <a href="https://todoist.com">ToDoist</a>  <a href="https://asana.com">Asana</a>  <a href="https://todo.microsoft.com/tasks/en-us">Microsoft To Do</a>  another you prefer', 'Figure out which software you''ll need and maybe try out a new category you''ve never used before.  Buy it and install it on your various devices.  This action is complete when you have obtained office software.', 'template: standard  So many options here.&  Thinking this is& intuitive for guys today.& & Definitely need& guidance on video editing software (another task) but not on office software.&  Delete task? -----ds  Agreed. Will delete when the interface supports it. --pcf  2017-08-25 content updated --pb  2019-12-10 content validated and links verified --pb  2020-01-02 Wunderlist removed on announcement of its discontinuation, replaced with MS To Do --pb  2020-12-14 changed name from "Buy software" & Due in # Days from 45& to 30& & Duration from 7 to 30; content updated --pb&  ', 4, 'todo', 29, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('de23dc8c-df60-54d3-bd59-c92502c770a1', 'e5b4e37d-7ffc-58af-a770-f5a7f6c94442', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm facility selection', 'Review the facility selection and provide feedback to the planter.', 'Ensure that the planter has thought through each available facility and selected the one that is most consistent with the vision of the church and in best proximity to the people they are trying to reach.', 'Have the planter describe to you the facility options and discuss why the specific facility was selected.  Provide feedback to the planter as appropriate.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s facility selection.', 'template: standard  2018-10-29 content updated --pb  2018-10-30 title changed from "obtain..." to "purchase a..." --pb&  2019-12-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 150& & Duration from 21& to 30& --pb&  ', 0, 'todo', 142, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('5c0e4c15-190f-5538-90f9-f72549aedc60', 'e5b4e37d-7ffc-58af-a770-f5a7f6c94442', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Sign the facility contract', 'Get the worship facility rental/lease agreement in writing signed by both parties.', 'Always get the contract in writing and signed. Always. Planters that go into a facility on a handshake regret it.  The contract reduces chances for unmet expectations. And it protects you by clearly stating the terms.  Ensure that anything discussed verbally is written into the contract such as:  The rental price of the facility  What time the church can enter the facility and what time the church must be out of the facility  Specific dates the contract covers  Storage requirements  Food and drink policies  Show the contract to others before you sign it: a friend in real estate, your coach, your Management Team, etc.', 'Have a draft contract reviewed by friends & colleagues with experience.  Sign the contract and make sure to get a copy with their signature on it, too.  File the fully signed contract with your important church legal paperwork.  This action is complete when you have filed the fully executed/signed contract for a rental facility.', 'template:  mirror content to Task ID #727 ', 1, 'todo', 150, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('81ed4886-b650-5553-b312-53222ac81416', 'e5b4e37d-7ffc-58af-a770-f5a7f6c94442', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Calculate how many services the facility dictates', 'Decide now whether you''ll start with one, two, or more weekly services based on what the facility allows.', 'Deciding on how many services to start with isn''t just a matter of personal preference. The factors that influence your decision include:  Cost  - If you are renting by the hour, two gatherings will cost more than one. Can you afford the extra cost?  Time Constraints  - Are there any limitations on service times (ex: when renting a movie theater, you may have to be out by 12pm)?  Volunteer Staffing  - Consider the impact on volunteers (children''s ministry in particular) and your ability to recruit enough volunteers for two weekly gatherings. On the flip side, if you have only one gathering, your children''s volunteers will be unable to participate in the worship gatherings with their families on weeks they serve.  Attendance  - The number of people you expect to reach on opening day and the expected attendance 3 months after opening day.  Critical Mass  - Don''t let your seating be less than 50% full to avoid the where-is-everyone effect  Facility size  - How many people can the auditorium seat? How large is the parking lot? The children''s area? Can one gathering handle the expected attendance? If you go with two gatherings, will there be critical mass in each?', 'Based on the facility, consider how many weekly worship gatherings are possible.  Pray about gathering times and the impact that one or two gatherings may have on your launch team and volunteers.  Pray about how your gathering time(s) will impact newcomers'' ability to attend the gathering.  Decide on how many weekly gatherings you will conduct and at what time they will be held.  This action is complete when you have finalized the number of weekly worship gatherings and their start times.', 'template: standard  2019-12-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 121& to 143& --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 134, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('27e4aa45-5d71-57ee-89a3-2dd7e5721a77', 'e5b4e37d-7ffc-58af-a770-f5a7f6c94442', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Purchase a church insurance policy', 'Bind a general liability insurance policy that protects the church and staff from unnecessary risk.', 'There are several types of insurance that you have to consider as a new church:  General liability (aka multi-peril)  Umbrella liability  Worker''s compensation  Auto/vehicle  Passion for Planting strongly recommends adding these common riders:  Inland Marine (covers trailer contents in storage & transit)  Sexual misconduct  Directors & Officers (covers your Management Team/Board of Directors)  Hiring Practices (covers lawsuits from disgruntled employees)  Professional/Ministerial Counseling (covers lawsuits from people who don''t like the pastor''s advice)  Get at least two quotes from different insurance companies. Start first with insurance carriers that specialize in churches.  Timing  You will be required to have a policy in place when you sign the facility contract, but you may want it sooner. You can get insurance as soon as you incorporate. That covers you from lawsuits that could happen even before you start worship gatherings. Specifically, it covers your Management Team and your own activities. Getting it that early can be trickier, since the primary policy will be based on a brick & mortar location. Often they''ll let you start with the planter''s residence as the ''church facility'' until the worship gathering facility is identified.  You decide which company to use and how much coverage to purchase, except that your landlord may have minimum requirements.  The insurance policy may need to be updated several times prior to launch:  when a facility contract is signed  after equipment is purchased  if a church trailer or vehicle is purchased  when an office is rented  To get a quote, be prepared to provide the insurance company with at least the following information about the facility:  address of the facility  the square footage of the area being used by the church  the construction type of the building (e.g., masonry or wood)  the age of the building  whether the facility requires any specific coverages  Portable Churches  For church plants that are portable, covering the equipment will require an inland marine policy. This rider will cover the equipment while it is being used, stored and in transit. In some cases, the main policy itself will not cover the equipment when it is being transported.  Also be sure to have an auto policy if the church purchases anything with a VIN & license plate: trailer, pickup, box truck, etc. Check with the insurance provider about whether they cover a volunteer''s vehicle being used to haul the equipment.  National Carriers  Although using a local insurance agent provides networking and evangelistic opportunities, often local agents are unable to provide the type of insurance a church plant needs. You may find the following companies helpful. These national carriers provide additional benefits such as reduced rates for background checks.  <a href="https://www.churchmutual.com/">Church Mutual</a>  <a href="https://www.guideone.com/">Guide One</a>  <a href="https://www.brotherhoodmutual.com/">Brotherhood Mutual</a>', 'Provide necessary information about the chosen facility.  Get quotes from insurance companies.  Choose and bind an insurance policy.  This action is complete when you have bound applicable insurance policies for the church.', 'template: standard  2017-05-23 updated content --pb&  2019-12-20 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 133& to 150 & Duration from 7 to 15& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 150, 30, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('a20f6adc-76d3-5dd9-baa2-dd3fbc935bfd', 'e5b4e37d-7ffc-58af-a770-f5a7f6c94442', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a facility layout map', 'Determine how you''re going to use your facility for worship gatherings, from layout to setup to traffic flow.', 'After you finalize the facility contract, develop a plan for how the church will use the space. The vision may be clear in the  your  mind, but the workers that will be doing all the set up need more concrete details than that.  Develop a detailed ''to scale'' map showing the auditorium and children''s areas as well as the interconnecting hallways. Note the location of all lobby tables (e.g., welcome table, information table, hospitality table) as well as the utilization of the stage, where the soundboard will go, etc. The objective of the map is to determine the most guest-friendly layout and flow as possible.  Often you can get a map of the facility simply by asking. Schools or hotels may say they do not have maps available, but if you ask for a  fire evacuation map  they will be happy to provide one. Use that map as the base or background for you space utilization plan.', 'Get or create a scale drawing of the facility  Tour the facility with a specific eye for:  Location/number of electrical outlets  Distance from parking lots to entry doors  Location and distance to restrooms  Location and distance to children''s ministry (will parents feel safe leaving their kids? Is the location naturally ''safe?'')  Distance from projector to screen  Which seats will be used in the auditorium  Natural traffic flow through the facility including exits and restrooms  Where to place the signs and tables  Determine which entrance and which rooms will be used.  Mark on the map where all of your equipment will go.  This action is complete when you have a completed facility layout map.', 'template: standard  2017-05-23 content updated --pb  2019-04-26 image added --pb  2019-07-15 image update & another added --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 182& to 172 --pb&  2020-01-13 replaced broken& gdurl& link to image; content updated --pb ', 4, 'todo', 150, 15, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('058c109d-f2b7-508b-a4c9-1316ce95fb3d', 'e9365b1b-0717-5164-b14f-41888b5bde24', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this Launch Team Strategy overview', 'Understand the importance of building a Launch Team and gain a frame of reference for the work ahead.', 'Developing the launch team is the most critical piece of launching worship gatherings. Studies like Ed Stetzer''s <a href="https://www.newchurches.com/product/churchplantingresearch/">The State of Church Planting in the U.S. Research Report</a> continue to show that the size of the Launch Team prior to launch of worship gatherings is a leading indicator of the church''s health and sustainability after the launch.  Your Launch Team is the group of committed adults & teens that have signed up to help the church launch worship gatherings. They will be the inviters and the worker bees. Some will become your key team leaders.  You Launch Team should be comprised of some percentage of people with little or no church background. Maybe they just said yes to Jesus, or maybe they''re checking this whole Jesus thing out. But if you haven''t reached any lost people prior to launching weekly worship gatherings, that may very well become your long-term legacy.  Your ability to gather people and build a team is the single best indicator of how healthy the new congregation will be after launching worship gatherings. You can have all the best strategies and all the resources you need, but without a Launch Team, the worship gatherings won''t ever come together. The Church is people, after all.', 'Read the overview above.  Watch the training video <a href="/resources/item/149">Develop and Grow Launch Team</a> by Ed Stetzer.  Read one or more of the posts linked below.  This action is complete when you have a clear understanding of what a Launch Team is and why you need one.', 'template: standard  2018-04-20 updated content, changed audience to planter --pb  &  2019-12-23 content updated --pb  ', 0, 'todo', 50, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('de2450ca-9c7c-5f8c-afab-ce3987cbaa68', 'e9365b1b-0717-5164-b14f-41888b5bde24', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about building a Launch Team', 'Open a conversation with your coach about building a Launch Team.', 'As a church planting veteran, your coach will have lots of practical experience with growing a Launch Team. It is one of the primary tasks of planting a new church - meeting people and getting them on mission together.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Whether to include lost people on the Launch Team  Closing the deal on an invitation to join  Where to meet people  Communicating expectations  What to do at Launch Team meetings', 'Call your coach about forming and growing a Launch Team.  This action is complete when you have called your coach about building a Launch Team.', 'template: standard  2017-06-09 content & resource links updated --pb  2018-06-01 added new Gdoc& template format --pb  2018-10-12 changed title from ''develop a launch team strategy'' (planters confused it with the launch strategy) --pb  2018-11-12 additional resources subsection added --pb  &  2019-12-23 content updated --pb  ', 1, 'todo', 56, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('ad46e53b-f141-5ebe-b1b7-5bf232cfe04c', 'e9365b1b-0717-5164-b14f-41888b5bde24', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Launch Team Development Strategy', 'Create a written strategy document outlining your contextual approach to finding people, building a team, and planning meetings.', 'To help you with the complexity of this strategy, key building blocks are laid out in the subtasks that follow. Download the  Launch Team Development Strategy Template  (below) to use like a fill-in-the-blank worksheet as you work through:  talking to your spouse about their role  developing a covenant or commitment agreement  developing a process for accepting people into the team  determining what types of info meetings to host  deciding what to do at Launch Team meetings  picking calendar dates for meetings  identifying training material to use with the Launch Team  Set a Goal  Set a prayerful goal for the number of people who will join the Launch Team. You should have already dreamed one up in your  Opening Day Expectations  document.  Look back in that document at the ministry teams you dreamed of having. Then ask, "How many workers will need to be on the Launch Team in order to support this vision?" Now ask, "How many workers will we need so that we can work out some kind of serving rotation and not burn everyone out?"  Set a Date  Set a target date to to hit your goal. You may find it helpful to break that number down into several smaller goals and set target dates for each along the way. For example, if the goal is to have 50 adults on the launch team by August, you might set a goal of 25 people on the team by June, and before that, 10 people on the team by April.  Be sure to allow adequate time to train launch team members before the start of worship gatherings. It would be amazing to be recruiting Launch Team members right up to the night before, but how equipped will they be to serve the next day? How much will they have internalized the common vision? Whatever your goal is, back your due date up a good 30 days before the launch of your worship gatherings.', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Launch Team Development Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/325">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/368">Google Doc</a>).  Complete each section as you work through the subsequent child tasks in PlanterPlan.  Refer back to the  Opening Day Expectations  document. Calculate how many workers will be needed to support that vision for the Opening Day of worship gatherings.  Send the written Launch Team Development Strategy to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have sent your Launch Team Development Strategy to your coach for feedback.', 'template: standard  2017-06-12 content updated --pb  2020-02-24 additional resources subsection added --pb  &  2019-12-23 content updated --pb  ', 2, 'todo', 66, 10, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c51f4508-eb95-5582-8a31-7e65830fa8eb', 'e9365b1b-0717-5164-b14f-41888b5bde24', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Launch Team Development Strategy', 'Review the planter''s Launch Team Development Strategy document to ensure that it is thorough and realistic.', 'The Launch Team Development Strategy document is a culmination of multiple tasks in PlanterPlan. The planter will use the template to record decisions they''ve made and specific strategies they''ll employ.  Their Launch Team Development Strategy document should include:  decisions about their spouse''s role  what it means to sign up  how people will sign up to join the team  how to leverage group settings to recruit  content of Launch Team meetings  date of the first meeting  training materials to use with the Launch Team', 'Review the planter''s Launch Team Development Strategy document.  Provide feedback where necessary.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Launch Team Development Strategy document.', 'template: standard  2017-06-14 content validated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 77& to 90& & Duration from 14& to 30& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 70, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('358f5f56-8b12-5248-a7e0-3e5417bd9d75', 'edafb56f-8a85-5250-b916-bc340f6a1c02', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this Prayer Team overview', 'Gain an understanding of the importance of having a prayer team and create a strategy to bathe the church plant project in prayer.', 'Making disciple-makers is a spiritual exercise. Fundamentally, you will be storming the gates of hell. You have to spend time in prayer yourself AND recruit others to be a part of praying for the project.  This milestone will walk you through crafting an Intercessory Prayer Team Strategy and provide you with some very practical tools and disciplines to make communicating prayer requests to your team easy.', 'View the <a href="/resources/item/212">Initiate Prayer Team Training Video</a> by Dr. Ed Stetzer.  This action is complete when you have watched the prayer team training video.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content validated --pb  2018-11-02 content updated --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 14 to 8 & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb ', 0, 'todo', 7, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b4e6657e-3e29-5b88-9a5a-d8d2020a2ce7', 'edafb56f-8a85-5250-b916-bc340f6a1c02', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft an Intercessory Prayer Team strategy', 'Create a strategic approach to recruiting a prayer team and keeping them updated with regular communications.', 'No partner is more important than prayer partners. Making new disciples and planting a church is a big deal. Satan does not want you to succeed. Surrounding yourself and your team with prayer partners is the single best thing you can do to ensure success.  Many planters underestimate the amount of spiritual warfare they will face. You have to make prayer a priority.  Do not be shy in asking people to join the prayer team. Consider how you can use prior church relationships to recruit people. Maybe you''ll ask supporting churches to give you e-mail lists/groups to invite people to join in prayer. But be careful not to SPAM or sign people up who are not interested - only  invite  people to join the team.  Contact as many friends and relatives as possible and ask them to be part of the team. Ask each of them to recruit additional prayer team members. The goal is to get hundreds (or thousands) of prayer team members actively praying for the new church. The prayer update is a great communication tool for keeping people informed and requesting prayer.  An Inner Circle  Consider inviting a small handful of prayer warriors into an inner circle relationship. Your prayer update will be going out to hundreds of friends, family & supporters. When that hard day comes when you feel like quitting, and it will, you need people praying for you, but you may not want to broadcast that to your entire distribution list.  Set a Schedule You Can Maintain  It is easy to get busy and forget to send updates to your prayer team. Set an expectation for how often you will send updates for each method of communication you''ve chosen. Set a recurring appointment in your calendar to serve as a reminder.', 'Take time away with God, seek His wisdom and counsel on how best to engage an army of prayer warriors committed to covering this project.  Download Passion for Planting''s  Prayer Team Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/329">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/376">Google Doc</a>).  Fill in the blanks to craft your own Prayer Team Strategy.  This action is complete when all subordinate actions have been completed.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content validated, new resource link added& --pb  2018-06-01 content updated,& gdoc& template added --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2021-01-28 merged in content from task "Develop a schedule for communicating with the prayer team" --pb ', 1, 'todo', 13, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('28e7ece9-fe99-5e23-b4d3-55ef14f53026', 'ef787a6e-86f7-5aef-a380-a7d82a5e790b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Watch this PlanterPlan tutorial', 'Get comfortable using PlanterPlan to get the most out of it.', 'PlanterPlan is an online project management app built  by  church planters  for  church planters. It contains a library of well over 800 tasks related to church planting. By using this app, you''ll minimize the risk of forgetting an important aspect of launching in-person worship gatherings.  <a href="https://youtu.be/2UzvD7M2bHs?si=MB4WrSQnG0UFzGLo"> </a>  Power Tips  Invite Your Team: create user accounts for others on your team and invite them to collaborate on the project; with premium content, training on how to do each task is built in!  Delegate: assign a task to a team member by changing their initials as the  lead ; for volunteers not in the system, simply use the  email button  to shoot them the task (with the same built-in training)  Communicate: use the built-in reports to send updates to your Management Team, church planting network and/or denomination  Customize: you can add additional milestones and tasks from our extensive library or custom ones you create', 'Watch the PlanterPlan tutorial video above.  This action is complete when the PlanterPlan tutorial has been viewed.', 'template: standard  Need to link in PlanterPlan Tutorial video when complete. &radic;  2017-08-30 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days & Duration from 3 to 1 --pb  &  2020-01-24 content validated --pb  2025-03-14 updated video from Vimeo to YouTube --pb ', 0, 'todo', 0, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0e37226e-8ed9-5557-ad0f-664dcd4ef9db', 'ef787a6e-86f7-5aef-a380-a7d82a5e790b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Attend church planter training', 'Prepare to plant a church by attending a church planter boot camp or completing a church planter residency program.', 'Church planting residencies are a great way to prepare to plant a church. Most church planters fail to see the need for such training because they don''t know what they don''t know. They are like the young engaged couple that don''t understand why they should go through premarital counseling. In their minds they''re in love and that''s all they''ll need to have a healthy marriage. However, they don''t realize the hard work that lies ahead of them on their journey towards happily ever after.  This is why pastors recommend young couples to go through premarital counseling, which offers them tools they can use to cultivate their relationship. Church planting training, like residencies and boot camps, do the same thing for church planters. They equip church planters with tools they can use to develop the systems and teams they''ll need to make disciples and start a healthy church.  Residencies vs. Boot Camps  The big difference between residencies and boot camps is time. Residencies typically last 9-12 months, while boot camps are 3 to 5 days of intense classroom training. During a residency a church planter will not only learn from reading books and discussions with experienced church planters, they''ll also learn from practical ministry experience. Boot camps are the quick way to gain much needed knowledge, but residencies allow participants to grow as leaders while practicing what they''re learning in real life.  You''ll typically attend a boot camp or complete a residency after you''ve been affirmed by an assessment center. Costs to participate in a boot camp range from less than $200 to over $1,500. Residency programs usually range from $1,500 to $3,000.  Many church planting networks offer their own boot camps and residency programs to prepare planters for the task which is before them. Each network''s training is unique, reflecting the particular passions of that network. If you aren''t a part of a network that offers church planter training, consider Passion for Planting''s boot camp or distance residency program (info below).  The bottom line is you need training. Why fly blind and make mistakes that are avoidable? Learn from others who have already walked in your shoes and develop your church planter toolbox which will help you complete the work God''s called you to.  <a href="https://church-planting.net/residencies/">Register Now</a> for our next Residency Cohort.  <a href="https://church-planting.net/bootcamp/">Register Now</a> for our next Boot Camp event.  If that doesn''t meet your needs or timetable, consider contacting these training organizations to get an overview of their schedule and topics covered:  <a href="https://www.acts29.com/acts-29-training-programs/">Acts29</a>  <a href="https://www.nutsandbolts.org/">Nuts & Bolts</a>  <a href="https://www.efca.org/resources/document/start-boot-camp">Evangelical Free Church of America (EFCA)</a> --> <a href="https://www.arcchurches.com/launch/">Association of Related Churches (ARC)</a>  <a href="https://www.converge.org/church-planting/training-101">Converge Worldwide</a>  <a href="https://churchmultiplication.net/launch">Church Multiplication Network </a>  <a href="https://www.cmtcmultiply.org/">Church Multiplication Training Center</a>', 'Research training options and select which to attend.  Register and adjust schedule to participate in training.  Attend church planting training.  This action is complete when you have attended training.', 'template: standard  2017-08-30 content and hyperlinks updated --pb  2019-11-22 links validated & content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed& title from "Attend a church plant boot camp" --pb  2020-12-22 updated the wording --SC  2022-11-21 deleted Value of Church Planter Training article link by Ed Stetzer& (broken)--sc ', 1, 'todo', 45, 46, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('67e75ce8-61e2-52e5-92b6-05c905c3f5ca', 'ef787a6e-86f7-5aef-a380-a7d82a5e790b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Visit other new churches', 'Experience other new church plants firsthand in order to understand trends and new innovations for reaching people; this will also expand your paradigm of church beyond the limits of your personal past experience.', 'Close your eyes. Picture opening day of the new church. What does it look like?  Chances are, the picture you see of the future  looks very much like a picture from your past . Many planters start with what is familiar and ask, "What do I want to change?" What you get is a minor variation to the picture of the past. How do we start with a blank piece of paper and create a brand new picture?  The first thing you need to do is to get the picture of past experience out of your mind. Commit that you will not let the past be the starting point for your future. Instead, take what is good from the past, and create a new thing. God is calling you to do a new thing.  Next, look at what other new churches are doing to reach people. Gain an understanding of trends and innovative practices. This starts with learning from others who have come before you.  Just as you are encouraged not to copy the paste, do not simply copy what others are doing. The goal is to understand what others are learning and doing as you begin to create a new picture. In breaking the paradigms of your past, it helps to understand the new things that others are doing.', 'Identify a list of new churches (planters) who have started within the past year.  Review the websites and social media pages of new churches to determine new and innovative things that are being done to reach people.  Contact and talk with as many planters as possible.  Visit as many new churches as possible (anywhere in the country).  If possible, visit existing churches in your target area to understand what others in the target area are doing to reach people.  This action is complete after you have visited at least 5 young, growing churches to observe what they are doing to reach lost people.', 'template: standard  2017-08-31 content validated --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Duration from 90 to 45 --pb ', 2, 'todo', 45, 46, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('20460a1a-e0a6-5372-8c57-d78a95853a20', 'ef787a6e-86f7-5aef-a380-a7d82a5e790b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Attend church planting conferences', 'Attend a church planting conference to learn from church planting experts, network with other planters, and connect with church planting vendors.', 'Conferences provide you with a unique opportunity to accomplish several things at once.  Training and Inspiration  Church planting conferences feature sessions and breakouts on the best practices of church planting led by experienced church planting experts. Conferences provide a rare opportunity to connect with nationally known church planting experts in large and small group settings. You will be learning from the best of the best and will often have the opportunity to choose breakout sessions on specific topics of interest.  Many planters receive an incredible amount of encouragement and motivation that provides energy for months to come. God often works through these speakers to confirm a call, encourage the disheartened, and inspire. The experience is similar in scope to the troops gathering before their generals in preparation for war. You will leave motivated and ready to fight the spiritual battles ahead of you.  Networking  In addition, the conferences are attended by other planters. This provides a great opportunity to develop networking communities to share in which planters gather either in person or online to share experience and provide support to each other.  In 1 Kings 18:22, Elijah said, "I am the only one of the LORD''s prophets left, but Baal has four hundred and fifty prophets" Many planters experience this same feeling of isolation. It is important to realize that you are not alone. In 1 Kings 19:18, God reminded Elijah, "Yet I reserve seven thousand in Israel, all whose knees have not bowed down to Baal and all whose mouths have not kissed him." A network of planters can be an invaluable source of spiritual encouragement. It can also be mutually beneficial to collaborate together on ideas for church planting.  Resourcing  Most church planting conferences have several vendors present as well. From website design to equipment to completing legal paperwork, there are many vendors who provide expert help to the planter. Take time to familiarize yourself with these vendors. Get contact information for each vendor you may want to work with. And of course register for all the free iPhones and giveaways the vendors have.  Tom''s Tips!  Eight suggestions for making the most of conferences and training events.  by Tom Herrick of Titus Church Planting Institute  It is training and conference season. Continuing education is imperative, but too often the only take-away from such opportunities ends up on your bookshelf (eg. simply another how-to binder or the speaker''s newly published work).  Consider these tips to make the most of the time, energy and resources you are investing:  Do your homework  If your training program includes a pre-assignment to be completed before the event, do it! You want to start the learning process on the right foot, instead of feeling like you are playing catch-up from the get-go. (Pre-work also helps you to make the change from the work-to-learning mode in your brain.)  Reflect on the outcome you want  Why are you investing in this training? What kind of take-away do you need? Perhaps you want a new or improved skill. Or maybe you need to build your network of go-to associates. Knowing your preferred outcome improves your chances of attaining it. It also helps you make better decisions when you need to choose between a variety of workshops.  Don''t go alone  Often, capturing the material presented at training events is like drinking from a fire hydrant; sometimes you just cannot catch everything being taught! Having colleagues or team mates alongside provide two purposes: more ears to hear means more information retained; and it is a great way to get the entire team on the same page-important in any ministry, but particularly in church planting and development.  Stay "Out of Office"  Be sure to turn off or silence your phone, shut down your email, and only open as many browser windows as are needed for the training. I know this sounds like heresy, but multi-tasking in a learning environment is otherwise known as distraction. Valuable information is missed when you take your focus on the presenter, and turn it to the technology calling your name.  Know your learning style  Do you know how you normally learn? If you are a visual learner, be sure to position yourself where you can easily see the presenter and any AV tools. Take good notes, so you can review and re-read them. If you are an auditory learner, grab a seat near the sound booth, where you are guaranteed to hear the speaker well. Perhaps ask the trainer if you can record the session, so you can listen to it again later. Are you a kinesthetic learner? Feel free to doodle away, to illustrate and reinforce your learnings. Create graphics and charts. Bring along colored pens and highlighters, too! However you learn best, be sure to find a very simple way to record your thoughts so you can retrieve them later when you''re putting what you''ve learned into practice.  Reflect with your team  At breaks, or at the end of each day, carve out time to reflect on what you''ve heard. Ask three questions: What jumped out to you today? How is it helpful to your work? What will you do differently?  Create an Action Plan  Based on your desired outcomes and daily reflections, develop a plan that includes:  Specific actions to take over the next X-number-of weeks/months  When you''ll take the actions  Identify the reasons you want to take these steps  Obstacles that might get in the way, and how you''ll tackle the them  How you''ll reward yourself  Get a Coach  Having a coach to come alongside you is an effective way to accelerate your progress toward a goal. Having a coach keeps your desire outcome before you and helps you to develop the plan to get there.', 'Decide which conference(s) to attend.  Register for the conference(s).  Make travel arrangements.  This action is complete when you have attended a church planting conference.', 'template: standard  2017-08-31 content validated --pb  2019-11-22 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Duration from 90 to 45 --pb  2022-05-09 removed hyperlink to Titus Church Planting as site & FB page are no longer valid --pb ', 3, 'todo', 45, 46, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('71dbeae0-7ffc-5d54-8cdd-f3cbaa8fd15d', 'ef787a6e-86f7-5aef-a380-a7d82a5e790b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop a reading plan', 'Discipline yourself to read disciple-making, church planting and leadership books to learn from other experienced church planters.', 'There are an increasing number of good books available about church planting. It is difficult to wade through them all and choose the ones that will best apply to you and your situation. Although many milestones in PlanterPlan have recommended books you may find useful on a particular topic, this action calls out some of the best books for you to start with. You should work with your coach to determine the most appropriate books to read.  Passion for Planting considers the following "must read" books for planters:  <a href="https://a.co/g6fmiSZ">Planting Missional Churches</a> (Ed Stetzer)  <a href="https://www.amazon.com/T4T-Discipleship-Re-Revolution-Planting-Community/dp/0974756210">T4T: a Discipleship Re-Revolution</a> (Steve Smith & Ying Kai)  <a href="https://a.co/22xxu2O">It''s Personal: Surviving and Thriving on the Journey of Church Planting</a> (Brian Bloye)  <a href="https://multiplication.org/product/the-emotionally-healthy-church-planter/">The Emotionally Healthy Church Planter</a> (Pete Scazerro)  <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Future-Church-Laws-Real-Growth-ebook/dp/B087RTBL71/ref=tmm_kin_swatch_0?_encoding=UTF8&qid=&sr=">Future Church</a> (Will Mancini)  <a href="https://a.co/gXVhcLg">Church Unique</a> (Will Mancini)  <a href="https://a.co/4ZdXGUa">Be Mean About the Vision</a> (Shawn Lovejoy)  <a href="https://a.co/ep6HWxc">Preaching</a> (Tim Keller)  <a href="https://multiplication.org/product/launch-strong/">Launch Strong</a> (Brett Andrews & Dale Spaulding)  <a href="https://multiplication.org/product/becoming-a-level-five-multiplying-church/">Becoming a Level 5 Multiplying Church</a> (Todd Wilson)  <a href="https://www.craiggroeschel.com/books/lead-like-it-matters">Lead Like It Matters</a> (Craig Groeschel)  <a href="https://multiplication.org/product/discipleship-is-the-core-mission-of-the-church/">Discipleship is the Core Mission of the Church</a> (Bobby Harrington)  <a href="https://a.co/9ldmqit">Helping without Hurting in Church Benevolence</a> (Steve Corbett & Bryan Fikkert)  Find other great church planting books and blogs in Passion for Planting''s annotated <a href="/resources/item/7">Bibliography of Church Planting Resources</a>.', 'Talk with your coach to determine which books to add to the reading plan.  Create a schedule with deadlines and/or calendar reminders for each book.  This action is complete when you have created a schedule of the selected books.', 'template: standard  2017-10-26 content & links updated --pb  2019-11-25 book list updated --pb  2021-03-12 additional resources subsection added with Ephesiology& link& --pb  2022-11-21 added Future Church and switched Lead Like It Matters for Courageous Leadership to reading list; updated Church Planting Certificate class link --sc ', 4, 'todo', 20, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b604d13b-38fb-5501-b104-60af16c7e595', 'fb3f6ed6-495c-51c7-842e-d21e94c696e6', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this fundraising overview', 'Understand the fundamentals of fundraising so that you can begin the fundraising journey well-prepared.', 'There''s a smart way to go about raising funds, and there are ways that will waste your time, energy, and emotions. Be smart.  Attitude & Theology  Ask your coach to help you uncover any objections or hang-ups you have about fundraising. Almost no one is a natural-born fundraiser; we all have junk we have to deal with in this process. If you don''t start here, your hang-ups will undermine almost everything you do in raising funds.  Relationship & Vision  Raising funds is really more about casting vision than it is about the money. You''re not asking them for money - you''re inviting them to partner in the work that God is doing through you. Paint a picture of what this new church could accomplish. Describe what the church will look like. Imagine how the city will be different because of this new church. Invite your supporters into the vision.  And fundraising is definitely more about relationships than funding your ministry. If you don''t treat it as a one-time transaction, there will be opportunities to pastor and encourage your supporters along the way. All of your tools & tactics should drive toward relationship, not replace it.  Helpful Tools & Good Design  If you were a carpenter, you''d want to show up to work with the tools you need in your toolbox, right? You should be no less prepared when you meet with people to invite them to join in supporting the church plant.  You''re going to need things like:  appeal letters  phone scripts  fliers or brochures  a meeting outline  presentation slides  a business plan (to assure high-capacity donors)  online giving option(s)  basic financial systems  notification and thank you systems  Don''t underestimate the effect the quality of your designs will have on your donors. In our era of graphic design and &uuml;ber-marketing, your print and digital publications need to respectable. You may want to go so far as hiring a graphic designer, especially if you''re after tens of thousands of dollars in support - a few hundred dollars will be money well spent.  Regardless, don''t let your materials be sloppy. That communicates something about how you''re going to lead this ministry.  Consistency is Key  Time and again we have seen novice fundraisers with discipline and consistency raise more funds than gifted, charismatic fundraisers who don''t stick with it. Talent is common; hard work is rare. Create a sustainable system that will keep you keeping on.', 'Read the content above.  Commit to writing down a simple, effective fundraising strategy.  Commit to working your fundraising strategy even when it gets hard.  This task is complete when you have read the content of this overview.', 'template:  2020-12-14 name changed from "get 501c3 nonprofit status"; & changed Due in # Days from 142 to 150& & Duration from 30& to 14& --pb  2021-01-28 merged in content from prior child tasks "Complete the IRS& 501c3 Application" and "Submit the IRS& 501c3 Application" --pb ', 0, 'todo', 21, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('978d9fb1-76f0-533d-a7a2-de6e22b81879', 'fb3f6ed6-495c-51c7-842e-d21e94c696e6', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about fundraising', 'Open a conversation with your coach about raising funds for the church plant.', 'Ministry takes money. Every church planter raises funds in some way, shape or form. Now is your chance to pick the brain of someone who has been there & done that.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  Setting a fundraising goal  Identifying and overcoming my own hesitations  Finding new prospects  Which print pieces are really necessary  Whether to ask for specific dollar amounts  How to close a deal  How to follow up with ''maybes''  Secondary staff fundraising requirements  Building a fundraising team', 'This action is complete when you have called your coach about fundraising.', 'template: standard  2017-05-30 content updated, changed audience to coach --pb  2018-04-20 updated content, changed audience to planter --pb  2019-12-10 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Duration from 14& to 7& --pb ', 1, 'todo', 27, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('7c01a9d6-1d68-5322-ba50-d8042eed0743', 'fb3f6ed6-495c-51c7-842e-d21e94c696e6', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft a Fundraising Strategy', 'Write down a clear fundraising strategy to ensure that you truly and effectively pursue the resources that God has set aside for His work.', 'Budgeting and fundraising can be two of the most daunting things that church planters face. This doesn''t have to be the case. In simple terms, your overall goal is to determine what God is calling you to do (budgeting) and to discover how God will provide for it (fundraising).  After initial planning, most church planters discover they need more money to accomplish what they would like to do. You have three options:  raise more money  spend less money  or some combination of the two.  The fundraising strategy will address how/when you''ll raise the resources you need.', 'Download the  Fundraising Strategy Template  (<a href="/resources/item/322">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/363">Google Doc</a>).  Work the subtasks that follow to assist you in completing the template.  Send your completed Fundraising Strategy to your coach for feedback.  This action is complete when you have an actionable fundraising strategy for the new church.', 'template: standard  2017-03-31 updated from ''plan'' to ''strategy'' and updated hyperlinks --pb  2018-05-07 added& google& doc template version --pb  2018-11-02 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 45& to 36& --pb  2019-11-19 title changed from "Issue Written Fundraising Strategy" --pb ', 2, 'todo', 45, 17, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('14bea38b-9669-5e6b-b72c-b22bcf57a8ca', 'fb3f6ed6-495c-51c7-842e-d21e94c696e6', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Fundraising Strategy', 'Ensure that the fundraising strategy is both reasonable and realistic.', 'The Fundraising Strategy needs to be well thought through, both in terms of an amount as well as how the planter is going to go about raising the funds.  It needs to contain the following elements:  An overall fundraising goal  Decisions on which fundraising collateral they''ll develop  A process to follow to get to "the ask"  Thoughts of following up after the ask and maintaining ongoing communication  Details on how donors will make their contributions  Identify gaps in the planter''s strategy and help them think through pitfalls they are likely to encounter based on your experience.', 'Review the completed fundraising strategy.  Provide feedback to the planter.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Fundraising Strategy.', 'template: standard  2017-05-31 content validated --pb  2018-11-02 content updated --pb  2019-11-19 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 52& to 43& --pb ', 3, 'todo', 42, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('ed2a41c3-5ffa-53b2-b184-b4fb1524ec8d', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Decide whether to have a voting church membership', 'Establish your congregation to have either a voting or non-voting membership.', 'Some planters argue that there is no evidence of voting membership in the New Testament. Others see voting as way to contextualize the church to the American culture.  Membership means different things to different people. Some are healthy, some are not. Consider the following ''definitions'' of membership:  Social Connection  - some people view membership as a social benefit, as with country clubs  Personal Benefit  - some people view membership through the lens of what they receive in exchange for committing to be part of the organization  Community Connection  - some people view membership as a way of building a sense of community belonging  Voting Right  - the IRS sees church membership as a distinction as to whether members have voting rights or not  Commitment  - some see membership as a way of clarifying expectations and memorializing commitment  You have 3 decisions to make in this action:  Will you have voting membership?  If so, your bylaws and other legal entity formation paperwork (developed in a subsequent PlanterPlan actions) need to address the rights of members and how voting will be accomplished. Voting membership typically implies a democratic ''equal voice'' approach.  Churches that choose not to have voting membership typically give their Elders the voting rights. Essentially the Elders represent the rest of the church body. These churches often refer to their membership as ''functional'' membership or ''informal'' membership.  What is the purpose of your membership?  You need to clearly communicate the purposes of membership in order to establish and maintain a healthy culture of commitment and belonging (i.e. membership is about commitment and belonging, not benefits or rights).  How will people become members?  Will they sign a commitment/covenant? Take a class? Sign a ledger? Meet with a staff member? Etc...  What the Government Means  When the State or Feds ask, "Does your corporation have members?" they''re typically asking about who has voting rights. You may need to answer the question  No  , depending on your context, even if you have a  ecclesiastical  but non-voting membership.', 'Decide whether to have voting membership.  Clarify your vision/basis for having membership and be prepared to proactively communicate it.  Whether you settle on a voting or non-voting membership, define the process for how people become members.  This action is complete when the decision has been made about membership and if will there will be a formal membership process developed.', 'template: standard  2019-12-10 content updated --pb ', 0, 'todo', 52, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('012af6fa-5734-5c29-bd6c-a865e099c7fa', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Incorporate the Church', 'Formally organize the church''s legal entity in your state.














', 'The most common and most strategic way to legally organize a church in the US is to form a corporation. Incorporation shields individual officers and directors from personal liability and sets the church up to become an official nonprofit organization.

Articles of Incorporation (also called Articles of Organization or Charter) are the first step in becoming a legally recognized 501c3 nonprofit organization. Articles of Incorporation provide your state with the basic information about the new church (e.g. name, directors, location, organizational purpose, type of organization, membership structure, etc.).

Where to File

In most cases, the paperwork is filed with your Secretary of State (list of all 50 states & DC).

Most states have websites that provide step-by-step instructions for preparing and submitting nonprofit Articles of Incorporation. Often they include a template the church may use. Most states now allow you to file online through their website, but for some states you''ll mail or walk them in.

What to File

You''ll file a simple form, typically 3 pages or less, that covers the basics of your new corporation. You''ll get back an approved Certificate of Incorporation and/or copy of the original paperwork stamped with an approval.

Corporate Citizenship

This sets into motion several ongoing responsibilities. Every nonprofit corporation must:

adopt Bylaws or a Constitution
have an active Board of Directors
maintain legal and financial records
in most states, file an Annual Report to keep the corporation in good standing
If you fail to maintain these things on an ongoing basis, a court may decide that your corporation doesn''t really exist and the the employees, directors and officers are personally liable for the actions of the church.

The Registered Agent

Most states require the name and address of an individual in that state who will serve as the Registered Agent (aka Statutory Agent, Agent for Service of Process). This is the state''s point of contact if legal papers have to be served (e.g. summons, subpoena).

The Registered Agent is not held liable for anything the church does or does not do; the agent is just a messenger. If the planter has not already moved on site, he''ll have to find someone in the destination state to volunteer. If he doesn''t know anyone that already lives in the target state, he should network with his affiliation of churches to find someone willing to be his Registered Agent.

If you are working with a Passion for Planting Project Manager, you will be getting significant custom support on this task. If not, follow the instructions in the subtasks to guide you.', 'Decide whether to prepare the Articles yourself or to pay a professional.
Prepare the Articles of Incorporation based on state and church planting network guidelines.
Review the Articles of Incorporation (with a lawyer if necessary) to ensure they meet the needs of the church.
Approve the Articles of Incorporation (typically signed by an officer of the organization).
Submit the Articles to your state for approval. Note that a small fee often applies. Ask for several certified copies of the approval certificate that the state will return to you. This may cost a few extra dollars but it''s always easier and sometimes cheaper to get extra copies up front than to have to go back and request one later.
This action is complete when you have received approved/certified copies of the Articles from the applicable state agency.', 'template: standard  2017-05-24 content updated --pb  2018-05-04 added link to 50 states'' SOS& --pb  2019-12-10 content updated --pb  2021-01-18 outdented from child to parent task --pb  2022-09-16 removed recommendation hyperlink to& StartChurch& --pb ', 1, 'todo', 59, 21, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('aa760d57-c8b3-5a5f-8b95-425b724a7c9c', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get a Federal EIN for the church', 'A Federal Employer Identification Number (also known as an EIN) is required for any legal entity.', 'An EIN is kind of like a social security number for an organization. An EIN is required to pursue 501c3 status. It is also useful for other legal and organizational issues (e.g. opening a checking account, etc.).  We recommend you reserve the church''s legal name prior to obtaining your EIN. If you don''t and you run into any issues finalizing that name at the state level, you''ll have to file Federal name change paperwork later.  Good luck with that.  The best way to reserve your name is by filing Articles of Incorporation with the state. Some states allow you to reserve your name prior to the actual filing by completing another simpler form. Either way, you should check with the state to:  find out what requirements they may have (does the name need to include "inc.")  search to see if the name is available and  either file the Articles of Incorporation or Name Reservation  before  you get the EIN.  Step-by-Step Instructions  The following recommendations do not necessarily apply to you and your situation. These are, however, the standard answers we provide the IRS for most of the churches Passion for Planting directly supports. Your answers may differ based on your circumstances. If you have any doubt, consult a lawyer familiar with applicable state and federal laws.  Click  Apply Online Now  toward the bottom of the page.  Click  Begin Application  .  Select  View Additional Types  and then click  Continue  .  Select  Church  (as opposed to other flavors of corporation) and the click  Continue  .  Click  Continue  on the  Please Confirm Your Selection  page.  Select  Started a New Business  and click  Continue  .  Select  Individual  as the Principal Officer and click  Continue  .  Input the requested information about the Principal officer (you, the planter), select  I am the President/CEO...  and click  Continue  .  Input the address of the corporation as requested (No PO Boxes allowed) and click  Continue  .  Input the requested information about the Corporation. It will be best to select  December  as the end of business year. Click  Continue  .  Answer the first 4 questions (your answer will probably be  No  ) and for the 5th question, answer:  Yes  for the last question if the church will be paying anyone by W-2 (most employees) or  No  if there are no paid employees to start with, or only clergy on staff that have all opted out of Social Security. You may also select  No  for the 5th question if another church or ministry is paying your employees'' payroll directly (a form of co-employment).  Confirm on the next page that all the data has been input correctly with no typographical errors. Click  Apply  .  It is imperative that you print and store the resultant form in a safe place. We recommend inserting it in your corporate records book  and  a secondary safe place. We also recommend keeping an electronic copy backed up in the cloud.', 'Visit the IRS website to <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/small-businesses-self-employed/apply-for-an-employer-identification-number-ein-online">apply online</a> for the federal Employer Identification Number (EIN).  Follow their interview-style application process.  Receive the EIN assignment letter as a PDF document at the end of the application.  Print and archive a copy of the letter in your corporate records book (see subsequent PlanterPlan action).  Save the PDF file to your computer and to a backup location.  This action is complete when you have obtained the federal Employer Identification Number (EIN).', 'template: standard  2019-12-10 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 52& to 67 --pb&  ', 2, 'todo', 66, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('9161348c-944c-5720-afed-7565b9803553', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Draft church bylaws', 'Adopt bylaws to provide structure and rules for operation for the new church.', 'Bylaws define the rules of operation for corporations. Some organizations refer to Bylaws as a Constitution. Bylaws are maintained by the church (prepared, approved, modified, etc.) and do not typically require any outside or government approval.  Corporations must adopt some version of Bylaws. Though you don''t need them approved by the government, you need to prove that you do have them when you apply for 501c3 tax-exempt nonprofit status. You''ll also need to prove that you have them when you apply for postal permits.  One key issue in Bylaws is whether or not the church will have official membership (per the IRS definition of membership) and whether all members have equal voting rights or whether the Elders make official decisions on behalf of the membership. Reference previous PlanterPlan task  Decide whether to have a voting church membership .', 'Review the <a href="/resources/item/30">Church Bylaws Template</a>.  Check online for additional sample bylaws. If necessary, find help online or check a book out of the library.  Customize the Bylaws as necessary for the new church.  Determine who will sign the Bylaws as legal agents and obtain their signatures. Minimally, have the Corporate Secretary sign.  This action completes when the Management Team (or other appropriate oversight) approves the final Bylaws.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content validated --pb  2019-12-11 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 203& to 67 --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 59, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('026202ca-9e38-57c6-af2f-895ce56592fd', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Conduct initial board meeting', 'Begin behaving like a corporation by holding the first official board meeting.', 'The first task of the new corporation is to hold the first board meeting. You can do that either just before or just after filing the incorporation paperwork. Passion for Planting recommends holding the meeting before incorporation so that you can ratify all of the initial legal docs up front, including the not-yet-filed Articles of Incorporation.  Minimally, you''ll want to cover the following at that meeting:  Appointing Directors  Approving the Articles of Incorporation (even retroactively)  Adopting Bylaws  Appointing or electing corporate officers  The minutes from this meeting must be signed by the secretary and filed promptly in the Corporate Records Notebook.  Why Meeting Minutes are Important  Most states practice a hands-off approach to churches: they don''t want to mess with routine or random examination of a church''s corporate records. However, if there is an examination, for a lawsuit for instance, you''d better have everything documented. The best way to be ready is to meet regularly as a board and keep good notes (meeting minutes).  If the church doesn''t have recorded meeting minutes or other proof of corporate activity, the judge may say, "What corporation?" If that happens, the board & staff may be held personally liable. As in,  your  car, house, retirement account, etc.', 'Notify your appointed Directors of the meeting or have them sign a  Waiver of Notice of Directors'' Meeting .  Make sure someone is taking minutes and recording action items.  Cover the items listed above and any other business that needs to be taken care of.  Conclude the meeting and file the signed minutes in the Corporate Records Notebook.  This action is complete when you have filed the minutes from the first Board Meeting in the Corporate Records Notebook.', 'template: standard  2017-05-25 content and resource link updated --pb  2018-02-09 additional resource link added --pb  2019-12-10 content updated --pb  2022-09-16 removed recommendation hyperlink to StartChurch --pb  2022-11-21 updated links --sc  &  ', 4, 'todo', 59, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('e3f75a6f-d94f-5038-a197-97b75087d455', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Build a corporate records notebook', 'Simplify finding and updating your important corporate documents by creating a notebook or binder where all of they are held.', 'You''ll create many different documents in the course of getting the new church started. Some of the originals will be difficult to reproduce, if not impossible. Keeping them in one safe place all together will keep them from being lost, misplaced, or coffee-stained. This will keep you from wasting time looking for them when you need them.  The Corporate Records Notebook should include:  Articles of Incorporation  Bylaws  Written Doctrines  Federal EIN Letter  Official policies of the board  Federal 501c3 Determination Letter  Board Meeting Minutes  State Exemption Letter  Employer withholding account documents (if applicable)  USPS nonprofit pricing classification  Other government correspondence  Member''s Register (if church is having membership)  Insurance Policy  Contracts  Keep the Book in a safe place where it is unlikely to be destroyed by fire or water. It is also a good idea to scan each document and keep an electronic copy in the cloud.', 'Purchase a 3-ring binder or folio-style book.  Scan each document and keep an electronic copy in the cloud.  Insert all of the original documents listed above along with any other document that should be archived for safekeeping.  Keep the book in a safe place.  This action is complete when a Corporate Records Notebook has been filled with all of the corporation''s founding documents.', 'template: standard  2017-05-26 content validated --pb&  2020-01-21 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 210& to 128& --pb  ', 5, 'todo', 66, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('62dae2d2-1e2a-52d2-9403-33da716c6aeb', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Apply for 501c3 nonprofit status', 'Complete and file the IRS 501c3 application so you can get discounts, donations, and stop paying sales tax (depending on your state).', 'The IRS grants churches an automatic 501c3 tax exemption. Basically, if you''re organized as a church and behaving as a church, you''re already a 501c3 nonprofit.  But the IRS are the only ones that seem to know about that rule. Even the US Post Office doesn''t honor the IRS'' automatic exemption. Many states won''t grant you a sales tax exemption unless and until you have a 501c3 determination letter from the IRS with your church''s name on it.  And increasingly, US corporations that offer grants and free or discounted products and services to nonprofits first check the IRS online database of approved 501c3''s. If you''re using the IRS'' automatic exemption, they won''t list you in that database. Therefore, some donors won''t give you the time of day.  So we generally advise US churches to formally apply for 501c3 exemption. It costs $600 to apply and takes quite a bit of work to complete, but it cuts through all of the confusion and opens doors of opportunity for your church. You''ll get a letter with your church''s name on it, and they''ll publish you in their online database.  The following subtasks will walk you step-by-step through completing, compiling and submitting the IRS application for 501c3 tax exemption.  Compiling What You Need  The IRS 1023 application for 501c3 tax-exempt status is a lengthy application that includes simple check box questions as well as long-answer essay questions. Putting together all of the requested information and composing all of the answers is well worth the effort, but will take some time.  You will want to have the following information available as you sit down to fill out the 1023 form:  The church''s EIN (see previous PlanterPlan action)  Full names and addresses of the officers/directors  3 years'' worth of budget figures, especially offerings, salary and rent. These can be proposed figures if you haven''t closed out your first fiscal year as a church.  Approximate bank account balance and the value of actual tangible church property (laptop, trailer, sound system, etc.) at time of application  As of January 31, 2020, the IRS put form 1023 Application for Recognition of Exemption online. You will create an online account according to the Actions steps below.  They will required supporting documentation, but only allow you to upload one singe file. Create a single PDF file of all attachments; be sure the church name & EIN are on every page:  Articles of Incorporation (along with any amendments in chronological order)  Bylaws with any amendments  Church Doctrines (if you''ve established a formal/written set of doctrinal statements)  Any facility lease or rental agreement the church has signed  Your r&eacute;sum&eacute; (optional, but recommended to support qualifications)', '<a href="https://www.pay.gov/public/registration">Create a company account</a> on www.pay.gov.  Use the search box to search on "1023" and begin the application.  Upload your single PDF file of all attachments (per above).  In the www.pay.gov 1023 application, use the  PDF Preview  button to download a completed but unsigned copy of your application and review it for accuracy.  Double check that you have spelled the name of the church correctly on the first page of the form, and that it matches  exactly  the legal name on the Articles of Incorporation.  Make sure that you have included all of the required supporting documentation in the single PDF attachment, and that the church''s name and EIN are included on  every page  (in case they get separated).  Make sure that the church planter''s name is spelled correctly in each instance.  Make any corrections to the online application.  Officially submit the application and pay the $600 application fee.  This action is complete when you have submitted the online 1023 Application for Tax Exempt Status.', 'template:  2020-12-16 changed Duration from 161 to 152& --pb&  ', 6, 'todo', 149, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('16e2e111-1934-5425-adb2-9491963cebe2', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'File for nonprofit pricing classification with the US Post Office', 'File necessary paperwork to qualify for nonprofit postage rates.', 'You can save a ton of money when doing a big mailing if you''re officially recognized by the Post Office as a nonprofit.  Some churches will get their own bulk mail permit. However, if you work with a direct mail vendor that specializes in helping churches, you can piggyback on their permit  and you don''t need to pay for your own bulk mail permit !  Here are some companies that have served our planters in the past:  <a href="https://outreach.com">Outreach Marketing</a>  <a href="https://www.d2design.com/">D2Design</a>  <a href="https://mailworksii.com/">MailWorks II</a>  For the Post Office discount, there is no application fee or annual fee, but this form often takes 2-4 weeks to be approved. Complete it and submit to the post office at least a month before your first mailing.  Applying for the nonprofit discount is tricky, though, because new churches are in a catch 22: you want save money announcing your Grand Opening, but the Post Office says you''re not a church until you''ve had your Grand Opening. They will demand a copy of your 501c3 Determination Letter, but most churches won''t get that back from the IRS in time. The vendors above will help you navigate this.  If you are working with a Passion for Planting Project Manager, you will be getting significant custom support on this task. If not, follow the instructions below.', 'Offline Application  Figure out which is your local "main" Post Office branch. We use their <a href="https://tools.usps.com/find-location.htm">location finder</a> and search for the branch that has US Passport services. You''ll name this location in the application and go there to submit the application.  Download the <a href="https://about.usps.com/forms/ps3624.pdf">Form PS 3624 - Application to Mail at Nonprofit Standard Mail Rates</a>.  Complete all questions in Part 1.  Compile and attach as many items from page 3 as possible.  Sign the application.  Carry the entire application packet in. Go around the back of the building to the Bulk Mail (business mail) counter, usually by the loading docks.  Wait to hear back from USPS headquarters.  Online Application  Figure out which is your local "main" Post Office branch. We use their <a href="https://tools.usps.com/find-location.htm">location finder</a> and search for the branch that has US Passport services. You''ll name this location in the application.  <a href="https://reg.usps.com/entreg/RegistrationBusinessAction_input">Create a USPS online account</a>.  Log in the <a href="https://gateway.usps.com/eAdmin/view/signin">USPS Business Gateway</a>.  Select  Postal Wizard > ps3624 .  Complete the application and upload as many of the supporting documents from the list as possible.  Wait to hear back from USPS headquarters.  This action is complete when you receive the approved NPA number from the US Post Office by either means.', 'template: standard  2017-05-25 contents validated --pb  2018-11-12 additional resources subsection added --pb  2019-08-21 new additional resource added --pb  2019-12-11 content updated --pb ', 7, 'todo', 166, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('eca6cea8-606f-50d4-9ba4-27ef2f68b679', 'fce96968-0be0-523b-93df-31999293e240', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Get your state sales tax exemption', 'File necessary paperwork to obtain sales tax exemption recognition from your state.', 'You can save thousands of dollars by not paying sales tax on purchases the church makes. It is clearly in the interest of the church not to pay unnecessary taxes.  State sales tax is paid to the state each time your church purchases something (typically 4-8% on top of the purchase price). Obtaining state sales tax exemption saves considerable money throughout the life of a church and can save hundreds (and in some cases thousands) of dollars during the pre-launch phase.  There are several categories that states fall in to (double check your state''s requirements):  there is no sales tax (AK, DE, MT, NH, OR)  churches can submit sales receipts for reimbursement of the sales tax (including NC)  churches can declare themselves nonprofit on an honor system and download an exemption form to use (including MI)  churches can apply for nonprofit sales tax exemption on their purchases (most states)  they do not grant any nonprofit a sales tax exemption (including CA, LA) - tough luck!  In many states that have an application process, you will not be able to apply until after receiving your 501c3 Determination Letter from the federal government.  Contact your state''s Department of Revenue to find out what kind of exemption, if any, is available. Try searching on  [name of state] sales tax exemption .  If you are working with a Passion for Planting Project Manager, you will be getting significant custom support on this task. If not, follow the instructions below.', 'Obtain an application form for sales tax exemption.  Complete the application form.  Sign and submit the application form along with required supporting documentation.  This action is complete when you have the state sales tax exemption certificate in hand.', 'template: standard  2017-05-25 content updated --pb  2019-12-12 content updated --pb  2020-12-14 changed Due in # Days from 59& to 67& & Duration from 7 to 14& --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 166, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('395440f5-0649-59f1-acdb-4712aace9915', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Read this "Vision Frame" overview', 'Understand the Vision Frame and commit to crafting one that is unique for the new church.', 'You have a way of doing ministry whether you''ve ever thought about it or not. The process of crafting a Vision Frame will force you to be intentional about how the new church is going to do ministry. And it will help you wordsmith powerful language that will help create the culture of the new church.  This milestone is based on Will Mancini''s seminal work,  <a href="https://a.co/9iJdt6c">Church Unique</a> . You need to buy a copy right now and begin working through it. The tasks in PlanterPlan will work in conjunction with the book to help you produce the various pieces of the Vision Frame.  This is a critical processes you can''t skip over, photocopy or microwave. Your Vision Frame will:  become the filter or decision matrix for everything you do going forward  become your protection against any who come with competing or toxic agendas  get everybody shooting at the same target  provide common language to create culture and stay on mission  What are the key parts of the Church Unique process?  Discover your Kingdom Concept  Define your Vision Frame:  Mission  Values  Strategy  Measures  Articulate the Vision Proper', 'Watch the Will Mancini video <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MbU7TonadH4">Organizational Alignment</a>.  Download and read the <a href="/resources/item/346">Vision Frame Summary</a> provided by Auxano.  This action is complete when you have watched the video and read all of the above.', 'template: standard  Not sure what the 1st Action "training videos" is& supposed to be linked to.&  It implies a series of videos.&  I''m thinking it should be just a link to the "Philosophy of Ministry" video by Ed Stezter.&  -----ds  2017-06-01 updated content and resource link --pb  2017-11-27 content updated to align with & Church Unique --pb  2019-01-11 Due in # Days corrected from 7 to& 31 --pb  2019-11-26 content validated --pb  2020-01-13 replaced broken& gdurl& link to image --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 31& to 15 & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb ', 0, 'todo', 14, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('6e850853-da35-538c-9216-ae1a24d035e0', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about crafting a Vision Frame', 'Open a conversation with your coach about crafting your "Vision Frame" (a methodology of preparing philosophy of ministry language based on Will Mancini''s  <a href="https://a.co/9iJdt6c">Church Unique</a> ).', 'You have to start thinking early in the planting process about how you''re going to approach ministry and what the DNA-setting language of the new church will be.  Sample issues to process with your coach:  The difference between vision and mission  How to communicate your Vision Frame visually  Your Vision Frame through the eyes of not-yet-believers  Where planting more churches fits into your Vision Frame', 'This action is complete when you have called coach about the Vision Frame process.', 'template: standard  2017-05-30 content updated, audience changed to coach --pb  2017-11-27 content updated to align with Church Unique --pb  2018-02-15 tweaked language based on feedback from Will Heath @ Auxano --pb  2018-04-20 updated content, changed audience to planter --pb  2019-01-11 Due in # Days corrected from 7 to& 31 --pb  2019-11-26 content validated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 31& to 15 & Duration from 7 to 1 --pb ', 1, 'todo', 14, 1, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('c4ef5422-2d3a-5ad8-b77e-2a8b86d79380', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Describe how your church will be unique', 'Write a clear, 1-sentence explanation of what makes your church unique.', 'Before God called you to plant this church, He had something in mind. He wanted to create a new congregation as unique as people are one to another. A congregation that would carry out His purposes and expand His Kingdom.  Where do you begin discovering God''s heart for this new church?  Begin with prayer. Lots of prayer.  Next, find early clues when you consider the overlap between your wiring and your community''s situation.  "The place God calls you to is the place where your deep gladness and the world''s deep hunger meet." - Frederick Buechner  What are the common threads between who God has created you to be and what your target community has become?  Where is the intersection between what inspires & animates you and your community''s specific flavor of brokenness?', 'Read  Church Unique  chapters <a href="https://www.willmancini.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Ch9_Kingdom_Concept.pdf">9</a> & 10.  Download and answer the <a href="/resources/item/347">Apostolic Esprit questions</a> provided by Auxano.  Download and answer the <a href="/resources/item/348">Local Predicament questions</a> provided by Auxano.  Regarding Collective Potential  if you already have even a small team, download and answer the <a href="/resources/item/356">Collective Potential questions</a> provided by Auxano  if it''s just you and your spouse at this point, the "Collective Potential" may be aspirational; set a reminder to revisit this when you have at least 15-20 people on your team  in BOTH cases, set a calendar reminder to revisit the Collective Potential exercise just after the first anniversary of your Launch - your team will have grown and changed  Craft your unique Kingdom Concept statement.  This action is complete after you''ve written a sentence that clearly describes how God is calling you uniquely to make disciples.  "', 'template: standard  2017-06-01 content and resource links updated --pb  2017-11-27 content updated to align with Church Unique --pb  2018-02-15 added venn& diagram images --pb  2020-01-13 replaced broken& gdurl& link to image --pb  2019-11-26 content validated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 56 to 36 & Duration from 7 to 14 --pb&  2022-11-21 updated links --sc ', 2, 'todo', 35, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('76a8a37d-d3ce-5172-9cdb-e66def15b22e', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Keep vision viral', 'Determine to do the hard work of word-smithing the various elements of the Vision Frame.', 'Simple clarity can be really hard work. Our temptation is to use more words so that people get a better idea of what we mean. But if the components of the Vision Frame are too long & complicated, people aren''t going to remember them. Or worse, they''ll offer up a version that sounds like it was put through <a href="https://www.wikihow.com/Play-the-Telephone-Game">the Telephone Game</a> first.  You will be crafting important culture-shaping language in the coming tasks and subtasks. Here are Mancini''s 5C''s that you will use to test and refine each element:  Clear  is measured by the Junior High Rule: Is our language clear enough that a 12-year old boy who has not been to church would understand it?  Concise  is measured by the One Breath Rule: Can any part of the purpose be stated in one breath?  Compelling  is measured by the Resonance Rule: When the purpose is stated, does this make people want to say it again?  Catalytic  is measured by the Actionability Rule: Does your language inherently remind the listener to act rather than define success as what the ministerial staff does?  Contextual  is measured by the Bouquet Rule: Do the words communicate biblical truth for the listener''s time and place, thus going to the garden of the Word and arranging the perfect bouquet for our people? For further clarification, refer back to  Church Unique  p.116  "If these five attributes are fused within the Vision Frame, amazing energy is released. People understand the vision because you have broken it down into meaningful bite-sized chunks. Credibility is enhanced by virtue of the fact that it is comprehensive without being overwhelming. Ownership is increased because it is portable; people can remember it, use it, and share it. It all funnels into an important reality: the vision is contagious.  Church Unique, page 116', 'This action is complete when you understand the 5C''s and commit to use them to evaluate how you articulate each side of the vision frame.', 'template:  2018-08-28 new task --pb  2012-12-02 content updated --pb  2020-12-16 changed Due in # Days from 141& to 135& & Duration from 7 to 1& --pb&  ', 3, 'todo', 35, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('6799a515-efe8-5a86-9f5e-0f0b7496b756', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Craft your Vision Frame', 'Compile a  Vision Frame  document that will get everyone shooting at the same target and using the same language.', 'The  Vision Frame  document will simply be a compilation of what you''ll produce in the following sub-tasks. Having them all together in one document will be useful in a variety of ways and will help transmit the DNA of the new church to others.  The  Vision Frame  will include the church''s:  Mission  Values  Strategies  Measures  Descriptive Vision (Vision Proper)', 'Download Passion for Planting''s  Vision Frame Template  (<a href="/resources/item/354">MS Word</a> or <a href="/resources/item/378">Google Doc</a>).  Copy and paste the various pieces of your  Vision Frame  into the template.  Send the document to your coach for review.  Incorporate the coach''s feedback and finalize the Vision Frame.  This action is complete after you have a final draft of the  Vision Frame  ready for distribution.', 'template: standard  2017-06-01 content and resources links updated --pb  2017-11-27 content updated to align with Church Unique --pb  2018-06-01& gdoc& template added --pb  2019-11-26 content validated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Duration from 21& to 28& --pb &  ', 4, 'todo', 52, 28, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('6210712c-affb-5419-9afd-e8551166384d', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm Vision Frame', 'Ensure that the planter has crafted a Vision Frame that can be virally transmitted.', 'Review the planter''s Vision Frame (philosophy of ministry). Either encourage the Planter to rework the insufficient section(s) or affirm that it is a workable and appropriate Vision Frame.  used by permission', 'Have the planter pitch his Vision Frame to you.  Provide feedback to the planter - from the various sides of the Vision Frame, you should be able to triangulate common language and themes; the sides should complement each other.  This action is complete when you, the coach, have reviewed and affirmed the planter''s Vision Frame.', 'template: standard  2017-06-02 content updated, audience changed to coach --pb  2017-11-27 content updated to align with Church Unique --pb  2018-02-15 tweaked language based on feedback from Will Heath @& Auxano& --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb  2020-01-13 replaced broken& gdurl& link to image --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 52& to 60 --pb&  ', 5, 'todo', 59, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('f8929b4d-530c-5800-86d5-b404de4699de', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Develop church beliefs', 'Craft a written beliefs statement for the new church.', 'Your Biblical beliefs will play a significant role in shaping the character of your church. Like the guardrails along a road that keep a car from completely veering off the road, beliefs help keep a church focused and on the right track. The guardrails do not guarantee that a car is always staying on the pavement, but they do keep it from dangerously veering off course.  You will be asked frequently (especially early in the new church) what your church believes. These questions don''t come just from churched people. In studies of unchurched visitors to church, a desire to hear Biblical teaching and learn what the Bible has to say is cited as one of the top reasons people visit.  While all Scripture is God-breathed and inspired by God, it is amazing how much disagreement we can have on what the Bible says. In matters essential to salvation, you must be firm in your approach and teaching. You need to be very clear on what you believe and what you will not compromise. You need to give thought to what you consider the essentials (those things where you will not compromise) to be.  In other issues, be cautious to maintain unity and to avoid becoming distracted with issues that keep you from your primary purpose. If necessary, agree to disagree and focus your efforts to primary issues of theology.  Our beliefs are those primary issues of theology that define what we believe about God, Jesus, the Holy Spirit, man, sin, the Bible, the role of the Church, and salvation. Our beliefs help answer the questions: "Why do we do what we do?" and "What do we do?" We will die for what we believe.  Craft the words in a manner that are understandable to people with little or no church background. Use wording that draws people in and causes them to ask more questions. Avoid wording that puts people on the defensive and causes barriers.', 'For further instruction and multiple examples, read <a href="/resources/item/12">How to Develop a Beliefs Statement</a>.  Make a list of key topics such as God, Jesus, the Holy Spirit, man, sin, the Bible, the role of the Church, and salvation.  Look to Scripture to speak for you on what you believe in these areas.  Write a brief beliefs statement about each. Attempt to tie the topics together into a common theme (like God''s plan for redemption of man).  Look at how other churches have written their beliefs statements. Search online key words such as  church beliefs  or  Christian Church beliefs .  Get feedback and input from others (particularly the unchurched).  Finalize the written beliefs statements.  This action is complete when you have written out a comprehensive set of belief statements.', 'template: standard  2017-06-01 content and resource link updated --pb  2017-11-27 changed parent to "268" (the milestone) and task type to "task" (was a child).  2019-11-26 content updated --pb ', 6, 'todo', 45, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('b13152f8-3888-5d0f-9c45-5d99424256b7', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Learn to listen for attunement', 'Adopt a framework that will help you understand where each of your team members is at and how to lead them.', 'In Church Unique, Mancini uses the metaphor of a cruise ship to illustrate your team. There are those that get the vision and those that don''t. And among them there are those that contribute and those that don''t. When you put those factors together, you get the Attunement Grid:  used by permission  Crew  - these are the lifeblood of your church: they are sold out to the vision and willingly contribute to the church and its mission  Passengers  - these people buy in to the vision, but either don''t know how to contribute or can''t; a little leadership will move many of them into your Crew  Stowaways  - they haven''t yet caught the vision and they don''t contribute  Pirates  - these can be the most dangerous because they can be easily mistaken for Crew: they show up, work hard, and even lead teams. But they have their own vision for the church which is not the vision God has entrusted you with.  You will discover where your team members are through dialogue. There will be telltale signs and signature phrases they use that will clue you in. This isn''t so you can pigeonhole people, but know how to lead them.  Especially think through:  the kinds of things you''ll say to Passengers to get them excited about contributing or perhaps connected to the right serving opportunity  how you''ll give a ''positive no'' to Pirates to keep their agenda from hijacking the vision of the church', 'Read  Church Unique  chapter 19.  Brainstorm the signature phrases of each group: the kinds of things they''ll say that reveal where they''re at.  Think through your basic approach to leading each of the groups toward greater clarity & contribution.  Set a calendar reminder to revisit this every 6 months - this needs to be an ongoing diagnostic and not a one-time exercise.  This action is complete when you have a strategy for recognizing and leading each of the four types of team members.', 'template: standard  2017-06-02 content and resource links updated; the ''case study'' was moved to become its own download (it was too lengthy); the other 3 resource links were updated but NOT the resources themselves --pb  2017-11-27 content overwritten (was Org Structure, now Attunement); changed parent to #268 (the milestone) and task type to "task" (was a child); content inserted to align with Church Unique --pb  2018-02-15 tweaked language based on feedback from Will Heath @& Auxano& --pb  2018-06-26 additional resources subsection added --pb  2019-11-26 content validated --pb  2020-01-13 replaced broken& gdurl& link to image --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 52& to 61 --pb&  2022-11-21 updated link --sc ', 7, 'todo', 60, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('0b5c69dd-acc0-576d-a687-e7505f06752c', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Call your coach about naming the church', 'Open a conversation with your coach about naming the new church.', 'While a good name won''t guarantee you a healthy church, a poorly selected name could become an obstacle for people. Call your coach and work through your preliminary list of potential names with two filters in mind:  Will this name connect with the target audience in the community?  Does the church name appropriately reflect the values of the church?  Sample issues to process with your coach:  What a name communicates to people who are far from God  Letting your demographics research inform what the name should be  How to test a potential name in the community', 'This action is complete when your have called your coach about naming the church.', 'template: standard  2017-05-30 content update, audience changed to coach --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 45& to 31 --pb&  ', 8, 'todo', 30, 7, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('948e2690-930c-5209-850f-bcadbfa773c8', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Select church name', 'Pick a legal name for the church that is both contextual and communicates the church''s identity.', 'The church name you choose can play a significant role in the people''s first impression of the church. Every name communicates  something :  Fresh or stodgy  Formal or informal  Alive or dead  Churchy or edgy  Old-school or hipster  Artsy or plain  But don''t start picking a name until you''ve done three important things:  Exegeted your community enough to create a  Target Area Report  Drafted your  Vision Frame  Prayed about it  You have to be  really know  your community before choosing a name. The nuances of local nicknames, geography, attitudes, etc. cannot be appreciated from across the country. If you haven''t done the missionary homework of studying your community, chances are really high that you''ll pick a name that you''ll end up changing to something else.  The name of the church should flow directly out of its identity, delineated in the  Vision Frame  you just completed. The church''s name encapsulates all of it. If you haven''t finished the  Vision Frame , chances are also high you''ll pick a name that you''ll end up changing.  And even when you think you have a winner, don''t finalize the name until you''ve done four important things:  Make sure the name is available in your state (google "[name of state] business name search")  Make sure there''s not a similarly-named church nearby ( Discover Church  is pretty close to  Discovery Church )  Run it past your coach  Conducted a coffee shop straw poll  The Tension of Timing  Unfortunately, picking a name is sometimes forced on you before all of that is done. The usual culprits are financial systems like bank account, payroll and/or online giving. Without a legal name for the church entity, those things are roadblocked.  If you find yourself rushing to pick a name, you have a couple of options:  See if a sponsoring church planting network or church congregation will handle your initial financial systems  Rush to see how much of the contextualization and visioning process you can get done in a day or two before picking a name  Pick a placeholder name, like "The Cheboygan Church Plant"; this is least desirable because it costs you time & expense to change the name later and banks are becoming increasingly inflexible on this', 'Complete at least a rough draft of your  Target Area Report  and  Vision Frame  (covered by preceding PlanterPlan tasks) before beginning.  Search online to determine what church names are being used in your target area. Make a list of all other churches and think about what each name communicates about that church.  Brainstorm possible names (see  Additional Resources  below).  Ask Jesus what He thinks.  Determine name availability/distinguishably through your <a href="https://www.llcuniversity.com/50-secretary-of-state-sos-business-entity-search/">Secretary of State''s office or Corporation Commission</a>.  Run the name past your coach, and if expected, your oversight or Management Team.  Get feedback from people in the target area, especially non-Christians.  Finalize the name.  This action is complete when you have finalized the church name.', 'template: standard  2017-06-02 content updated --pb  2018-05-04 added link to 50 states''& SOS& --pb  2018-05-15 added Additional Resources subsection & links --pb  2019-11-26 significant content updated --pb  2020-12-11 changed Due in # Days from 52& to 45 --pb&  2022-09-16 removed dead Babylon Bee hyperlink --pb ', 9, 'todo', 44, 14, '{}'::jsonb),
  ('ecd2eba7-cf45-5d8f-835c-ff3233dd5d4b', 'fe8353d6-0b13-593c-bdba-2abf5975a65b', (SELECT id FROM auth.users WHERE email = 'timothy.cheung58@gmail.com'), 'template', 'Coaching Checkpoint: review and affirm church name', 'Affirm that the name the planter wants to us is contextually appropriate and reflects the values of the church.', 'Use two filters when reviewing the name of the church:  Will this name connect with the target audience in the community?  Does the church name appropriately reflect the values of the church?  If the name fails to meet either of these criteria, provide feedback to the planter and help the planter discover why the name is not a good fit. Some church planting networks will require the use of a denominational name. Have the planter confirm whether this is the case before making a final decision.', 'The planter communicates the name of the new church to the coach.  The coach affirms that the name is contextually appropriate and reflects the values of the church.  This action is complete when the coach has affirmed that the name of the church is contextually appropriate and reflects the values of the church.', 'template: standard  2017-06-02 content validated --pb  2019-11-26 content updated --pb ', 10, 'todo', 52, 7, '{}'::jsonb);

